<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Jailbreaks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Over 100 inmates staged prison breaks in Thailand during 1998
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ More than 100 inmates escaped
Thailand's overcrowded prisons in 1998, a record year for
jailbreaks, the Department of Corrections said Wednesday.
	   Only 10 of the 102 prisoners who escaped, however, remain at
large, department statistics showed. The rest have been captured.
	   Interior Ministry officials said earlier this year that
Thailand's prison population was surging as more people turned to
crime because of the country's economic crisis.
	   At the same time, the crisis has forced budgets for government
agencies, including the Department of Corrections, to be slashed.
	   Thailand is in the midst of its worst economic downturn in
modern times and is receiving a dlrs 17.2 billion bailout from the
International Monetary Fund.
	   Four of the prisoners still at large escaped during the past
week.
	   Two convicted killers who escaped from the maximum security Bang
Kwan prison on the outskirts of Bangkok on Tuesday were still on
the run, as were two prisoners who escaped from a northeastern jail
over the weekend. 	   
</TEXT>
