<SLUG> BC-Guatemala-Peace Anniversary,0240 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Guatemala unveils monument to mark second anniversary of peace
</HEADLINE>
accord &QL; 
 &UR; RECAPS pvs.
 &UR; By ALFONSO ANZUETO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) _ President Alvaro Arzu has appealed for
reconciliation and asked Guatemalans to forgive the state for the
hardships and thousands of deaths they suffered in almost four
decades of civil war.
	   ``In the name of the state, I ask forgiveness for the historic
responsibility it has for the pain and death suffered by dozens of
thousands of Guatemalans en 36 years of armed conflict,'' Arzu said
Tuesday.
	   ``I ask all Guatemalans to forgive one another, and families
still estranged do so with one another, and together join the
pilgrimage towards the goal of national reconciliation,'' he added.
	   Arzu spoke at a ceremony in Santa Cruz, the capital of
northwestern Quiche province, marking the second anniversary of the
signing of a U.N. brokered peace pact Dec. 29, 1996, that ended 36
years of civil war.
	   More than 170,000 people were killed in fighting between leftist
guerrillas seeking power and social change against a succession of
rightist military-dominated governments. Another 30,000 have been
missing.
	   Arzu spoke to a crowd in the town's municipal stadium, and his
words were broadcast nationwide. Quiche province, about 50 miles
(75 kms) from Guatemala City was one of the regions hardest hit by
the conflict.
</TEXT>
