<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Budget, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mexican president urges legislators to approve new budget
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ISAAC A. LEVI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ With time running out, President Ernesto
Zedillo is urging the Congress to stop squabbling and redouble
efforts to pass the 1999 budget package before the end of this
year.
	   ``As president, I am confident that a sense of responsibility
among legislators will prevail,'' Zedillo told a meeting Tuesday of
his ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, which lost its
majority in the House of Deputies in mid-term elections last year.
	   Zedillo indicated his administration is in a bind.
	   While the 1999 budget, he said, is the most modest in Mexico's
modern history and the deficit foreseen is small, the government
still needs money to finance basic spending such as health,
education, welfare, key public works and security.
	   Public finances continue to be buffeted by low crude oil prices
_ from which his administration had derived some 36 percent of its
revenue _ and uncertainty on world markets.
	   No one knows what will happen if the Dec. 31 deadline lapses _
Mexican constitutional law makes no provisions for it.
	   So it cannot cut further its expenditures as opposition groups
demand, Zedillo said.
	   The PRI with its plurality of more than half-plus-one in the
house regularly rubber-stamped the administration budget since the
party was founded and gained power in 1929.
	   The government needs to raise 15 billion pesos, equivalent to
dlrs 1.5 billion, to make up for the lower oil prices and other
shortfalls.
	   The Congress ended its ordinary session Dec. 15. It is now in
special session and the squabbling continues daily late into the
night in back rooms and caucuses.
</TEXT>
