u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-KhmerRouge 2ndAdd   12-30 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge, 2nd Add </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHNOM PENH: be bygones.''
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   In his statement, Sihanouk was clearly chafing at the amnesty he
was pressured to give Ieng Sary, another major Khmer Rouge leader,
in 1996 in exchange for getting him to lead thousands of guerrillas
out of a stalemated civil war.
	   The deal broke the back of a conflict that had festered after
the Khmer Rouge were toppled by a Vietnamese invasion in 1979.
Since, more fighters made peace and the movement has become nearly
extinct.
	   The de facto surrender of Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea has no
bearing on the military situation. Just one leader, the brutal
general Ta Mok, remains at large with no more than 100 troops. They
pose no threat to national stability.
	   Sihanouk, who was held prisoner by the Khmer Rouge in his palace
and lost a score of family members under their rule, noted he had
been pressured in 1996 to pardon Ieng Sary by his two prime
ministers _ Hun Sen and his son, Prince Norodom Ranariddh _ at the
time.
	   ``From now on, I leave all the responsibility to Hun Sen of
handling this unfortunate and dramatic affair of pardons accorded
to the Khmer Rouge,'' Sihanouk said. ``I will sign no more decrees
concerning the Khmer Rouge.''
	   That leaves Hun Sen, who defeated the prince in disputed
elections in July and is now sole premier, alone in facing intense
international pressure.
	   With peace-seeking no longer seen as a reason to grudgingly
swallow pardons for men with so much blood on their hands, demands
have been building for someone to be held accountable.
	   However, Hun Sen is by far Cambodia's most powerful man and his
will amounts to law. He controls the judiciary and security
services and could simply accord the pair a de facto pardon,
possibly through the pliant court system.
	   The king's refusal to approve an amnesty makes such a pardon
less legitimate in the eyes of the world and many Cambodians. But
Sihanouk is largely a figurehead and has no real way to enforce his
will.
	   The premier has said he had Sihanouk's approval in negotiating
the defections of the pair, who have been on the run for months as
Khmer Rouge territory came under government control.
 &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
