<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge, 3rd Add </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHNOM PENH: government control.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   The Khmer Rouge won a civil war in 1975 and emptied Cambodia's
cities in a Maoist-inspired plan to turn the country into a huge
labor camp. About one person in five died of overwork, starvation,
disease and systematic executions.
	   Sihanouk denounced Cambodia's western neighbor, Thailand, for
helping keep the Khmer Rouge alive over the past two decades, part
of a Thai strategy to contain regional rival Vietnam. The Thais
were supported by China and the United States.
	   Vietnam ended military occupation of Cambodia in 1989, but
Thailand kept up a lucrative log-and-gem trade with Khmer Rouge
guerrillas along the border.
	   Thai officials consistently state that no Khmer Rouge leaders
are on their territory, though sightings are frequently reported.
	   Local officials in a former Khmer Rouge stronghold in western
Cambodia, Pailin, said they met Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea at a
border crossing Saturday and brought them across.
	   ``No one is ignorant of the way our Thai neighbors have favored
the Khmer Rouge for decades,'' Sihanouk said.
	   ``They have no lesson on anti-Khmer Rougisim to give me or my
family who, with our people, so suffered from the Khmer Rouge's
cruelty and injustices,'' the king said.
	   Sihanouk was Cambodia's ruler before being toppled in a
U.S.-backed military coup in 1970 for being perceived as siding
with communist North Vietnam in the Vietnam War.
	   Knowing little about the Khmer Rouge, then a tiny movement,
Sihanouk lent them his considerable personal prestige to fight the
new government. The Khmer Rouge discarded him after they seized
power. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
