<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
King won't approve amnesty for Khmer Rouge leaders
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: COMBINES previous; UPDATES with former U.N. chief meeting
Khmer Rouge leader, saying doesn't favor tribunal; TRIMS; ADDS
byline &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By CHRIS FONTAINE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ King Norodom Sihanouk refused
Wednesday to approve amnesty for two leaders of the genocidal Khmer
Rouge, setting up a collision course with his prime minister, who
has pledged to shield them from trial.
	   The refusal casts doubt on the legitimacy of the deal Prime
Minister Hun Sen has made with Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea to
defect to the government in exchange for assurances they will not
be tried for crimes against humanity.
	   ``Taking into account the very wide and undeniable discontent of
the majority of the Khmer people, I announce to this majority that
I respect them and will not renew my power of amnesty for major
Khmer Rouge criminals, who are anti-Cambodian people,'' the king
said.
	   Sihanouk, 76, receiving medical treatment for a range of
ailments in Beijing, made the comments in his palace bulletin.
	   Sihanouk said that an international tribunal would have ``the
perfect right to take up the case of genocide in Cambodia, because
it concerns crimes against humanity.''
	   Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea, both members of the inner circle of
the late Khmer Rouge leader Pol Pot, spent their second day in
Phnom Penh after being greeted by Hun Sen with smiles Tuesday and
assured they would not stand trial.
	   Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea told a news conference Tuesday they
were ``very sorry'' for the deaths of as many as 2 million
Cambodians under Khmer Rouge rule between 1975 and 1979 but refused
to accept responsibility. Khieu Samphan said: ``Let bygones be
bygones.''
	   They and Hun Sen said separately that pursuing Khmer Rouge
leaders for prosecution would simply lead to a renewal of civil
war.
	   Khieu Samphan met Boutros Boutros-Ghali, the former United
Nations secretary general, who is in Cambodia to promote the French
language as head of the International Francophone Organization.
Boutros-Ghali made no comment as he left the meeting.
	   The Cambodia Daily newspaper quoted Boutros-Ghali as saying
Tuesday that he did not support the formation of an international
tribunal to bring the Khmer Rouge leaders to trial.
	   That clashes with the mission of a U.N. team dispatched by the
present secretary-general, Kofi Annan, to Cambodia recently to
assess the possibility of creating such a tribunal.
	   ``My personal view is that this is a Cambodian problem,''
Boutros-Ghali was quoted as saying. ``The U.N. should not interfere
in the affairs of member countries.''
	   Sihanouk is clearly chafing at the amnesty he was pressured to
give Ieng Sary, another Khmer Rouge leader, in 1996 to persuade him
to lead thousands of guerrillas out of a stalemated civil war.
	   The deal broke the back of a conflict that had festered after
the Khmer Rouge were toppled by a Vietnamese invasion in 1979.
Since, more fighters made peace and the movement has become nearly
extinct.
	   The de facto surrender of Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea leaves
just one leader, the brutal general Ta Mok, at large with no more
than 100 troops. They pose no threat to national stability.
	   ``From now on, I leave all the responsibility to Hun Sen of
handling this unfortunate and dramatic affair of pardons accorded
to the Khmer Rouge,'' Sihanouk said. ``I will sign no more decrees
concerning the Khmer Rouge.''
	   That leaves Hun Sen, who defeated the prince in disputed
elections in July and is now sole premier, alone in facing intense
international pressure to bring the new defectors to trial.
	   With peacemaking no longer seen as a reason to swallow pardons
for men with so much blood on their hands, demands have been
building for someone to be held accountable.
	   However, Hun Sen is Cambodia's most powerful man and his will
amounts to law. He controls the judiciary and security services and
could simply accord the pair a de facto pardon, possibly through
the pliant court system.
	   The king's rejection would make a pardon less legitimate in the
eyes of the world and many Cambodians. But Sihanouk is largely a
figurehead and has no way to enforce his will.
	   The Khmer Rouge won a civil war in 1975 and emptied Cambodia's
cities in a Maoist-inspired plan to turn the country into a huge
labor camp. About one person in five died of overwork, starvation,
disease and systematic executions.
	   Sihanouk was Cambodia's ruler before being toppled in a
U.S.-backed military coup in 1970 for being perceived as siding
with communist North Vietnam in the Vietnam War.
	   Knowing little about the Khmer Rouge, then a tiny movement,
Sihanouk lent them his considerable personal prestige to fight the
new government. The Khmer Rouge discarded him after they seized
power. 	   
</TEXT>
