<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Warne </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Recalled Warne admitted he feared the worst
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Sports-Cricket-Australia-England &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ Recalled Australian spinner Shane
Warne admitted he feared the worst during his nine-month exile from
the international arena which ended Wednesday.
	   Warne replaced rookie paceman Matthew Nicholson in the
Australian team after its stunning 12-run loss to England at the
MCG on Tuesday and will play in Saturday's fifth test in Sydney.
	   The most successful spinner in cricket history said he felt his
career was starting again and admitted there were times he feared
it might be over.
	   ``My life has been a bit like a soap opera,'' Warne said. ``It's
been like a drama, especially the last six months.''
	   Warne had surgery in April to fix a shoulder injury and the
Australian public has been following the injury's every twinge.
	   Warne said he hit a low point about six weeks after surgery and
when told he could be out of action for two years.
	   ``When I got out of the sling in six weeks nothing was really
happening,'' Warne said Wednesday. ``I started to think `well geez,
what am I going to do.' I'm not qualified at anything, I've
basically dedicated my whole life to cricket.''
	   Warne started to read up on his injury, and got no great relief
from his investigation.
	   ``I did a bit of research and some baseballers and javelin
throwers never came back from identical surgery,'' Warne said.
``That was a bit distressing. I started feeling sorry for myself
for a while then I spurred myself on and got motivated to get back
in the side.''
	   He has been low key in three Sheffield Shield matches this
season but is confident he can return to the form which has brought
him 313 test wickets.
	   ``There's no drama in my shoulder anymore, it feels good, I'm
ready,'' Warne said.
	   Warne has not played international cricket for eight months but
he has maintained a record of grabbing as many headlines as
wickets.
	   His troublesome year culminated this month when he publicly
admitted taking money from an illegal Indian bookmaker during
Australia's tour of Sri Lanka in 1994.
	   Warne and teammate Mark Waugh were fined by the Australian
Cricket Board for providing pitch and weather information to the
bookmaker in action kept secret for almost four years.
 &UR; (tjh)
</TEXT>
