<SLUG> BC-Britain-Avalanche </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Four people killed and three injured in avalanche on Scottish
</HEADLINE>
mountain &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   FORT WILLIAM, Scotland (AP) _ Four hikers have been killed and
three injured in a mountain avalanche on Scotland's northwestern
coast, police said Wednesday.
	   The seven person group were participating in ''winter skills''
training course on Aonoch Mor near Ben Nevis in the Scottish
highlands when they were caught in the avalanche, police said.
	   The hikers were reported missing at 2230 GMT Tuesday when they
did not return from the day's climb. A search was immediately
launched by a Royal Air Force mountain rescue team. Gale force
winds forced a helicopter to abandon rescue attempts, but ground
crews managed to locate the group at 0120 GMT Wednesday, a police
spokesman said, speaking with customary anonymity.
	   The three survivors were carried off the mountain, and were
being treated for injuries at a local hospital. Police did not say
whether any of their injuries were life-threatening.
	   ``They had been caught in an avalanche and it has been confirmed
that there are four fatalities and three injured,'' the police
spokesman said.
	   Rescuers were still struggling Wednesday to recover the bodies
of those killed, he said. Their efforts were being hampered by the
threat of further avalanches.
	   Northern England and Scotland have been hit by strong winds and
cold weather over the Christmas holiday, and the storm conditions
continued Wednesday.
	   Police did not release any of the victim's names or any more
information.
	   ``I'm afraid it may be some while before we get more details
because we are having to do everything on foot because of the
treacherous conditions,'' said the spokesman.
	   (mb)
</TEXT>
