<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Balloon Quest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Balloon capsule lifts off for first time during testing
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Tentative launch time is 5 a.m. local time on Jan. 1 (1930 GMT
Dec. 31)
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By ROHAN SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALICE SPRINGS, Australia (AP) _ Technical problems were
identified Wednesday when the spaceship-like capsule a
U.S.-Australian team hopes to fly around the world beneath a
balloon was lifted off the ground for the first time in Outback
Australia.
	   But organizers for the latest bid to be the first to fly nonstop
around the world say the problems were part of normal testing and
the final adjustments process, and should not in themselves delay
the launch, planned for Jan. 1.
	   The 7-ft. by 8-ft. (2.1-meter by 2.4-meter) gondola was lifted
off the ground for the first time in the Australian launch zone
Wednesday.
	   But it rose only inches (centimeters) over the red sand of the
desert launch zone, dangling beneath a crane to be weighed and for
some ballast and landing equipment checks.
	   The bid by the Re/Max team comes just days after Chicago
millionaire Steve Fossett and his team splashed down in the Pacific
Ocean.
	   Fossett, British millionaire Richard Branson and Per Lindstrand
of Sweden abandoned their more conventional balloon flight near the
northeast tip of Oahu, Hawaii on Christmas Day. They have tried a
total of 11 times.
	   For the Re/Max attempt, testing Wednesday showed uneven weight
distribution between the six steel cables from which the gondola
will be strung beneath the giant polyethylene balloon which the
three pilots plan to fly at the edge of space.
	   Technicians began working on redistribution of the 6,600-pound
(2,970-kilogram) capacity payload.
	   Scientists and engineers continued checking equipment, including
oxygen and nitrogen tanks to create the atmosphere inside the
pressurized gondola, space suits and parachutes the pilots will
wear, scientific and communications equipment and food and waste
disposal units.
	   ``We're checking and rechecking every circuit, every life
support component,'' team leader and Denver, Colorado real estate
magnate Dave Liniger said Wednesday.
	   ``There's no question that it's more dangerous than the other
missions,'' Liniger said.
	   ``The other people, if they get in trouble they can slowly go
down and sit down in the ocean. If we get into trouble, we're 25
miles (40 kilometers) up, so it creates some special hazards.''
	   The tin workshop outside the central Australian town of Alice
Springs, which serves as balloon central, was a hive of activity
Wednesday as team members including many volunteers continued final
preparations.
	   Spokesman Kevin Roark said the team was not behind schedule for
the planned Jan. 1 launch, despite many components not yet being
installed in the capsule.
	   Weather conditions may yet delay the launch further, however, if
dangerously strong winds continue to blow over the site.
	   The attempt has already been delayed twice; once when the
contract for the C-130 Hercules transport plane, which was to have
brought the capsule to Australia from the United States, was
canceled because of the latest Gulf crisis and once by high winds
and unseasonal rain over the launch zone.
	   The capsule, carrying pilots Liniger, journalist Bob Martin from
Albuquerque, New Mexico, and Australian John Wallington, will
dangle beneath a balloon that is 460 feet (138 meters) in diameter
at ``full float'' and 700 feet (210 meters) high, large enough to
envelope the Houston Astrodome.
	   It will rise 1,000 feet (300 meters) a minute during takeoff,
filling with helium on the way up to a cruising altitude of 130,000
feet (39,000 meters), or about 24 miles (39 kilometers) above sea
level.
	   There, the team expects to catch winds that will carry it west
at up to 80 mph (128 kph) along a route that almost directly
follows the Tropic of Capricorn, and complete the 22,800-mile
(36,480-kilometer) journey in about 18 days.
	   The NASA-developed balloon type has been used before, but only
to carry unmanned scientific payloads to heights of about 80,000
feet (24,000 meters)
	   ``Its great to see her hanging here,'' said Martin as he oversaw
the weighing procedures and began fitting the cameras he expects
will transmit pictures from the edge of space.
	   Martin said that along with the landing, the launch would be the
most dangerous part of the trip.
	   ``We have parachutes, but in reality below about 10,000 feet
(3,000 meters) it is doubtable that the parachute will open in time
to save you,'' he said.
	   ``For the first 500-1,000 feet (150-300 meters) will be very
risky, we will be biting our fingernails.'' 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Australia-Balloon Quest; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:MEST;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
