<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Earthquake </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Moderate earthquake awakens many residents in central Philippines
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DUMAGUETE CITY, Philippines (AP) _ A moderate earthquake with a
preliminary magnitude of 4.3 shook several central Philippine towns
early Wednesday, rousing many residents from sleep but causing no
casualties or damages, witnesses said.
	   The earthquake hit several towns in the island provinces of
Negros Oriental and Bohol at 2:45 a.m. (1845 GMT Tuesday) and was
centered 35 kilometers (22 miles) southwest of Dumaguete City in
Negros, seismologists said.
	   ``I was awakened and felt my house shaking,'' said businessman
Manuel Sagarbaria in Dumaguete. A reporter said some residents
rushed out of several houses in the city.
	   Government seismologist Henry Penarubia said the earthquake,
caused by a movement in the Negros Trench 18 kilometers (11 miles)
below the ground, was not strong enough to generate destructive
waves or destroy structures.
	   The Philippines is located in one of the most earthquake-prone
regions in the world. 	   
</TEXT>
