<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Exports </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Vietnam loses export revenue from lower prices
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ Vietnam has lost dlrs 630 million in
export revenue this year due to lower prices for some key items,
Wednesday's Labor newspaper quoted Trade Minister Truong Dinh Tuyen
as saying.
	   Lower world prices for crude oil, seafood, garments and rubber
have cost the country dlrs 1.16 billion in export revenue, but that
was partially offset by a dlrs 530 million gain from higher prices
for rice, coffee and cashew nuts, Tuyen said.
	   The Asian crisis has taken a toll on Vietnam's exports, which
grew only 0.9 percent to dlrs 9.356 billion this year, compared
with an average of 25 percent in recent years, according to
preliminary data from the General Statistical Office.
	   This year's trade deficit stands at dlrs 2.034 billion, down
from dlrs 2.35 billion last year.
	   The National Assembly last month set an export growth target of
5 percent to 7 percent for 1999.
	   Tuyen said Vietnam can achieve its export target of dlrs 10
billion for next year with efforts to increase export revenues of
crude oil, garments and shoes.
	   Tuyen projects that world prices for Vietnam's key export items
next year will see only very little improvement compared with 1998.
</TEXT>
