<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Indonesia-Elephants </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Five Thai elephants stranded in Indonesia return home
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Five Thai elephants stranded in
Indonesia for the past 15 months returned home on Wednesday,
arriving by barge in the early morning darkness at the southern
port of Phuket.
	   A score of animal rights activists and government officials were
on hand to greet the elephants as a crane lifted them, one by one
with their handlers riding on their backs to keep them calm, on to
the dock at Phuket, a resort island, 690 kilometers (430 miles)
southwest of Bangkok.
	   The activists, who had been waging a campaign to pressure the
government to rescue the elephants, held yellow banners that read
``Welcome Home to Thailand Elephant.''
	   They draped the beasts with garlands of marigolds while some fed
them bananas and other fruits.
	   Thais regard elephants as a symbol of their nation, and all
white elephants are regarded as property of the royal family.
	   The elephants and their handlers were sent to Indonesia last
year on a ten-year contract to train elephants in that country's
logging industry.
	   But when a severe economic crisis hit Indonesia, the company
that hired the elephants and their handlers could not pay their
salaries.
	   The handlers returned to Thailand, but with no money or way to
transport their charges, were forced to leave them behind.
Indonesian officials said their government was too broke to pay for
the elephants transport home.
	   The elephants left the Indonesian port of Medan on the island of
Sumatra and sailed across the Andaman Sea to Phuket after
government officials raised 1.5 million baht (dlrs 40,500) in
donations to transport them.
	   Hardwood logging has been illegal in largely-deforested Thailand
since 1989, depriving elephants of one of their valued roles in
this country.
	   With their habitat rapidly shrinking, many handlers have had
little choice but to lead their beasts along city streets begging
for food.
	   Illegal logging is still ongoing in many border areas.
	   The governor of Lampang province, one such area near the border
with Myanmar, or Burma, said more than 200 elephants were being
overworked and force fed amphetamines by illegal loggers in three
districts in his province, according to Wednesday's Bangkok Post
newspaper.
	   The Post also reported that an elephant stomped his handler to
death in a forest in Lampang on Tuesday, but was eventually subdued
with tranquilizer darts.
	   (aptn-rh)
</TEXT>
