<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Terrifying Elephants </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Villagers told not to confront wild elephants
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ Villagers in the southern province of Dong
Nai have been told not to confront a herd of 14 wild elephants that
have killed three people this month, a local government official
said Wednesday.
	   Local officials, meeting Saturday, also crafted ways to live in
peace with the pachyderms. They include informing villagers who
reside near jungles not to go to rice fields after 3 p.m. and to
offer more food to the elephants, said Nguyen Bach Mo, chief of the
Dinh Quan district forest control bureau.
	   The elephants often terrify villagers at night. Earlier this
month, three people were trampled by the elephants, bringing the
number of deaths to nine since 1993. Fifteen families have been
evacuated, Mo said.
	   But he said long-term solutions _ evacuation of some 400
families living in areas often threatened by the elephants or
relocation of the animals to other areas _ would be expensive.
	   The officials agreed to provide relief aid to families who go
hungry because they can not harvest their crops in areas frequented
by elephants, Mo said. Those villagers also have been encouraged to
buy life insurance.
	   Over the past few months, the elephants have terrified villagers
once every week or two. During their rampages, they have eaten all
the available food, including rice and salt.
	   The provincial government has allocated 40 million dong (dlrs
3,000) to buy salt, which is to be mixed with shell and bones and
placed at spots that the elephants frequent.
	   Mo said the herd became particularly aggressive since 1993, when
a team of foreign elephant trainers was hired to trap 11 elephants
and transport them to a village in the central highland province of
Daklak for taming. All of those elephants later died.
	   The Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development estimates
Vietnam has 120 to 130 wild elephants down from 1,500 to 2,000 a
decade ago.
</TEXT>
