<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Refinery </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Joint venture for Vietnam's first oil refinery gets license
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ A joint venture with Russia to build and
run Vietnam's first oil refinery has been granted an operating
license, the Vietnam News Agency reported Wednesday.
	   The license was granted Tuesday for the VietRoss Refinery, to be
located at the small fishing village of Dung Quat about 100
kilometers (60 miles) south of Danang.
	   It is expected to refine 6.5 million tons (1.88 billion gallons)
of crude oil per year, with the first phase to be operational in
2001.
	   The refinery is a joint venture between Vietnam's oil and gas
monopoly, PetroVietnam, and Russia's Zarubezhneft. They signed a
contract last month and are to equally fund the projected
investment capital of dlrs 1.3 billion.
	   At a meeting in August, Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
Vietnamese counterpart Tran Duc Luong pledged to rebuild their
countries' Soviet-era alliance.
	   ``As a minimum, we should restore our past relations,
concentrating on the oil and gas complex,'' Yeltsin said.
	   The first oil production joint venture between the countries was
VietSovpetro, established in 1986.
	   It has been Vietnam's major crude oil producer ever since,
accounting for 80 percent of this year's total output of crude and
earning about dlrs 1.2 billion from exports this year _ 13 percent
of the country's total export turnover.
	   Before the contract was signed, speculation had been rife that
the refinery project never would be finished. Two potential foreign
partners backed out, concerned about the distance from the
oilfields and lack of control over pricing.
	   Vietnam exports high-quality sweet crude from its White Tiger
offshore field near the Spratly islands, mostly to Japan. But it
had to import 6 million tons of refined products in 1997.
	   Foreign investors wanted the refinery in southern Vietnam, near
the oil and gas fields. The government opted for Quang Ngai
province, on the typhoon-prone central coast, to help the poor
region.
</TEXT>
