w2369 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-Iraq     12-30 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Iraq,0650 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With US, Iraq, still in military mode, UN tries to find its future
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ U.N. weapons inspectors joke about looking
for new work and outgoing Security Council members trot to their
last meetings, apparently relieved their two-year terms will end
before the council decides what to do about Iraq.
	   It seems few people at the United Nations sense an urgent need
to figure out a future for U.N. weapons inspections in Iraq _ at
least not during the holidays or as long as Baghdad and Washington
still trade fire and angry rhetoric.
	   But there is little question they must do so: U.N. resolutions
and international law demand that U.N. weapons experts oversee the
elimination of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction before sanctions
are lifted.
	   Most diplomats acknowledge that the process of finding a new
relationship with Iraq will be long and contentious in the wake of
the U.S.-British bombing campaign and Iraq's declaration that
inspectors will never return.
	   Permanent council members Russia and China have criticized both
the strikes and chief weapons inspector Richard Butler, whose
report on Iraq's alleged lack of cooperation triggered the military
attack. Iraq's other sympathizer on the council _ France _ has
suggested a whole new system of monitoring Iraq's proscribed
weapons programs.
	   The result is that nearly two weeks after the first cruise
missiles fell, the Security Council has yet to agree on a formal
response to the bombing campaign and the future of Butler's U.N.
Special Commission.
	   ``Major differences remain,'' Russia's deputy U.N. ambassador,
Yuriy Fedotov, told reporters heading into a council meeting on an
entirely different subject: the Ethiopia-Eritrea dispute.
	   Indeed, the United States objects to the key elements of a
Russia-drafted statement on Iraq, most significantly a reference
that the council ``expresses regret'' that force was used against
Baghdad.
	   Meanwhile, on the 38th floor, Secretary-General Kofi Annan has
assembled a team of four of his closest aides to advise him on what
to do next. But he is bound by the will of the council, which seems
paralyzed _ at least temporarily _ by the conflict.
	   ``He clearly wants guidance from the council,'' said U.N.
spokesman Manoel de Almeida E Silva, indicating that Annan, too,
feels powerless by the divisions.
	   Annan told reporters last week that he hoped council members
would use the Christmas holidays to reflect on how they could
bridge the gaps among themselves to ``forge the way ahead.''
	   ``To do that, in my judgment, will require flexibility,
compromise, and a willingness to really think creatively,'' he
said.
	   On Jan. 1, the council welcomes five new nonpermanent members _
Canada, the Netherlands, Argentina, Malaysia and Namibia _ who will
have to take up Annan's call.
	   On Tuesday, Portuguese Ambassador Antonio Monteiro was downright
jovial as he headed into one of his last council meetings,
indicating his relief that he wouldn't have to deal with the
situation.
	   Inspectors, meanwhile, continued working in New York, preparing
documents for a future assessment of Iraq's weapons capabilities,
U.N. spokesman Ewen Buchanan said Tuesday.
	   A third of the inspectors who were pulled from Baghdad just
before the first missiles rained down have been sent home, however.
	   Inspectors joke about updating their resumes and finding new
work, citing predictions of the demise of UNSCOM and the calls for
Butler's ouster by Iraq, Russia and others.
	   One such call came from an unusual place this week: Former
inspector Scott Ritter, one of Iraq's greatest critics, wrote in
Monday's Wall Street Journal that Butler should resign for having
allowed himself to be used by Washington.
</TEXT>
