w2375 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Vietnam-DrugTrafficki     12-30 0222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Drug Trafficking </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Drug-related crimes quadrupled in Ho Chi Minh City this year
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ Drug-related crimes have quadrupled this
year in Ho Chi Minh City, the Thanh Nien newspaper reported
Wednesday.
	   It cited a report from the city prosecutor's office as saying it
handled 1,473 cases this year from 388 in 1997, evidence of
Vietnam's growing drug problem.
	   The Ho Chi Minh City Police newspaper reported Tuesday that
courts nationwide this year have issued a record 49 death penalties
_ up from 26 last year _ and 31 life sentences for convicted
traffickers.
	   It said 18,000 people in 9,000 cases have been arrested
nationwide this year on drug-related charges, up 44 percent and 35
percent, respectively, from 1997.
	   Police have seized 65.53 kgs (144.5 pounds) of heroin and 1,135
kgs (2,502 pounds) of opium so far this year.
	   In a major crackdown as part of the government's anti-drug
campaign, police arrested 1,119 people in 607 cases nationwide in
15 days ending Dec. 15, seizing 4.06 kilograms (8.95 pounds) of
heroin and 22 kilograms (48.5 pounds) of opium.
	   There are about 80,000 drug addicts in the country with police
records, but the National Drug Control Committee estimates that
there are 134,000 drug addicts nationwide, 70 percent under age 30.
</TEXT>
