<HEADLINE>
Sports institute to investigate abuse claims
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Australian Institute of Sport (AIS)
director John Boultbee said Wednesday he will investigate claims
that female tennis scholarship holders were subjected to starvation
diets and verbal abuse.
	   However, Boultbee believes the AIS should never be blamed for
athletes failing to make the grade at international level, saying
the taxpayer-funded program provides the ``opportunity'' only for
graduates to reach greater heights.
	   Responding to claims from at least 34 women that their careers
were ruined by the AIS training regime, Boultbee said the AIS had
to ensure basic fitness requirements were met.
	   ``It's all too easy to blame the AIS when someone is not
successful,'' Boultbee said. ``Sometimes the athletes should
perhaps look at themselves a bit more closely.''
	   Players involved in the program between 1981 and 1995 have
leveled the accusations, with some saying they developed eating
disorders because of the pressure to lose weight. (djp) 	   
</TEXT>
