<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-Thomson </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Olympic organizers want Howard to muzzle renegade legislator
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Prime Minister John Howard on Wednesday
ignored pleas from Olympics organizers to silence a former sports
minister who wants the Games abolished following a bribery scandal.
	   International Olympic Committee (IOC) member Kevan Gosper of
Australia said Howard should bring renegade member of Parliament
Andrew Thomson into line, but the prime minister said Thomson was
entitled to an opinion, even if he did not share it.
	   ``He's a mere backbencher, he's entitled to his view,'' Howard
said.
	   Thomson, who was replaced as sports minister after the October
federal election, this week said the international Olympic movement
was so tainted by bribery scandals that the 2004 Olympics in Athens
should be the last modern Olympics.
	   Howard said he would not take any disciplinary action against
Thomson, even though Gosper said his comments could damage Olympic
reputation ahead of the 2000 Games in Sydney.
	   Thomson said IOC members, who are not elected but appointed for
life, were a bizarre group of men.
	   ``If you're going to organize sport on a global level I would
have thought the first requirement would be that it be ethically
clean and that there be no suggestion of any financial taint to it
all,'' Thomson said.
	   ``But I don't think that with these people (IOC members)
appointed for life, silly as that obviously is, that they can
redeem themselves.
	   ``Why can't we organize a global competition in some other form
where the franchises are not handed out by this extraordinary,
bizarre group of men ... What better than to say Athens . . . why
not make 2004 the last?'' (djp) 	   
</TEXT>
