<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Avalanche, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Four people killed and three injured in avalanche on Scottish
</HEADLINE>
mountain &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES to ADD quote from police inspector; new information
about condition of survivors; recovery of two bodies; EDITS
thruout &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   FORT WILLIAM, Scotland (AP) _ Four hikers have been killed and
three injured in a mountain avalanche on Scotland's northwestern
coast, police said Wednesday.
	   The seven person group were participating in ``winter skills''
training course on Aonoch Mor near Ben Nevis in the Scottish
highlands when they were caught in the avalanche, police said.
	   Police did not release any of the victims' names.
	   Police Inspector Chas Ross told British Broadcasting Corp.'s
Radio 4 that the climbers were ''not well versed in the ways of the
hills but they had an instructor with them.''
	   The hikers were reported missing at 2230 GMT Tuesday when they
did not return from the day's climb. A search was immediately
launched by Royal Air Force mountain rescue teams. Gale force winds
forced a helicopter to abandon rescue attempts, but ground crews
managed to locate the group at 0120 GMT Wednesday, a police
spokesman said, speaking with customary anonymity.
	   The three survivors were carried off the mountain one at a time,
said a spokesman for Inverness ambulance services, speaking with
customary anonymity. He said they were taken to Belford Hospital in
Fort William, where they were being treated for hypothermia.
	   ``They had been caught in an avalanche and it has been confirmed
that there are four fatalities and three injured,'' the police
spokesman said.
	   Rescuers recovered two of the victim's bodies Wednesday morning,
and were still struggling to bring the other two off the mountain,
police said. Their efforts were being hampered by the threat of
further avalanches.
	   Northern England and Scotland have been hit by strong winds and
cold weather over the Christmas holiday, and the storm conditions
continued Wednesday.
	   ``I'm afraid it may be some while before we get more details
because we are having to do everything on foot because of the
treacherous conditions,'' said the police spokesman.
	   (mb)
</TEXT>
