w2396 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Taiwan-China     12-30 0375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-China </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan warns China against stepping up diplomatic isolation
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Taiwan's foreign minister on Wednesday
warned China against stepping up its campaign to isolate the
island, saying it will only hinder reunification of the two sides.
	   ``China believes when it succeeds in taking away all of our
diplomatic allies, the time will come for reunification,'' Jason Hu
told a news conference. ``But I am afraid the more they push to
leave us zero diplomatic allies, it will only mean zero chance of
reunification.
	   ``Their suppression only sparks antagonism among our people, and
they must try to understand how people feel about it.''
	   Taiwan lost four diplomatic allies to Beijing this year _ South
Africa, Central African Republic, Guinea Bissau and Tonga. But it
picked up one new ally, the Marshall Islands.
	   Despite that gain, Taiwan is left with just 27 allies, mostly
small countries in Africa and Central and South America.
	   China considers Taiwan a renegade province and threatens to use
force to retake it, if necessary, after 49 years of political
separation following a civil war.
	   Hu warned China against pursuing so-called ``Big Country
Diplomacy'' by striking strategic alliances with advanced nations
while seeking their commitments to isolate Taiwan.
	   During his visit to Beijing last summer, U.S. President Bill
Clinton pledged not to support Taiwan's efforts to rejoin the
United Nations or its independence.
	   ``Despite their closer relations, Western nations will never
ease their attacks on the mainland's human rights violations,'' Hu
said. ``As Washington and Beijing get closer to each other, they
will also realize the wide gaps between them.''
	   When asked to comment on news reports that Washington has urged
Taiwan and China to establish a direct link between their military
forces, Hu said it has remained a ``scholastic idea.''
	   Setting up a hot line between Taiwan and China was among several
ideas U.S. officials have broached to help avoid a confrontation
resulting from a misjudgment of the other side's military
maneuvers, he said.
	   None of the ideas shall materialize unless both Taiwan and China
agree, he said.
</TEXT>
