<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Bullet Train </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan to retire original bullet trains
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Once the fastest railcars in the world and a symbol
of modern Japan, the nation's original bullet trains will make
their final runs in 1999, a railway official said Wednesday.
	   The trains will be gradually retired throughout next year to
make way for a new, faster express, said Yukihiro Ishitani of
Central Japan Railways.
	   Billed as the ``superexpresses of the century'' when they
debuted in 1964, the first-generation trains traveled between Tokyo
and the western city of Osaka at a record-setting speed of 210 kph
(130 miles per hour).
	   New routes have been added since then, and a total of 3,216 cars
of the original model were built by the defunct Japanese National
Railways (JNR), the forerunner of the privatized Japan Railway
group companies.
	   Sleeker, faster trains have also been introduced, including the
``Nozomi,'' which travels the 408-km (253 mile-) distance from
Tokyo to Osaka in just two and a half hours, compared to four hours
on the original train.
	   A new version of the Nozomi, with a maximum speed of 285 kph
(177 miles per hour), will debut in March 1999.
	   Kazutaro Oishi, 65, who drove the original bullet train on its
first day of operation, said he is sorry to see it go, Kyodo News
Agency reported Wednesday.
	   ``The train was high-tech, totally different from the trains
before,'' he was quoted as saying. ``It's really sad to see them
retire.'' 	   
</TEXT>
