<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Tajikistan-Fighting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fighting erupts in Tajik capital
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DUSHANBE, Tajikistan (AP) _ Rival groups staged a fierce gun
battle in the center of Tajikistan's capital Dushanbe on Wednesday,
news reports said.
	   There was no immediate word on casualties in the Central Asian
nation.
	   Security guards from the National Reconciliation Commission
traded fire with troops loyal to a military commander, Rakhmon
Sanginov, according to Russia's Interfax news agency.
	   Civilians fled the center of the capital, leaving it deserted
except for the combatants, who were armed with rifles, machine guns
and grenade launchers, Russian news agencies reported.
	   It was not immediately clear what sparked the conflict in
Tajikistan, which is still recovering from a 5-year-civil war that
formally ended last year.
	   Ex-rebels now serve in the government, the army, and the
National Reconciliation Commission, which was established to bring
the former combatants together. However, there are still frictions
among the various groups.
	   Russia has about 25,000 troops in the Central Asian nation to
support President Emomali Rakhmonov, but there was no indication
that they were involved in the fighting.
	   (gm/nw) 	   
</TEXT>
