<HEADLINE>
Chechen businessman released from captivity
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A businessman was released from captivity in the
breakaway region of Chechnya on Wednesday, two weeks after he was
taken hostage, a news report said.
	   Salamabek Khadshiyev, who heads a department of the regional gas
company Chechengazprom, was on his way to work when he was taken
hostage in mid-December, according to the Interfax news agency. No
details about his release, including whether a ransom was paid,
were available.
	   Chechen bandits have kidnapped hundreds of people for ransom
since the end of Chechnya's 1994-96 independence war with Russia.
	   Chechnya now runs its own affairs, though no country recognizes
its claim of independence, and Moscow says the territory remains
part of Russia.
