w2411 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Vietnam-Smuggling     12-30 0329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Smuggling </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Viet-Australian businessman given five years for smuggling
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ High-profile Vietnam-born Australian
businessman Nguyen Trung Truc and one of his associates have been
sentenced to five years in jail for smuggling 242 motorcycles, a
court official said Wednesday.
	   Truc and Nguyen Van Dung were convicted in a one-day trial last
Friday in the southern province of Ba Ria Vung Tau. They have 15
days to appeal.
	   Truc set up a joint venture with the now-bankrupt Peregrine
Capital Holdings in 1991 to engage in financial and investment
consulting.
	   Between the end of 1995 and mid-1996, he authorized Dung to
arrange import quotas for motorbikes with local companies and
imported three batches, the court official said.
	   He imported a fourth batch of 242 Piaggio motorbikes in
September 1996, but could only arrange for the import quota with a
local trading company in December 1996.
	   The local company refused to sign the import contract because
the motorcycles already had been brought in, the official said, and
in March 1997, customs officials decided to confiscate them.
	   The case sent chills through the foreign investor community
because many businessmen say Vietnam's rules are unclear and
unevenly enforced, encouraging risk-taking that can backfire.
	   In May this year, Truc and five of his associates were charged
with tax evasion. With a series of affiliate companies, he
allegedly avoided dlrs 8 million in taxes by declaring imported
goods at lower prices than actual costs.
	   Truc was one of the first businessmen to jump into the Vietnam
market in the early 1990s, when the government had just begun
liberalizing its Soviet-style planned economic system.
	   His flamboyant style and rapid success in setting up auto and
computer dealerships brought him the spotlight, and he was
frequently profiled by international business publications as a
Vietnam success story.
</TEXT>
