<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-US-Holocaust </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. and Israel form committee to monitor Holocaust restitution
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel's parliament and the U.S. Congress are
forming a committee to monitor the return of Holocaust-era property
worldwide, an Israeli legislator said Wednesday.
	   The committee, headed by Congressman Ben Gilman, a New York
Republican, and Israeli legislator Avraham Hirshson from the Likud
Party, will monitor implementation of restitution plans that
representatives from over 40 countries made at a conference in
Washington, D.C. last month, Hirshson said.
	   ``We want to remind these countries of their commitments,''
Hirshson said. He estimated the value of Jewish property either
plundered by the Nazis or left unclaimed after its owners perished
in the Holocaust at several billion dollars.
	   Restoring the property will be complicated, Hirshson said,
because many of the assets, including gold, works of art and real
estate, have changed hands several times.
	   Several countries have already begun restoring property or
paying out insurance claims.
	   Hirshson said there was no way to know how long the restitution
process would take but that participants in last month's conference
agreed to meet twice more to continue discussing the issue.
 &UR; sb-kl
</TEXT>
