w2416 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Myanmar-NLDResignatio     12-30 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Myanmar-NLD Resignations </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Myanmar military says 192 opposition members resign from party
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ In the steady and mysterious collapse
of Myanmar's main opposition party, 192 more members have resigned
from Aung San Suu Kyi's National League for Democracy, the
state-run New Light of Myanmar reported on Wednesday.
	   The 183 members from Ayerwaddy Division, or province, and nine
from Myeik Township, ``on their own volition tendered their
resignations'' to the Election Commission because ``they no longer
wished to participate in the activities of the NLD,'' the paper
said.
	   The paper, which is tightly controlled by the military
government, did not explain what prompted so many party members to
reach that decision simultaneously after eight years of membership.
	   Myanmar's laws have forbidden parties from taking on new members
since that time.
	   The paper also did not say if the 192 were among the more than
900 NLD members detained by the military since September.
	   A government spokesman has said they are staying at government
guest houses for a friendly exchange of views.
	   Nearly 500 have since been released, after resigning from the
party or signing undertakings pledging not to be involved in
political activity.
	   Those who have not resigned from the party have not been
released.
	   The military has ruled Myanmar, also known as Burma, in various
forms since 1962. In 1990, an election was held in which the NLD
won 82 percent of the seats in parliament.
	   The military refused to honor the result and has never allowed
parliament to convene. Suu Kyi's attempt to assemble the surviving
parliamentarians in September resulted in the mass detentions.
	   Suu Kyi, the daughter of Myanmar's independence hero, was placed
under house arrest from 1989-95 for her campaign to restore
democracy to the resource-rich, but poverty-stricken country.
	   In 1991 she was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
	   ``We want to make clear that all these resignations were made
under coercion,'' Suu Kyi said in November. ``We are heartened by
the spirit of the great majority of the NLD members. The great
majority of our members remained staunch and have not been shaken
in their resolve.''
	   Asked if the mass resignations of members could paralyze her
party, Suu Kyi replied: ``The NLD will stand as it always stands _
fighting fit.''
	   She said the NLD leadership does not recognize the resignations.
	   Suu Kyi, who preaches nonviolence, emerged as the leader of
Myanmar's democratic movement in August 1988, two weeks after the
military crushed a nationwide uprising against its rule by gunning
down more than 3,000 protesters.
</TEXT>
