w2419 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yemen-Kidnapping 3rdLd-Writethru   12-30 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Kidnapping, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Four Westerners killed in bloody end to Yemen kidnapping
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS lead and UPDATES with foreign criticism, includes
capture of some kidnappers reported earlier. &QL; 
 &UR; By AHMAD AL-HAJ &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ Yemen faced a barrage of criticism Wednesday
after its troops stormed the hideout of Islamic extremist
kidnappers holding 16 Western hostages. Four of the hostages were
killed.
	   Two other hostages were wounded during the siege near the
southern town of Mawdiyah, about 175 miles (280 kilometers) south
of the capital, San`a.
	   The remaining 10 hostages were freed unharmed. Three kidnappers
died.
	   Yemen's Interior Ministry blamed the kidnappers for the deaths
of the three Britons killed instantly and an Australian who died in
later in a hospital. It said security forces intervened after the
kidnappers had begun killing the hostages.
	   ``They proceeded in killing the captives after refusing any
attempts at negotiations, which led security forces to storm the
area to prevent further bloodshed and ensure the safe release of
the rest of the hostages,'' a ministry statement said.
	   But British newspapers accused the Yemeni authorities of
premature intervention in the case. The Daily Mail asked on the
front page, ``Did your tourists really need to die?''
	   British Ambassador Vic Henderson reportedly had pleaded with the
San`a government to do nothing ``that in any way could jeopardize
the safety of the hostages.''
	   In San`a, Yemenis told journalists they were surprised the
government had intervened so quickly when it usually negotiated for
several days, if not weeks, in the hostage-taking frequent in
Yemen.
	   A London-based Islamic human rights group said Tuesday that it
had contacted the kidnappers the night before and received
assurances that they would not harm the hostages.
	   ``We hold the Yemeni government responsible for the deaths. The
way the authorities handled the situation was barbaric and
irresponsible,'' said a spokesman for the Islamic Observation
Center.
	   Kidnappings of foreigners occur often in Yemen, large parts of
which are run by lawless tribes, but until now the hostages usually
have been treated well and released unharmed.
	   But this was the first time an abduction was carried out by
Islamic extremists. Security officials said the kidnappers belong
to Islamic Jihad, many of whose leaders fought Russian troops in
Afghanistan. The group is believed to have about 200 members.
	   The 16 tourists, 12 Britons, two Americans and two Australians,
were kidnapped Monday near Mawdiyah.
	   In London, the Foreign Office confirmed that three Britons _
Ruth Williamson, Margaret Whitehouse and Peter Rowe _ were killed,
but did not provide their ages or hometowns.
	   The Australian Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade said the
fourth victim was a 35-year-old man from Sydney whose name would
not be released until next of kin had been informed.
	   The tourists wounded in the clash were an American woman and a
British woman.
	   The surviving hostages were recovering from their ordeal at a
hotel in Aden, where volunteers from the British and American
communities were helping them cope with their trauma, said David
Pearce, a British Embassy official in San`a.
	   ``They are obviously in a state of severe shock, and I mean
severe shock,'' Pearce told the British news agency Press
Association. ''They are uninjured but obviously very tired, very
stunned and in need of a good meal, a good rest and someone to talk
to. They have been through an awful experience.''
	   After the shootout, security forces detained scores of suspected
Islamic extremists, said the officials, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
	   At least three of the kidnappers _ including the mastermind of
the abduction _ were captured alive, the Interior Ministry said. It
said one of the kidnappers killed was an unidentified Egyptian.
	   The kidnapping began Monday when the tourists' convoy of five
vehicles was ambushed by men who opened fire on their police
escorts. The kidnappers threatened to kill the tourists if the
police did not back off, Yemeni security officials said.
	   The kidnappers demanded the release of their leader, Saleh
Haidara al-Atwi, who was detained two weeks ago in a government
crackdown on Islamic vigilantes who had been enforcing strict
Islamic rules in southern Yemen, security officials said.
	   The kidnappers also wanted the release of another leader, the
officials said. They did not identify him.
	   Yemen said the governor of Abyan province, Ahmad Ali Mohsen, was
negotiating with leaders of the Al-Fadl tribe, to which the
kidnappers belong, before the shootout occurred.
	   Tribesmen usually kidnapped foreigners to pressure the
government into providing them with new roads, water or clinics.
	   Four Germans are being held by a tribe in northeast Yemen. The
kidnappers are demanding more schools, hospitals and telephone
lines in their area.
	   German diplomats have appealed to the Yemeni authorities not to
attempt to rescue the four German hostages being held by a tribe in
a different part of the country, Yemeni officials said Wednesday.
