<HEADLINE>
Japan. Some of these stories also moved earlier today as
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from China, the Philippines, South Korea, and
separates. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Ticket sales for Japan's year-end lottery rose for
the first time in four years, as many Japanese gambled on one last
chance for something to cheer about in a year filled with miserable
economic news.
	   Sales of ``Jumbo'' lottery tickets rose to 215.5 billion (dlrs
1.87 billion), up 6 percent from a year ago, the company that sells
the tickets, Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd., said Wednesday. The sales
figure was short of the record of 244.3 billion yen (dlrs 2.12
billion) set in 1994, the bank said.
	   The increase in lottery sales reflected people's hopes for a big
win amid the nation's deepening recession, said Satoshi Oda,
spokesman for Dai-Ichi Kangyo.
	   Japan is mired in its worst recession since the end of World War
II, with unemployment at a record high.
	   Tickets for the year-end lottery cost 300 yen (dlrs 2.6) each.
The first prize is 60 million yen (dlrs 521,000), an amount that
would buy a 100-square-meter (1,125 square feet) home in a Tokyo
suburb.
	   The drawing for the grand prize will be held Thursday at noon
and will be televised nationally.
	    &UR; ___
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Boosted by massive state spending on public
works, China's economy grew by 7.8 percent this year but missed its
official target, according to figures released Wednesday.
	   Growth was down sharply from 1997, when the economy expanded by
8.8 percent. Chinese leaders had hoped for at least 8 percent this
year to create jobs for millions of workers laid off in a sweeping
overhaul of state companies.
	   China has escaped the full impact of the 18-month-old Asian
financial crisis, but faces serious problems of its own in trying
to turn around money-losing state industries and clean up its
state-owned banking system.
	   The Chinese economy has slowed since its days of double-digit
growth in the early 1990s, but still is doing better than its
neighbors. Indonesia, one of the Asian economies hardest hit by the
crisis, says its economy could shrink by up to 15 percent this
year.
	   In a positive sign, the Chinese growth rate began to rise in
recent months, pumped up by the start of a dlrs 1.4 trillion,
three-year stimulus plan of spending on new highways and other
projects, according to the State Statistical Bureau.
	   Investment in fixed assets _ the centerpiece of the stimulus
plan _ was up 15 percent to 2.9 trillion yuan (dlrs 364.4 billion).
Most of that spending came from state companies, while investment
by private companies was unchanged, said Ye Zhen, a spokesman for
the Statistical Bureau.
	   Industrial output was up 8.8 percent.
	   Exports were almost unchanged from 1997 at dlrs 182 billion,
while imports fell 3.8 percent to dlrs 137 billion. That left China
with a trade surplus of dlrs 45 billion, up dlrs 4.7 billion from
the previous year.
	    &UR; ___
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ President Joseph Estrada on Wednesday
formally approved a 1999 budget of 579.5 billion pesos (dlrs 14.8
billion), which he said would allow the Philippine economy to
recover from Asia's financial crisis.
	   ``With this expenditure program, we will be able to give our
economy the push it needs to get out of the danger zone and set it
firmly on the path of steady growth,'' Estrada said.
	   He said nearly 68 percent of the budget would be spent for
social services, infrastructure in rural areas and the development
of agriculture which would help the country register a gross
national product growth of 3.0 to 3.5 percent next year.
	   The Philippine economy suffered a slowdown this year due to the
effects of the regional financial turmoil, a severe drought and a
series of killer typhoons that devastated key agricultural regions.
	   Budget Secretary Benjamin Diokno said that with better weather
and more rainfall forecast next year and funding for projects aimed
at boosting agricultural production, the government's economic
targets could be attained.
	   Estrada said changes have been made in budgetary disbursement
procedures to avoid corruption and allow the prompt payment of
financial obligations. Details of major budget releases would be
posted on the Internet for transparency, he said.
	   The Department of Education, Culture and Sports got the highest
appropriation amounting to 88.3 billion pesos (dlrs 2.26 billion),
followed by the defense department with 51.7 billion (dlrs 1.32
billion) and the Department of Public Works and Highways with 38.2
billion pesos (dlrs 979 million), Diokno said.
	    &UR; ___
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ South Korea will abolish its
20-year-old import ban on an assortment of Japanese cars and other
industrial goods by June next year, government officials said
Wednesday.
	   South Korea currently bans the import of 48 Japanese products,
including many types of cars, as part of its effort to protect
domestic industries and fight a chronic trade imbalance with Japan.
	   South Korea will begin Thursday by first lifting the ban on 32
products, including station wagons with 1- to 1.5-liter engine
capacity, jeeps with over 1.5-liter gasoline engines, as well as
camcorders, copy machines and audio components.
	   The remaining 16 items _ such as sedans, color televisions, cell
phones and station wagons with less than 3-liter engine capacity _
will be freed from the import ban on June 30 next year, said the
Ministry of Trade, Industry and Energy.
	   ``In the long run, the decision will likely increase our trade
deficit with Japan,'' said Choi Chul-woo, a ministry official. ``It
will most likely affect domestic car, electronic home appliances
and machine tool industries.''
	   But with the country's imports remaining sluggish amid an
economic crisis, the Japanese products newly exempt from the ban
will pose little immediate competition to domestic manufacturers,
Choi said.
	   South Korea imposed the ban in 1978 to control a chronic trade
deficit with Japan, which had provided up to 40 percent of all
South Korean imports in the 1970s.
	   The ban helped South Korea to reduce its dependence on its
neighbor for imports to around 24 percent in the 1990s. But its
trade deficit with Japan has kept increasing _ from dlrs 2.8
billion in 1980 to dlrs 13 billion last year.
	   Tokyo has complained that the restrictions are an unfair trade
practice, and Seoul has been gradually lifting the ban, reducing
the number of goods prohibited.
	    &UR; ___
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Nomura Securities Co., Japan's biggest brokerage,
will cut 650 overseas jobs next year as part of a major
restructuring campaign, a company official said Wednesday.
	   Facing massive losses in its overseas operations, the company
will shed nearly 20 percent of its work force in Europe and the
Americas and close some overseas offices, Nomura representative
Kimizo Hayakawa said.
	   At the same time, the company will hire 50 new employees in Asia
outside Japan to strengthen securities operations in Taiwan and the
Philippines, he said.
	   As of the end of September, Nomura employed 4,600 people outside
Japan, including 1,400 in North and South America and 2,300 in
Europe.
	   Through the planned job cuts, to be carried out by March 1999,
the company hopes to reduce fixed overseas costs by 30 billion yen
(dlrs 259 million), targeting overseas businesses that sustained
big losses in the first half of fiscal 1998.
	   Nomura announced in October that it would cut 2,000 jobs from
its 13,000-strong domestic work force by 2001 and close about 20
percent of its Japanese retail outlets to cope with the nation's
economic recession.
	   At that time, the company reported 207.2 billion yen (dlrs 1.76
billion) in losses, mostly from foreign operations, for the first
half of fiscal 1998.
	    &UR; (tz-buros)
