<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Suharto </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian president orders end to Suharto investigation before
</HEADLINE>
June
 &UR; With Indonesia-Corruption

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ President B.J. Habibie on Wednesday
ordered state prosecutors to wrap up their corruption investigation
of former authoritarian leader Suharto before national elections in
June.
	   The statement was unlikely to appease student protesters who
have been pressing for an immediate trial of Suharto, who quit in
May after riots and protests against his rule.
	   Critics believe Habibie, whose career in the government
flourished under the tutelage of his predecessor, is too
compromised to push hard for a thorough investigation of the wealth
of 77-year-old Suharto.
	   Suharto is alleged to have helped his six children build
business empires by granting them tax breaks, government contracts
and other official perks. He denies any wrongdoing.
	   Habibie gave a deadline for the investigation one day after the
government announced that corrupt business practices, largely by
the family and associates of Suharto, cost Indonesia as much as
dlrs 580 million over the last five years.
	   ``The president has today instructed state officials to
accomplish the investigation of former President Suharto before the
general election in June,'' Information Minister Yunus Yosfiah said
after a Cabinet meeting.
	   Habibie scheduled the parliamentary elections as part of a
program of political reforms, but students say he is not moving
fast enough on democratic change.
	   Also Tuesday, Attorney General Andi Mohamad Ghalib warned
witnesses in the Suharto case that they could face charges if they
give misleading information to prosecutors.
	   Suharto's credibility was eroded in part by allegations of
official graft at a time when Indonesia's economy was buckling
under the worst financial crisis in decades. Millions of people
have lost their jobs and inflation has soared.
</TEXT>
