<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Summary,1566 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
An overnight summary of Caribbean news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; MARTINIQUE: Police unblock port _ again _ as workers continue
protest &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   FORT-DE-FRANCE, Martinique (AP) _ Police on Tuesday cleared
angry banana workers from a back entrance of Martinique's main port
as exporters rushed to move shipments blocked for weeks by
protesters' barricades.
	   The workers continued to block the port's main entrance with a
weighted freight container. Police reported no injuries or arrests.
	   About 200 banana workers struck Nov. 21 to demand raises. They
agreed Dec. 19 to remove the barricades, but raised them again
after labor negotiations fell through on Dec. 22.
	   On Monday, police cleared the back entrance long enough for
freight companies to move about 300 containers of goods ranging
from clothing to groceries. As soon as they left, the protesters
resumed the blockade.
	   About 4,200 containers are stranded on the port, said
Jean-Claude Lubin, manager of the Martinique Chamber of Commerce.
He said the protesters struck as retailers were gearing up for the
lucrative holiday business season.
	   ``Several companies will face financial obstacles and file for
bankruptcy because of the strike,'' Lubin told the newspaper
France-Antilles.
	   Companies have lost about dlrs 200 million (1 billion French
francs) because of the barricades, said Daniel Robin, president of
the Regional Union of Small Companies.
	   On Dec. 18, hundreds of company managers gathered in front of
the government's prefecture offices to stage a counter-protest
against the workers.
 &UR; TRINIDAD: Fugitive suffocated in jetliner's wheel well, coroner
says
	   PORT-OF-SPAIN, Trinidad (AP) _ Antiguan fugitive Trevor Jacobs
suffocated while stowing away in the landing gear well of a BWIA
jetliner, coroners in Trinidad said Tuesday.
	   Pathologist Ramnath Chandu Lal of the Trinidad Forensic Science
Center said Trevor Jacobs, a 30-year-old former police officer,
died from lack of air at high altitude during the flight from
Antigua to Trinidad.
	   Jacobs' frozen body was found Dec. 22 by workers doing
maintenance on the Lockheed 1011 in a hangar at Trinidad's Piarco
International Airport. It apparently had frozen in temperatures
near -40 degrees Fahrenheit (-40 degrees Celsius) at the airplane's
cruising altitude.
	   The flight began in Toronto, and police believe Jacobs climbed
aboard the aircraft during a stopover in Antigua.
	   Jacobs was wanted by Antiguan authorities on charges of
kidnapping 60-year-old Donna Pietracupa on Oct. 7. Pietracupa was
later released unharmed.
 &UR; PUERTO RICO: Referendum winners claim governor fudging results
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Opponents claim Gov. Pedro
Rossello, an advocate of U.S. statehood for Puerto Rico, is using
government ads to gloss over his defeat in a Dec. 13 referendum on
the issue.
	   The opposition Popular Democratic Party complained Tuesday to
the Puerto Rico Elections Commission and the Comptroller's Office
about State Department ads that imply statehood won.
	   ``The government of Pedro Rossello is demonstrating its
disregard for the democratic processes and the sentiment of the
majority of the people,'' Sen. Antonio Fas Alzamora said in the
newspaper El Nuevo Dia.
	   The ads claim that through the vote, the Puerto Ricans are
urging the U.S. Congress to end ``100 years of political
subordination'' and clear up the island's ambiguous relationship
with the United States.
	   It lists U.S. statehood coming in first with 728,157 votes,
followed by independence with 39,838 votes.
	   But the winner in the referendum was a ``none of the above''
protest vote backed by supporters of the status quo. It got 787,900
votes, or 50.3 percent, compared to 46.5 percent for U.S.
statehood.
	   The ads list the ``none of the above'' option at the bottom,
grouped with totals for ``null and void'' and ``blank ballots.''
	   Last week, the Elections Commission certified statehood's loss,
despite appeals from Rossello's New Progressive Party.
 &UR; UNITED STATES: Bahamians arrested in drug bust
	   SALEM, New Hampshire (AP) _ Police seized more than four pounds
(two kilos) of cocaine and arrested three men as part of an
undercover drug bust in the northeastern state of New Hampshire.
	   Tracey Swann, 28, of Tallmadge, Ohio, and Meriden, Connecticut;
Maurice Barr, 30, of the Bahamas and Meriden; and Kendall
Barr-Smith, 28, of the Bahamas were arrested Monday night and
charged with selling cocaine, a felony.
	   They were being held on dlrs 250,000 cash bail each, pending
arraignment Tuesday in Salem District Court.
	   All three men were from the Bahamas, and state police were
working with the Immigration and Naturalization Service to figure
out their residency status. If convicted, they could be deported.
	   State police said a trooper was able to infiltrate the group of
large-scale drug traffickers.
	   After a month of undercover work, the trooper arranged to buy
two kilograms of cocaine, or 4.4 pounds, for dlrs 37,000 from
Swann, who acted as the middleman, state police narcotics officers
said.
	   Barr-Smith, the group's leader, got the drugs in the Bahamas and
arranged for them to be delivered to the United States through
Florida, state police said. Barr acted as the lookout man and
bodyguard.
 &UR; UNITED STATES: Smuggled Cubans land in South Florida
	   MIAMI (AP) _ At least 35 more Cubans landed in Florida early
Tuesday, bringing to 117 the number of immigrants smuggled into the
United States since Friday.
	   Miami Beach police reported nine people ashore Tuesday in trendy
South Beach, said Border Patrol Assistant Chief Daniel Geoghegan.
Less than an hour later, police on Key Biscayne reported 20
arrivals. Monroe County officials called from the Florida Keys
about four hours after that to say that six Cuban men had been
found near Marathon.
	   ``They're all being smuggled professionally,'' Geoghegan said
Tuesday.
	   The 35, including some children, were taken to the U.S.
Immigration and Naturalization Service's Krome Detention Center
west of Miami. Geoghegan said one boat was recovered, but officials
weren't immediately sure who owned it or who was operating it.
	   Earlier, 46 Cubans, 30 Haitians and six Jamaicans were been
picked up at eight sites from West Palm Beach to Key West in the
days just after Christmas.Twelve children were included among the
three groups.
	   One person required medical attention after complaining of chest
pains. All others were reported to be in good condition.
	   Miami Border Patrol Assistant Chief Keith Roberts would not say
how many alleged smugglers were among those caught, nor what
happened to the would-be immigrants. Immigrants pay thousands of
dollars to smugglers so they can reach the U.S. shore.
	   Last Tuesday, Border Patrol agents intercepted nine Haitians who
scrambled from a speedboat in a North Miami canal to a waiting
truck. Earlier this month, a speedboat overloaded with Cubans
capsized near the Florida Keys and 14 people drowned.
 &UR; PUERTO RICO: Local stocks rose in 1998 as interest rates dipped
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Stocks of publicly traded Puerto
Rican companies, most of them banks, soared in 1998 because of
lower interest rates, financial experts say.
	   The Puerto Rico Stock Index, a basket that includes most of the
public companies on the island, rose 36 percent during the year to
8,237 as of Dec. 24, the San Juan Star reported Wednesday.
	   But experts said the increases were due to the Federal Reserve
Bank's lowering of interest rates, since six of the 11 companies in
the index are banks.
	   ``It's not like the Dow, which is a representative sample of all
types of businesses,'' said Todd Savastano, branch compliance
manager for brokerage firm Samuel Ramirez and Co. ``When rates go
down, people refinance mortgages and banks make money. So this is
not really a good indicator of the economy in general.''
	   The largest gain during the year was CoreComm, the local branch
of Cellular One, which saw its stock price nearly quadruple from
dlrs 4.87 on Jan. 2 to dlrs 18.75 on Dec. 24.
	   Banks R &AMP; G Financial Corp. and Doral Financial Group saw their
stock prices rise 117 percent and 82 percent, respectively.
	   Firstbank of Puerto Rico posted a gain of 67 percent, while
competitors Popular Inc., WesternBank and Oriental Financial gained
between 16 and 27 percent each.
 &UR; SURINAME: President to visit Cuba Jan. 11
	   PARAMARIBO, Suriname (AP) _ Surinamese President Jules
Wijdenbosch will visit Cuba on Jan. 11, the government announced
Tuesday.
	   Wijdenbosch, whose South American country is the second-poorest
in the Western Hemisphere after Haiti, is facing increasing
pressure to resign and has been seeking support from other leaders
in the region.
	   Cuba, meanwhile, has courted Suriname as part of its push to
become a member of the 15-member Caribbean Community trade group.
	   Wijdenbosch's visit is to ``contribute to the aim of deepening
the relationship'' between the two countries, the government said.
	   Cuban President Fidel Castro has been invited to Suriname next
year, it said.
</TEXT>
