<SLUG> BC-Kyrgyzstan-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kyrgyzstan's new prime minister appoints Cabinet
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Kyrgyzstan's new prime minister unveiled his
Cabinet on Wednesday, a week after the old government of the
Central Asian nation resigned, a news report said.
	   The previous Cabinet quit on Dec. 23 after President Askar
Akayev accused it of incompetence in dealing with the nation's
economic problems.
	   Prime Minister Zhumabek Ibraimov, himself approved by parliament
only days ago, appointed new ministers in trade, industry and
finance, among others, the Interfax news agency said.
	   A number of officials, including the ministers of national
security, foreign affairs, health and justice, all retained their
posts, according to Interfax.
	   Kyrgyzstan, a mountainous agricultural nation, posted modest
economic growth in 1998, according to government figures. But the
country suffers from high inflation, a trade deficit, and a
weakening currency, and has seen little economic development since
the 1991 Soviet breakup.
	   (nw/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
