<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Stocks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Shares down ahead of New Year break
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Share prices in Hong Kong closed lower
Wednesday in lackluster trading ahead of the year-end holidays.
	   The blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 104.53 points, or 1 percent,
to close at 10,121.44.
	   Turnover climbed to 1.96 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs
251 million) from Tuesday's 1.33 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S.
dlrs 171 million).
	   Since last week, the Hang Seng has bounced in a narrow range
just above the benchmark 10,000-point support level. The Hang Seng
fell 0.5 percent on Tuesday.
	   The index rose as high as 10,266.21 early in the session,
following a rise in the futures market, but it slipped later as
investors sold shares for cash ahead of the long weekend.
	   The market closes for the year at midday Thursday and reopens
Monday.
	   A slight recovery in market volume showed that retail and
institutional investors were trying to sell their stock holdings
before the holidays, said Johnson Hui, research head at BOCI
Securities Ltd.
	   There was little buying interest ahead of the introduction of
the European Union's new single currency, the euro, which begins
trading on Monday, Hui said.
	   Among the most active blue chips, banking giant HSBC Holdings,
which dominates the index, lost 1.50 Hong Kong dollars to 195.50.
Its affiliate, Hang Seng Bank, also lost 1.50 to 69.50.
	   Property company Cheung Kong (Holdings) inched up 25 Hong Kong
cents to 56.75. But its associate Hutchison Whampoa closed down 25
cents at 54.50. 	   
</TEXT>
