<SLUG> BC-India-Sri Lanka,0354 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sri Lanka yet to act on international mediation offers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ Sri Lanka has yet to decide on
international mediation offers to settle the 15-year-old ethnic
conflict with Tamil Tiger rebels, President Chandrika Kumaratunga
was quoted Wednesday as saying.
	   But Sri Lanka will not again seek India's help, as it did in the
1980s when Indian troops became embroiled in the conflict and
ultimately withdrew after heavy casualties, she said.
	   Sri Lanka has received many offers from different countries and
international organizations. ``We will decide when the time
arises,'' Kumaratunga told a group of senior Indian journalists on
Tuesday.
	   She flew home Wednesday after three days in New Delhi during
which she signed an agreement setting up a free trade area between
the two countries.
	   Kumaratunga said her peace plan offering autonomy to the
country's nine provinces, including the Tamil-dominated north, was
widely favored by the people. But she accused the main opposition
party of blocking its adoption in Parliament, where she lacks the
required two-thirds majority.
	   Tamil rebels are fighting for a separate homeland for minority
Tamils, accusing the majority Sinhalese of widespread
discrimination in education and jobs. More than 50,000 people have
been killed.
	   India's previous involvement in the conflict stems from its
geographic proximity and the fact that Sri Lankan Tamils share a
common language and culture with those living on the southern
India.
	   Asked about the possibility of resumption of peace process with
Tamil Tigers, Kumaratunga said the LTTE must agree to certain
conditions if the dialogue were to be resumed.
	   She didn't elaborate, but in a recent interview with Frontline
magazine she said the Tigers must agree to a time frame so that
negotiations will not drag on and allow the guerrilla army to
regroup. An earlier demand for the rebels to surrender some arms
has been dropped.
	   The last round of peace talks broke down after three months in
1995. Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 18.5 million
people.
</TEXT>
