<HEADLINE>
Turkish troops kill 10 Kurdish rebels in southeast
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DIYARBAKIR, Turkey (AP) _ Troops killed 10 Kurdish rebels in
clashes in southeastern Turkey, authorities announced Wednesday.
	   The clashes between the Turkish army and rebels of the Kurdistan
Workers Party, or PKK, took place in the provinces of Diyarbakir
and Batman. Authorities did not say when the fighting took place.
	   Despite pledges to end violence by PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan,
fighting continues in the southeast, where the rebels have been
waging a 14-year-old war for autonomy.
	   Ocalan was detained in Rome last month. Turkey, which holds him
responsible for the deaths of tens of thousands of people, wants
him extradited for trial on terrorism charges, but Italy says it
cannot extradite him because Turkey has the death penalty.
	   On Tuesday, the National Security Council, which includes
Turkey's top civilian and military leaders, reiterated its
determination to fight the PKK.
