<SLUG> BC-Russia-Yeltsin </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin calls for program to combat extremism
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ President Boris Yeltsin called Wednesday for the
government to combat political and religious extremism in the wake
of several anti-Semitic outbursts by Russian politicians.
	   Yeltsin issued instructions to Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov
and several other senior officials, calling on them to draw up a
program to oppose extremism, presidential spokesman Dmitry
Yakushkin told Russian news agencies.
	   The brief reports did not specify what sorts of measures Yeltsin
envisioned.
	   Several Communist Party leaders have made anti-Semitic remarks
in recent months, and a number of smaller political movements
routinely preach anti-Semitism.
	   Many mainstream politicians, as well as religious leaders and
human rights activists, have denounced the remarks by the Communist
Party officials. Several prominent Russian businessmen and
politicians have even called for banning the Communist Party,
saying it had evolved into fascism.
	   Russian authorities have said they are investigating the
anti-Semitic statements, but have not prosecuted any of the
Communist officials.
	   Meanwhile, Yeltsin also planned to meet Wednesday with his chief
of staff Nikolai Bordyuzha at Gorky-9, the country residence
outside Moscow where Yeltsin has spent much of his time in recent
months.
	   (gm/nw)
