<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Privatization </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ukraine's privatization revenues in 1998 far below target
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Ukraine has raised less than half of its
planned privatization revenues in 1998, partly because of problems
caused by Russia's financial crisis, a news report said Wednesday.
	   The State Property Fund had channeled 422 million hryvna (dlrs
123 million) to the state budget as of Tuesday, far below the 1
billion hryvna (dlrs 292 million) the government originally planned
for the year, according to the fund's acting chairman, Vadym
Vasyliev.
	   Vasyliev said privatization efforts this year were hindered by
neighboring Russia's financial crisis, which sent aftershocks into
Ukraine's economy and scared foreign investors away from its shaky
financial markets.
	   Still, privatization results were better than in previous years.
	   The government received only 70 million hryvna (dlrs 20 million)
from state property sales in 1997, Vasyliev said, according to the
Interfax news agency.
	   He said the government hopes to draw investors back to Ukraine
next year by offering them controlling stakes in several
enterprises.
	   Vasyliev did not name the companies, but was apparently
referring to the former Soviet republic's energy giants, which the
government was preparing to sell this year. The sale was delayed
because of the financial crisis.
	   Ukraine also wants to sell its telecommunications monopoly, but
preparations for the auction are not expected to be complete until
2000.
	   The government has set its privatization revenue target at 800
million hryvna (dlrs 233 million) for 1999.
	   (vl/nw/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
