<HEADLINE>
Pakistani authorities allow Bhutto to travel abroad on court order
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) _ Pakistani authorities allowed former
prime minister Benazir Bhutto to board a Dubai-bound flight on
Wednesday, days after they barred her from leaving the country, an
official from her party said.
	   Bhutto left for Dubai on Wednesday, said Munawar Suharwardi, a
spokesman of Bhutto's Pakistan Peoples' Party.
	   On Monday, authorities prevented Bhutto from going to Dubai,
saying she may not leave because of corruption cases against her.
	   Lahore High Court on Tuesday gave permission for her to leave.
	   ``It is a victory of justice,'' Bhutto told reporters at the
airport.
	   Bhutto, the twice elected prime minister and the opposition
leader, has gone to Dubai to celebrate New Year with her three
children who are studying there.
	   Former president Farooq Leghari sacked Bhutto's government in
1996 under allegations of corruption and misrule. Bhutto and her
jailed husband Asif Ali Zardari face a number of corruption cases.
	   Bhutto has denied the charges and accuses Sharif of graft and of
victimizing the opposition.
	   There was no immediate comment from the government.
