<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Military Warning </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian military warns of stern measures in case of looting
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ The Indonesian military warned that it
might shoot looters if security deteriorates at the end of the
Islamic holy month of Ramadan, the official Antara news agency
reported Wednesday.
	   Every year, millions of people in predominately Muslim Indonesia
leave the cities to spend at least a week of holidays in their home
villages after fasting during Ramadan, which ends Jan. 18.
	   Last year, the period was marred by riots over food prices and
looting in many small towns as Indonesia's worst economic crisis in
decades kicked in. Inflation has soared and millions of people have
lost their jobs.
	   The Southeast Asian nation of 200 million endured deadly riots
this year that reached a peak in May shortly before the turbulent
ouster of former authoritarian President Suharto. Some 1,200 people
died in several days of violence in Jakarta.
	   Since then, ethnic and religious tensions have risen and student
protesters have been pressed for swifter political reforms in
sometimes violent demonstrations.
	   Lt. Gen. Fachrul Razi, a military security chief, said at least
50 places on the main island of Java and the tourist island of Bali
had been identified as possible areas of unrest during celebrations
to mark the New Year and the end of Ramadan.
	   Antara quoted Razi as saying Tuesday that soldiers would crack
down on criminals and rioters if they threatened the safety of
others. Measures included orders to shoot looters on the spot, he
said.
	   He said security forces were guarding highways on Java's
northern and southern coasts after reports that trucks carrying
goods had been looted. Troops will also be deployed in areas of
Jakarta and other cities where crime has been on the rise.
	   Brig. Gen. Togar Manatar Sianipar, a national police spokesman,
said police have arrested 175 people suspected of looting across
Java in recent weeks.
	   The transport ministry predicted that the number of people
returning to their hometowns next month will be 16,922,000, down 8
percent from earlier this year. Many cash-strapped people can no
longer afford to go to their villages.
</TEXT>
