<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Land Claims </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Looming deadline sees flood of land claims in SAfrica
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ Government officials have been
swamped by a flood of land claims ahead of a Thursday deadline to
reclaim property confiscated during white rule.
	   Officials at the Department of Land Affairs told the Cape Times
newspaper Wednesday that some regional offices had taken more than
1,000 calls in recent days from people seeking to press their
claims.
	   Land Affairs Director-General Geoff Budlender said the rush
would see a total of about 40,000 claims registered by the cut-off
point.
	   Colonial governments and then apartheid rulers confiscated the
best land for whites, crowding millions of blacks into tiny tribal
homelands unable to support such large populations.
	   During 1994's all-race elections which ended apartheid, the
prospect of giving land back to poor blacks was a key factor in
sweeping the African National Congress into power.
	   However, progress has been slow and dogged by legal
complications. So far only 27 claims have been processed by the
Commission on Restitution of Land.
	   Processing all the claims, some of which date back to 1913, is
expected to take at least five years.
	   Some black opposition politicians have criticized the slow
progress and called on the ANC to revoke the deadline.
	   ``Those who dispossessed our people did not have a time frame to
dispossess them,'' said Ngila Muendane, general secretary of the
black nationalist Pan-Africanist Congress.
	   (ph/djw)	   
</TEXT>
