<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge-VIPS, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nice hotel, tours, beaches: Khmer Rouge leaders get VIP treatment
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS name of hotel, 3rd graf
 &UR; By KER MUNTHIT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Relaxing in a luxury hotel, planning
tours and a beach holiday, two Khmer Rouge leaders basked in VIP
treatment Wednesday in the capital they emptied of people in 1975
to launch a reign of terror.
	   Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea are widely believed responsible for
crimes against humanity. But since arriving Tuesday in Phnom Penh
to be greeted by Prime Minister Hun Sen under guarantees they will
not be prosecuted, they've been living the good life.
	   On Wednesday, they awoke in crisp sheets at the Royal Phnom Penh
Hotel, had breakfast in the stylish Thai restaurant and set about a
busy day of meetings that included Boutros Boutros-Ghali, a former
U.N. secretary general.
	   Their families embarked on a tour of the capital in luxury cars,
viewing temples and palaces that they last saw 20 years ago when
the Vietnamese army toppled the Khmer Rouge regime.
	   In coming days, they plan to visit the historic Angkor temples
in the north, the Sihanoukville seaside resort in the south, and
their home provinces before settling in at an ex-stronghold,
Pailin.
	   Not all staff at the hotel, where lodging runs from dlrs 120 to
dlrs 540 per night, are pleased at the lavish treatment.
	   ``I'm very disappointed,'' said a hotel security guard, speaking
on condition of anonymity for fear of losing his job. ``I don't
think soldiers who lost their legs to defend the country enjoy the
same treatment given to these people here.''
	   Well-groomed and neatly dressed, the leaders and their families
resemble upper-class urban Cambodians. In 1975, they would have
worn the black pajamas that became a revolutionary symbol.
	   The Khmer Rouge emptied Phnom Penh and all other cities after
taking power _ even forcing hospital patients onto the roads _ and
marched the populations at gunpoint to rural slave labor camps.
	   As many as 2 million people _ one Cambodian in five _ died of
overwork, starvation, disease or systematic executions.
	   The Khmer Rouge waged a long civil war after being ousted. Hun
Sen has justified pardoning surviving leaders in the interests of
peace, but the movement is extinct anyway and many feel the Khmer
Rouge are getting off too lightly.
	   ``It will set a bad precedent,'' said Chhay Yi Heang, dean of
philosophy at the University of Phnom Penh. ``Those who used to
kill will continue to kill in future because they will believe they
can be easily pardoned.''
</TEXT>
