<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Japan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China concerned over Japanese satellites
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China expressed concern Wednesday that Japanese
plans to launch military satellites and research an anti-missile
system with the United States could affect security in Asia.
	   Japan's Cabinet has approved a plan to launch four surveillance
satellites by 2002, apparently to monitor North Korea's weapons
program. U.S. and Japanese officials have also decided to study a
regional missile defense system.
	   ``China is deeply concerned about the political and military
connotation of the aforementioned moves, as well as their possible
impact on regional and global security,'' Chinese Foreign Ministry
spokesman Zhu Bangzao said in a statement carried by the official
Xinhua News Agency.
	   Zhu warned that the development of a ``strategic arms system''
could ``spark arms races and harm both the global strategic balance
and stability.''
	   ``China sincerely hopes Japan will strictly abide by a defense
policy limited to its own territory and coastal waters, and adhere
to a peaceful development path,'' Zhu said.
</TEXT>
