<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yugoslavia seeks to have Kosovo rebels declared terrorists
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES with top Serb official in Kosovo saying
government will fight KLA, Kosovo reported quiet; trims &QL; 
 &UR; By VESELIN TOSHKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ A top government official in Kosovo
warned in remarks published Wednesday that Serbia is running out of
patience with ethnic Albanian rebels and suggested it could launch
another large-scale action against them.
	   Veljko Odalovic, the province's leading official, accused the
Kosovo Liberation Army of taking advantage of an October truce to
take positions abandoned by withdrawing Serbian police and Yugoslav
army.
	   ``We have to defend our state, its integrity and people ... with
or without the international community,'' said Odalovic in an
interview with the Belgrade daily Glas. ``There will be problems,
but we will punish the last terrorist.''
	   Odalovic's comments came amid growing fears that the October
truce, mediated by American diplomats, could collapse altogether.
Four days of fierce fighting last week in northern Kosovo claimed
at least 15 lives and sent thousands fleeing.
	   Serb officials accuse the KLA of triggering the clashes by
attacking police and army in Kosovo. Yugoslavia, formed of Serbia
and Montenegro, on Tuesday urged the United Nations to declare the
KLA a terrorist organization and crack down on their support
network abroad.
	   The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which
is monitoring the Kosovo truce, has sent an additional 100
international observers to the province. They will bring to about
700 the number of Americans, Canadians and Europeans trying to ease
tensions in Kosovo.
	   An OSCE spokesman said the province was quiet Wednesday. On
Tuesday Serb sources reported that the bodies of five ethnic
Albanians were found in three different locations in Kosovo. It was
not clear who killed them.
	   Odalovic accused the independence-seeking rebels of trying to
frighten the minority Serbs into leaving Kosovo and create an
ethnically pure Albanian land. Ethnic Albanians make up some 90
percent of the population in Kosovo, a province in southern Serbia,
while the Serb population has decreased in the past decades.
	   ``There can be only one state here, one authority, one police
and one army. There is no space for any paramilitary forces,'' said
Odalovic, referring to the ethnic Albanians' struggle to form their
own state in Kosovo since Serbia revoked their autonomy in 1989.
	   ``We are not asking anything else from the international
community, but to let us use our legitimate right'' to crack down
on the KLA, said Odalovic.
	   A Serb crackdown against KLA earlier this year claimed over
1,000 lives and left some 300,000 people homeless. Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic ended it in the face of the threat of
NATO airstrikes.
	   NATO has said it is ready to act in fighting in Kosovo flares up
again.
	   Acknowledging ``problems and limits,'' Odalovic still said ``we
cannot stand by and watch crimes being committed.''
	   ``People are not safe in their homes, at work, schools or bars.
That is something which has pushed our patience beyond limits,''
said Odalovic.
	   Yugoslavia's Serb-led government claims the ethnic Albanian
Kosovo Liberation Army is a terrorist organization which should be
branded as such by world leaders in order to restrict its support
from Albanian expatriate communities in Switzerland, Germany and
elsewhere.
	   Yugoslavia's foreign minister Zivadin Jovanovic claimed Tuesday
the rebels have carried out 470 attacks since the October
agreement, including the killing of ethnic Albanians loyal to the
government.
	   (jg/dc)
</TEXT>
