<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Recession </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong Monetary Authority head sees difficult year ahead
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TARA SUILEN DUFFY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ After hitting the worst recession in years,
banks in Hong Kong face an even more difficult new year, the head
of the de-facto central bank warned Wednesday.
	   Joseph Yam, chief executive of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority,
also told reporters the authority is on ``full alert'' for another
potential attack on its currency, the Hong Kong dollar.
	   ``Although the economy is expected to recover somewhat in 1999
from the rather depressed state of 1998, the banking scene is
likely to get more difficult next year'' as the problems in the
territory's corporations catch up with the banks that lent them
money, Yam said in a year-end press conference.
	   Yam said he expected to see a slight increase in bad debts as
companies that ran into trouble this year find themselves unable to
repay existing loans.
	   ``I won't actually be surprised if one or two of the banks this
year report a loss,'' for their activities in 1998, he said, but
dismissed the possibility of any banks becoming insolvent.
	   After facing the ``most difficult year in monetary history,''
the de-facto central bank will be watching out for possible renewed
speculative attacks on the Hong Kong dollar by hedge funds. In
August, investors aggressively sold the Hong Kong dollar, forcing
monetary authorities to raise interest rates to preserve the
currency's fixed link with the U.S. dollar.
	   ``We have to be on full alert,'' because the speculators may try
again to force a devaluation of the Hong Kong dollar, Yam said. Yam
predicted the link to the U.S. dollar will hold _ and said the
territory will raise interest rates if necessary to preserve it.
	   The speculators who were selling the currency in August also
sold borrowed shares in the Hong Kong stock market on a bet that
prices would fall. They then cashed in when the higher interest
rates pulled shares lower, prompting a dramatic and controversial
response from Hong Kong authorities.
	   The government spent the equivalent of U.S. dlrs 15.1 billion in
an unprecedented stock buying spree and later introduced a series
of regulations to restrict speculative activity and stabilize the
markets.
	   Although the small size of Hong Kong's markets make them
susceptible to speculation, the regulations will make it more
expensive for hedge funds to attack Hong Kong stock and currency
markets, if they decide to try again, Yam said.
	   Yam also said Hong Kong may have to draw down its massive
foreign exchange reserves _ which stood at U.S. dlrs 88.6 billion
as of Nov. 30 _ to fund a budget deficit for the coming fiscal year
that begins April 1.
	   Yam also said Hong Kong officials will keep a close watch on the
new European Union single currency _ the euro _ which begins
trading Monday. Yam said the government would consider adding euros
to its assets, but probably only on a small scale.
</TEXT>
