<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian markets close mixed in year-end lull
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Asian stock markets closed mixed Wednesday in
thin trading ahead of the year-end holidays, with some rising on
overnight Wall Street gains and others slipping amid local economic
and political worries.
	   In Tokyo, the region's biggest market, prices closed the year's
last trading day slightly lower amid plunging bond prices and
political and economic uncertainties.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 4.73 points,
or 0.03 percent, to finish at 13,842.17 points. On Tuesday, it
closed up 137.84 points, or 1.01 percent.
	   The Tokyo market reopens Monday.
	   The Nikkei had a turbulent year dominated by political
indecisiveness, an oscillating yen and a shrinking economy. It rose
to a year's high of 17,264.34 points on March 2. But it was mostly
downhill from there, hitting its yearly low of 12,879.97 points on
Oct. 9.
	   When trading resumes next year, investors will be closely
monitoring talks between the ruling Liberal Democratic Party and
the opposition Liberal Party on forming a coalition government,
analysts said.
	   ``The domestic political and economic situations remain
uncertain,'' said Sachio Ishikawa, a general manager at Chuo
Securities.
	   Still, Wednesday's market got some support from Tuesday's rise
on Wall Street. The Dow Jones industrial average closed at 9,320.98
points, up 1.02 percent.
	   In the currency market, the U.S. dollar fell marginally against
the Japanese yen in lackluster trading. The dollar bought 115.20
yen in late dealings, down 0.16 yen from late Tuesday and below its
late New York level of 115.53 yen overnight.
	   In Singapore, share prices closed higher on hopes of an
eleventh-hour interest rate cut before the end of the year.
	   The Straits Times Index closed 1.2 percent higher at 1,394.70.
	   Dealers said they expected the government-controlled Development
Bank of Singapore Ltd. to pave the way for lower rates with a
half-point cut in the prime lending rate, which stands at 5.5
percent.
	   In Taipei, stock prices fell for the fifth straight session to
near four-month lows.
	   The benchmark Weighted Price Index dropped 16.24 points at
6,462.03, the lowest level since it hit 6,219.89 on Sept. 1.
	   Investors continued to sell shares amid fears of Taiwan's weak
economy and ahead of the release of December corporate sales
results, due out by Jan. 10, dealers said.
	   In Hong Kong, the blue-chip Hang Seng Index slumped 1 percent to
10,121.44 points in lackluster trading.
	   Retail and institutional investors were trying to sell their
stocks before the holidays, said Johnson Hui, research head at BOCI
Securities Ltd.
	   Elsewhere:
	   BANGKOK: Thai shares rose as local fund managers bought shares
in an effort to push up prices in their investment portfolios
before the year end. The SET index rose 1.1 percent at 351.81
points.
	   JAKARTA: Indonesian shares closed a tumultuous year higher on
late buying in tobacco and mining blue chips. The JSX Composite
Index closed up 1.305 points at 398.038.
	   KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares finished mixed as investment
banks bought blue chips while retail investors sold their
second-tier holdings. The benchmark Composite Index rose 8.33
points to 574.56.
	   SYDNEY: Australian stocks ended higher, pushed along by rises in
blue-chip stocks such as Commonwealth Bank of Australia, News Corp.
and AMP Ltd. The All Ordinaries index closed up 0.6 percent at
2,784.2.
	   WELLINGTON: New Zealand's benchmark NZSE-40 capital index
finished lower, led by a fall in market heavyweight Telecom Corp.
of New Zealand. It shed 5.11 points to 2,105.23.
	   Markets in the Philippines and South Korea were closed
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
