<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Tajikistan-Fighting, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fighting in Tajik capital sends residents fleeing
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: UPDATES with additional details throughout. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   DUSHANBE, Tajikistan (AP) _ Rival groups waged a fierce gun
battle Wednesday in the center of Tajikistan's capital, leaving at
least two people dead and sending residents fleeing for cover.
	   The clash erupted along the main street in Dushanbe between two
feuding factions that control territory in the eastern part of
Dushanbe, witnesses said.
	   Supporters of the two groups opened fire outside the National
Reconciliation Commission, which was established to bring together
the combatants in the country's 5-year-old civil war, which
formally ended last year.
	   About 20 gunmen on each side took part in the shootout, which
damaged vehicles and buildings, witnesses said.
	   Both factions, led by commanders Rakhmon Sanginov and Ali
Pirmakh, had been expected to take part in meetings at the
commission, witnesses said.
	   At least two people were killed and three wounded in the
fighting, which drove civilians from the streets. The shooting
ended after about 45 minutes, and police restored order, witnesses
and Russian news agencies said.
	   Since the end of the civil war, ex-rebels have begun to serve in
the government, the army, and the National Reconciliation
Commission.
	   However, there are still frictions among the various groups, and
some renegade warlords have refused to recognize the peace
agreement.
	   Russia has about 25,000 troops in the Central Asian nation to
support President Emomali Rakhmonov, but there was no indication
that they were involved in the fighting.
	   (gm/nw) 	   
</TEXT>
