w2556 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Taiwan-Cambodia-Waste     12-30 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Cambodia-Waste Scandal </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan company to conduct own tests on waste dumped in Cambodia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ The plastics company that shipped some
3,000 tons of mercury-laden waste to Cambodia is dispatching a team
of investigators on Thursday to conduct its own tests into the
material that caused a deadly scandal.
	   Formosa Plastics Corp. has taken issue with earlier tests taken
in Cambodia, including one by an environmental group, that found
illegal levels of mercury in the waste.
	   A dock worker died a day after cleaning the hold of the ship
that brought the waste, and four more people were killed in road
accidents in a panic-stricken exodus from the area.
	   The team organized by Formosa Plastics, to be led by a Taiwanese
lawmaker, Tseng Chen-nung, will collect samples and conduct tests
to decide whether or not the waste is toxic, executives said
Wednesday.
	   Cambodia has accused Taiwan of trying to dump toxic waste in
poor countries. The disclosure of the dump, discovered near the
port of Sihanoukville two weeks ago, sparked riots by residents who
accused officials of allowing the illegal shipment.
	   On Monday, Taiwanese officials said an analysis conducted on
samples taken by an environmental group showed the waste was more
toxic than allowed by law _ and they ordered Formosa Plastics to
bring the material back to Taiwan.
	   The mercury emission level of the waste was 0.284 parts per
million, compared to the safety standard of 0.2 ppm, according to
the analysis. The level refers to the mercury that can be emitted
from the waste when placed in a natural environment.
	   Formosa Plastics questioned the analysis and decided to conduct
its own sampling.
	   Meanwhile, Taiwanese newspapers reported another analysis made
by a Japanese expert showed the waste had a mercury content level
as high as 4,000 parts per million and could be hazardous to
humans.
	   But Lee Chih-chun, general manager at Formosa Plastics, said the
total mercury content cannot indicate whether the waste is
hazardous.
	   Reports from Cambodia said there were 3,000 tons of the waste,
but Formosa Plastics put the figure at around 2,800 tons.
	   Meanwhile, Wu Yih-hsiung, deputy director of Taiwan's
Environmental Protection Bureau, said Formosa Plastics should
either take back the waste or send it to the United States or a
European country for proper treatment.
	   ``The waste should be sent to a country which has the capability
to handle it, not another poor country,'' Wu said.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
