<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Fog </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fog disrupts air traffic in Warsaw
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Thick fog over Warsaw delayed most
outgoing flights Wednesday and forced airlines to reroute incoming
flights.
	   Anna Jozwik, spokeswoman for Warsaw's Okecie airport, said the
cloud level was low at 90 meters (300 feet) and visibility poor.
	   Planes were rerouted to other airports in Poland, such as Krakow
or Poznan, while a Delta flight from New York City landed in the
Czech capital of Prague.
	   Airline authorities canceled all domestic flights, she added.
	   Jozwik said 16 international flights had left Warsaw by noon,
all behind schedule.
	   Despite traffic disruption, only about 100 people, many of them
booked on the Delta return flight for New York City, were waiting
for departure at the airport. Jozwik said there are generally few
passengers at the turn of the year.
	   The weather was expected to improve by early afternoon.
 &UR; (ajs-pfg)
</TEXT>
