w2567 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-KhmerRouge-B     12-30 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge-Boutros-Ghali </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former U.N. chief urges respect over Khmer Rouge deal
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Former U.N. Secretary General
Boutros Boutros-Ghali said Wednesday that the world must respect
Cambodia's decision not to try two Khmer Rouge leaders for
genocide.
	   Boutros-Ghali said that as long as the United Nations is unable
to create an international tribunal to prosecute crimes against
humanity, national law will prevail.
	   ``You need an international intervention,'' Boutros-Ghali told a
news conference. ``It has to come from the forum which exists,
which is the United Nations.''
	   Boutros-Ghali, in Phnom Penh to promote the French language as
head of the International Francophone Organization, met one of the
Khmer Rouge leaders, Khieu Samphan.
	   ``It was quite interesting to know what had changed,''
Boutros-Ghali remarked. ``How I was not successful and a new
government was successful in finding a reconciliation.''
	   Boutros-Ghali was secretary general in the early 1990s during
the U.N.-organized, dlrs 2 billion project to hold elections and
bring peace to Cambodia.
	   The Khmer Rouge boycotted the vote, but the elections were a key
step in bringing peace to the country after decades of strife.
	   Khieu Samphan was the official head of the bloodstained
revolutionary group, though others held real power. Nuon Chea, long
seen as the number-two behind the late Pol Pot, is with him.
	   The pair traveled Tuesday to Phnom Penh to meet Prime Minister
Hun Sen, who promised to shield them from prosecution in what he
says is a necessary step to ensure the country does not return to
civil war.
	   Deals struck with other leaders over the past two years brought
peace to nearly all of Cambodia for the first time in a generation,
but the Khmer Rouge is now nearly extinct.
	   King Norodom Sihanouk, who refused to endorse the deal, is one
of many Cambodians who believe the pair should be held to account
before an international tribunal for the deaths of as many as 2
million people under their rule from 1975 to 1979.
	   The current U.N. secretary general, Kofi Annan, dispatched a
team of legal experts to Cambodia recently to assess the
feasibility of holding such a trial. Their report is due in a few
weeks.
</TEXT>
