</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Immigrant Rules </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore announces point system to assess immigrant applications
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Immigration authorities announced Friday a
point system for assessing permanent resident applicants on their
ability to contribute to Singapore's growth and welfare.
	   It is the first time the criteria have ever been publicly
stated, said government television. The new rules take effect Jan.
2.
	   The city-state of 3.1 million people is undergoing its severest
economic crisis in more than a decade and many have complained
about the government's policy of encouraging ``foreign talent.''
	   At the same time, it was announced that work visas will not be
required for certain visitors, such as businessmen participating in
trade shows, and journalists covering specific news events.
	   Trade show participants had in the past found themselves in
Singapore illegally because they didn't know of the requirement for
work visas, said Graham Hayward, chairman of the Singapore Chamber
of Commerce.
	   Those seeking permanent residence will be judged on the basis of
points, awarded for the type of work they wish to do, how long they
want to stay, their academic qualifications, monthly salary, age
and local kinship ties. 	   
</TEXT>
