<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Croatia-US-Military </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Croatia purchases radar system from U.S. company
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) _ Croatia has purchased a dlrs 16 million
radar system for maritime surveillance from a U.S. company,
Croatian media reported Wednesday.
	   Defense Ministry officials said the contract was signed with the
Metric System Corp. just before Christmas, according to the
Vecernji List daily, which did not have further details about the
firm.
	   The system will enable Croatia to monitor its part of the
Adriatic Sea, including submarines and low-flying planes, as well
as its more than 1,000-kilometer (625-mile) -long coast.
	   Croatia's maritime space, amounting to about 32,000 square
kilometers (13,000 square miles), equals half its continental
territory.
	   Vladimir Zagorec, head of the Defense Ministry's company for
arms trade, said the radar equipment will be used by the navy and
also police, to secure a timely action when needed.
	   Vecernji List said that with the new system, ``a possibility of
aliens' entrance into our territorial waters is reduced to a
minimum.'' That should also prevent smuggling at sea, it said.
	   Croatia, which seceded from the former Yugoslav federation in
1991, has had only the radar systems it inherited from the Yugoslav
army, so the purchase was necessary, Zagorec said.
	   In addition, the systems are compatible to NATO member
countries' equipment. Croatia hopes to be admitted to NATO's
Partnership for Peace program and is trying to adjust its military
to NATO standards.
	   (sv/dc)
</TEXT>
