<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 1200 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   HONG KONG _ Asian stock markets closed mixed Wednesday in thin
trading ahead of the year-end holidays, with some rising on
overnight Wall Street gains and others slipping amid local economic
and political worries. In Tokyo, the region's biggest market,
prices closed the year's last trading day slightly lower amid
plunging bond prices and political and economic uncertainties. The
benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 4.73 points, or 0.03
percent, to finish at 13,842.17 points. On Tuesday, it closed up
137.84 points, or 1.01 percent. The Tokyo market reopens Monday.
The Nikkei had a turbulent year dominated by political
indecisiveness, an oscillating yen and a shrinking economy. It rose
to a year's high of 17,264.34 points on March 2. But it was mostly
downhill from there, hitting its yearly low of 12,879.97 points on
Oct. 9. (ASIAN MARKETS)
	   SEOUL, South Korea _ South Korea will abolish its 20-year-old
import ban on an assortment of Japanese cars and other industrial
goods by June next year, government officials said Wednesday. South
Korea currently bans the import of 48 Japanese products, including
many types of cars, as part of its effort to protect domestic
industries and fight a chronic trade imbalance with Japan. South
Korea will begin Thursday by first lifting the ban on 32 products,
including station wagons with 1- to 1.5-liter engine capacity,
jeeps with over 1.5-liter gasoline engines, as well as camcorders,
copy machines and audio components. (SKOREA-JAPAN)
	   HANOI, Vietnam _ A joint venture with Russia to build and run
Vietnam's first oil refinery has been granted an operating license,
the Vietnam News Agency reported Wednesday. The license was granted
Tuesday for the VietRoss Refinery, to be located at the small
fishing village of Dung Quat about 100 kilometers (60 miles) south
of Danang. It is expected to refine 6.5 million tons (1.88 billion
gallons) of crude oil per year, with the first phase to be
operational in 2001. The refinery is a joint venture between
Vietnam's oil and gas monopoly, PetroVietnam, and Russia's
Zarubezhneft. They signed a contract last month and are to equally
fund the projected investment capital of dlrs 1.3 billion.
(VIETNAM-REFINERY)
	   TOKYO _ Nomura Securities Co., Japan's biggest brokerage, will
cut 650 overseas jobs next year as part of a major restructuring
campaign, a company official said Wednesday. Facing massive losses
in its overseas operations, the company will shed nearly 20 percent
of its work force in Europe and the Americas and close some
overseas offices, Nomura representative Kimizo Hayakawa said. At
the same time, the company will hire 50 new employees in Asia
outside Japan to strengthen securities operations in Taiwan and the
Philippines, he said. As of the end of September, Nomura employed
4,600 people outside Japan, including 1,400 in North and South
America and 2,300 in Europe. (JAPAN-NOMURA)
	   BEIJING _ Boosted by massive state spending on public works,
China's economy grew by 7.8 percent this year but missed its
official target, according to figures released Wednesday. Growth
was down sharply from 1997, when the economy expanded by 8.8
percent. Chinese leaders had hoped for at least 8 percent this year
to create jobs for millions of workers laid off in a sweeping
overhaul of state companies. China has escaped the full impact of
the 18-month-old Asian financial crisis, but faces serious problems
of its own in trying to turn around money-losing state industries
and clean up its state-owned banking system. (ASIA-BUSINESS BRIEFS)
</TEXT>
