<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Myanmar-Obit-Tin Oo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former Myanmar ruling party leader dies
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   YANGON, Myanmar (AP) _ Brig. Gen. Tin Oo, who was once general
secretary of Myanmar's ruling party, died of a heart attack at his
home Wednesday, family members said. He was 71.
	   Tin Oo was removed from office in 1983 and sentenced to life
imprisonment for misuse of state funds and property, but was
released after six years.
	   Tin Oo was a powerful figure in military intelligence under the
rule of Gen. Ne Win, who overthrew a civilian government in 1962
and imposed one-party military rule over the country, also known as
Burma.
	   The Burma Socialist Program Party beggared what had once been
the richest country in Southeast Asia until the people revolted
against military rule in 1988.
	   The revolt was bloodily suppressed. Ne Win and his party stepped
aside in favor of a younger generation of officers who introduced a
more market-oriented economy while keeping a firm lid on dissent.
	   Tin Oo spent his retirement devoted to religion and meditation.
He is survived by his wife and three grown children.
</TEXT>
