<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0767 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of news from The Associated Press. Some items have
moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f'' category
codes:
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ A mob of 200 villagers, some armed with
machetes, tortured and killed eight Indonesian soldiers after
stopping a public bus. On Wednesday, rioters in the same area
attacked a police station and burned two police cars. The violence
in northwestern Aceh province was likely to raise tensions in a
region where the Indonesian military recently ended a decade-long
campaign against separatist rebels. Officials suspect guerrilla
followers were behind the slayings of the soldiers on Tuesday.
Accused of widespread atrocities in Aceh, the military apologized
and withdrew some troops in a conciliatory gesture after the
resignation in May of former President Suharto. However, resentment
toward the military remains deep. (INDONESIA-SOLDIERS KILLED)
	   SAN`A, Yemen _ Yemen faced a barrage of criticism Wednesday
after its troops stormed the hideout of Islamic extremist
kidnappers holding 16 Western hostages. Four of the hostages were
killed. Two other hostages were wounded during the siege near the
southern town of Mawdiyah, about 175 miles (280 kilometers) south
of the capital, San`a. The remaining 10 hostages were freed
unharmed. Three kidnappers died. Yemen's Interior Ministry blamed
the kidnappers for the deaths of the three Britons and an
Australian, one of whom died later in in a hospital. It said
security forces intervened after the kidnappers had begun killing
the hostages. But British newspapers accused the Yemeni authorities
of premature intervention in the case. (YEMEN-KIDNAPPING)
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ King Norodom Sihanouk refused Wednesday
to approve amnesty for two leaders of the genocidal Khmer Rouge,
setting up a collision course with his prime minister, who has
pledged to shield them from trial. The refusal undermines a deal
Prime Minister Hun Sen has struck with Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea
to allow them to defect and give up to his government with
assurances they will not be tried for their roles in the deaths of
as many as 2 million people. The king said he would not invoke ``my
power of amnesty for major Khmer Rouge criminals.'' However, Hun
Sen is Cambodia's most powerful man and his will amounts to law. He
controls the judiciary and security services and could simply
accord the pair a de facto pardon. The popular king's stance will
make a pardon less legitimate in the eyes of the world and many
Cambodians. But Sihanouk has no way to enforce his will.
(CAMBODIA-KHMER ROUGE)
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia _ The prosecution in the sex and
corruption trial of ousted Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim
dealt him a huge blow Wednesday when a state DNA expert positively
identified his semen on a mattress. Prosecutors are trying to prove
Anwar had sex with the wife of his former secretary, sodomized his
family driver and abused his powers to try to cover up sexual
trysts. The mattress was seized by police in July from an apartment
in a Kuala Lumpur suburb that Anwar is accused of using for secret
meetings with sex partners. (MALAYSIA-ANWAR TRIAL)
	   LUANDA, Angola _ President Jose Eduardo dos Santos ruled out
talks with the rebel group UNITA on ending the country's renewed
civil war, and described rebel leader Jonas Savimbi as a liar for
pretending to be committed to a 1994 peace pact. Dos Santos said in
a speech broadcast on state radio RNA late Tuesday that the army
had given ``the correct response'' to UNITA's failure to heed the
terms of the United Nations-brokered peace accord. Dos Santos
indicated that he will not yield to international pressure to call
off the army offensive against rebel strongholds in the central
highlands which began Dec. 4. (ANGOLA)
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ A top government official in Kosovo
warned in remarks published Wednesday that Serbia is running out of
patience with ethnic Albanian rebels and suggested it could launch
another large-scale action against them despite the possibility of
NATO intervention. Veljko Odalovic, the province's leading
official, accused the Kosovo Liberation Army of taking advantage of
an October truce to take positions abandoned by withdrawing Serbian
police and Yugoslav army. ``We have to defend our state, its
integrity and people ... with or without the international
community,'' said Odalovic in an interview with the Belgrade daily
Glas. ``There will be problems, but we will punish the last
terrorist.'' (YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO)
</TEXT>
