<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 12/30/1998 07:01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2606 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-US-ProtocolPitfal     12-30 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-US-Protocol Pitfalls,0941 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Presentation of credentials _ a sometimes tricky exercise in
</HEADLINE>
diplomacy &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos NY7, WX110 &QL; 
 &UR; By DONNA ABU-NASR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ On his first day at work, the chief of
protocol strode confidently down a White House hallway, the
Sudanese ambassador following closely behind.
	   With a flourish, James Symington opened what he thought was a
door leading to the Oval Office, where President Lyndon Johnson was
waiting to receive the new ambassador's credentials.
	   But instead of stepping into America's most famous room, the two
men found themselves in a broom closet.
	   ``It is my first time in your country,'' said a bewildered
Mohammed Amin Hussein. ``And this is my first day on the job,''
responded Symington. ``We both had a laugh and went upstairs.''
	   Broom closet fiascoes, flags flown upside down, mixed up welcome
cards. These are protocol lapses that occur despite the stiff and
highly choreographed world of diplomacy.
	   But Symington, as well as other protocol chiefs who have
supervised credentials ceremonies, says such gaffes are inevitable
and the best way to deal with them is with a sense of humor.
	   ``Without a sense of humor you're finished. There's no hope,''
said Symington.
	   The presentation of credentials is a time-honored exercise of
diplomacy that symbolizes the importance the president has for the
relationship with the envoy's country. It is also an opportunity
for new ambassadors to have what in many cases is their only
one-on-one with the president of the United States.
	   The envoys and their families emerge from the meeting with
highly prized mementos: pictures with one of the world's most
powerful men that are prominently displayed on walls, pianos and
desks.
	   Lebanon's ambassador to Washington says the day he took his wife
and two teen-age boys with him to present his credentials to
President Bill Clinton was a ``great event.''
	   ``They were very happy,'' said Mohamad Chatah, recalling the
September 1997 ceremony. ``Everybody has heard of the White House
and the Oval Office, so there's something special about being
there.''
	   All ambassadors present their credentials _ official letters
establishing them as envoys _ to the president within a few weeks
or months of their arrival in Washington irrespective of the size
of their country or its relationship with the United States.
	   Depending on who's in the White House, the ceremony has peaked
in pomp and circumstance or has been simplified to suit the
president's schedule and priorities.
	   President George Bush sent limousines to pick up the envoys, who
were offered coffee, tea and juice before meeting with him.
President Jimmy Carter usually did not send limousines, but the
envoys had lunch at the White House dining room before or after
meeting the president. The Reagan ceremony was brief, the Bush one
more choreographed and homey. Mrs. Carter and Mrs. Bush were
usually on hand, Mrs. Reagan and Mrs. Clinton have stayed out of
the proceedings.
	   The person who plans the ceremony is the chief of protocol of
the White House, who is in fact a State Department staffer and is
also an assistant secretary of state.
	   The protocol chief acts as a mayor of the diplomatic corps, said
Evan Dobelle, who served in that post under President Carter. The
job includes taking care of the envoys' safety, the education of
their children and ambassadorial residences.
	   Several former protocol chiefs look back fondly on their days as
senior diplomats and chuckle when they recount their gaffes.
	   Symington said he didn't know exactly where to take the Sudanese
ambassador but didn't want to look indecisive.
	   ``The presidential aides were smiling and looking at me ... but
they weren't particularly helpful in directing me,'' recalled
Symington.
	   Joseph Reed has had his lapses.
	   On one occasion, Reed, who served under President Bush, greeted
what he thought was the ambassador of Gabon, a former French colony
in Africa, with his best Lausanne French.
	   ``I am the ambassador of Tanzania,'' came the response in Oxford
English.
	   ``I had gotten my welcome cards mixed up,'' recalled Reed. ``It
was so awful. But then we became great friends.''
	   Another embarrassing moment came when he sent a limousine to
pick up the Benin ambassador with the Benin flag flying upside
down.
	   That African country had just had a revolution and the flag was
new.
	   ``We weren't sure which side it was. But he didn't mind,'' said
Reed.
	   President Reagan's protocol chief, Selwa ``Lucky'' Roosevelt,
found herself in a quandary one chilly day in November 1983.
	   Peter Helemisi Mtetwa, the ambassador from Swaziland, showed up
for the presentation of credentials barefoot, wearing ceremonial
dress: a sheath covering a bit more than a loincloth and a spear.
	   Secret Service officials wouldn't let him see the president with
a ``lethal weapon,'' recalled Roosevelt. As she sent her assistants
to ``please explain this was not a serious threat to the
president,'' Roosevelt delayed the ambassador's entrance long
enough for someone to go warn Reagan about the envoy's garb.
	   Mtetwa did go in to see the president, spear in hand, said
Roosevelt.
	   ``That was an exception,'' she added.
	   Dobelle, who notes ``honestly and with great pleasure ... we
didn't make any mistakes,'' said being a protocol chief for four
years was a ``real privilege.''
	   ``It's a seat to history,'' said Dobelle. ``For me it was a
terrific ride.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-US-Protocol Pitfalls; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
