<DOCNO> APW19981230.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 12/30/1998 07:20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2622 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Netherlands-Unwelcome     12-30 0316
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Netherlands-Unwelcome Refugees </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rich residents accused of setting up `apartheid' with move to bar
</HEADLINE>
refugees

<TEXT>
	   VUGHT, Netherlands (AP) _ Protesters on Wednesday accused a
group of rich residents of setting up a ``new apartheid'' by buying
a disused hospital for millions of guilders (dlrs) to prevent
asylum seekers being housed there.
	   A group of left-wing activists occupied the building known as De
Steffenberg after it was revealed Tuesday that a consortium of
residents had bought it for 3.7 million guilders (dlrs 1.9 million)
to prevent house prices in their leafy avenue plummeting.
	   ``This is like a new apartheid,'' said Socialist Party leader
Jan Marijnissen. ``People here are opting to live in a white
ghetto. It is white now and they want it to stay white.''
	   A government-funded bureau which finds accommodation for asylum
seekers had asked the municipality in this town 90 kilometers (56
miles) south of Dutch capital Amsterdam for permission to use the
former hospital to house 320 refugees pending the outcome of their
asylum requests.
	   But the residents' group wants the building to provide temporary
accommodation for elderly people forced out of their homes by
renovation work, Dutch daily De Volkskrant reported.
	   ``Their action is preventing the democratic process from taking
its course,'' Marijnissen said. He asked the government to
investigate ways of preventing similar actions in the future.
Marijnissen and 30 other protesters left the building peacefully in
the early afternoon.
	   The residents' group could not immediately be reached for
comment.
	   The Netherlands is struggling to find homes for an
ever-increasing number of refugees flooding across its borders. In
recent months, the government has set up three temporary tented
villages to house asylum seekers because all the permanent centers
are full.
	   (mc)
