<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Israel </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Minister: Egypt has no plans to sell natural gas to Israel
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Egypt's oil minister said Wednesday that the
country has no plans to open negotiations to supply natural gas to
Israel.
	   He was responding to an announcement on Tuesday in Israel that
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon instructed the country's
national electricity supplier to open talks, saying the state-run
Egyptian General Petroleum Corp. had sent a letter expressing
interest in a deal.
	   The Israeli ministry said negotiations with EGPC over price and
the quantity of gas to be supplied were to begin in the next few
days.
	   But Egyptian Oil Minister Hamdy el-Banbi said in a statement on
Wednesday that all the gas produced by EGPC was being consumed
domestically and that Egypt planned to buy more from international
companies working in Egypt.
	   ``EGPC has signed a number of agreements with foreign companies
to buy its shares for the years to come to meet increasing domestic
demands for natural gas,'' he said in the statement, which was
faxed to The Associated Press.
	   Banbi said, however, that international companies working in the
country _ including America's Amoco and the Italian Agip _ have
been in contact with Israel about gas deals.
	   ``These companies _ including Amoco and Agip _ have been trying
for years to ensure their shares in the international market,''
Banbi said. He noted they have been in contact with a number of
countries in the region, including Israel and Turkey.
	   Relations between Israel and Egypt have been strained in recent
months by the deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
	   Egypt maintains a `cold peace'' with the Jewish state with few
commercial or economic ties.
 &UR; sn-eap
</TEXT>
