w2661 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yemen-Kidnapping 6thLd-Writethru   12-30 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Kidnapping, 6th Ld-Writethru,0855 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yemen faces criticism in raid on kidnappers; four tourists, three
</HEADLINE>
kidnappers killed &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: Recasts throughout, RAISES references to kidnappers killed,
kidnappers' demands; ADDS that kidnappers were protesting
US-British airstrikes; UPDATES with condition of wounded hostages,
identity of Egyptian kidnapper. &QL; 
 &UR; By AHMAD AL-HAJ &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ Yemen faced criticism Wednesday from Britain
after its troops stormed the hideout of Islamic militant kidnappers
holding 16 Western hostages. Four of the hostages _ three Britons
and an Australian _ and three kidnappers were killed.
	   Two other hostages were wounded during the siege near the
southern town of Mawdiyah, about 175 miles (280 kilometers) south
of the capital, San`a. The remaining 10 hostages were freed
unharmed.
	   The kidnappers, members of Islamic Jihad in Yemen, had demanded
the release from prison of two of the group's leaders and were
protesting the recent U.S.-British airstrikes against Iraq, Yemeni
security officials said.
	   Yemen's Interior Ministry blamed the kidnappers for the deaths,
saying that security forces intervened after the kidnappers began
killing the hostages. The security forces also captured three of
the kidnappers, including a leader, the ministry said.
	   ``They proceeded in killing the captives after refusing any
attempts at negotiations, which led security forces to storm the
area to prevent further bloodshed and ensure the safe release of
the rest of the hostages,'' a ministry statement said.
	   But British newspapers accused Yemeni authorities of intervening
prematurely. The Daily Mail asked on the front page, ``Did our
tourists really need to die?''
	   British Ambassador Vic Henderson reportedly had pleaded with the
San`a government to do nothing ``that in any way could jeopardize
the safety of the hostages.''
	   A London-based Islamic human rights group said Tuesday that it
had contacted the kidnappers the night before and received
assurances that they would not harm the hostages.
	   ``We hold the Yemeni government responsible for the deaths. The
way the authorities handled the situation was barbaric and
irresponsible,'' said a spokesman for the Islamic Observation
Center.
	   Foreigners often are kidnapped in Yemen, large parts of which
are run by tribes. But until now the hostages usually have been
treated well and released unharmed. Tribesmen typically use
kidnappings to pressure the government into providing new roads,
water or clinics.
	   This was the first time an abduction was carried out by Islamic
militants. Security officials said the kidnappers belong to Islamic
Jihad, many of whose leaders fought Russian troops in Afghanistan.
The group is believed to have about 200 members.
	   The 16 tourists, 12 Britons, two Americans and two Australians,
were kidnapped Monday near Mawdiyah.
	   In London, the Foreign Office confirmed that three Britons _
Ruth Williamson, Margaret Whitehouse and Peter Rowe _ were killed,
but did not provide their ages or hometowns.
	   The Australian Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade said the
fourth victim was a 35-year-old man from Sydney whose name would
not be released until next of kin had been informed.
	   The tourists wounded in the clash were an American woman and a
British woman.
	   Al-Jamhouriya Hospital in the southern port of Aden said the two
wounded were women, that one was shot in the shoulder and the other
in the pelvis, and that both had lost a lot of blood.
	   Relatives of one of the women, Claire Marston of Britain, told
reporters she was in critical condition Wednesday. She was married
to Canadian-born Peter Rowe, one of the four hostages killed.
	   The surviving hostages were recovering from their ordeal at a
hotel in Aden, where British and American volunteers helped them
cope with their trauma, said David Pearce, a British Embassy
official in San`a.
	   ``They are obviously in a state of severe shock, and I mean
severe shock,'' Pearce told the British news agency Press
Association. ``They are uninjured but obviously very tired, very
stunned and in need of a good meal, a good rest and someone to talk
to. They have been through an awful experience.''
	   After the shootout, security forces detained scores of suspected
Islamic extremists, said the officials, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
	   The kidnapping began Monday when the tourists' convoy of five
vehicles was ambushed by men who opened fire on their police
escorts. The kidnappers threatened to kill the tourists if the
police did not back off, Yemeni security officials said.
	   The kidnappers demanded the release of their leader, Saleh
Haidara al-Atwi, who was detained two weeks ago in a government
crackdown on Islamic vigilantes who had been enforcing strict
Islamic rules in southern Yemen, security officials said.
	   The kidnappers also wanted the release of another leader and
were protesting the recent U.S. and British airstrikes against
Iraq, the officials said.
	   The officials identified one of the captured kidnappers as Osama
al-Masri of Egypt.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yemen-Kidnapping, 6th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
