<HEADLINE>
Fog disrupts air traffic in Warsaw
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in 6th graf with Delta flight canceled, the airline
refusing info about passengers stranded in Prague, new forecast &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Thick fog over Warsaw delayed most
outgoing flights Wednesday and forced airlines to reroute incoming
planes.
	   Anna Jozwik, spokeswoman for Warsaw's Okecie airport, said the
cloud level was low at 90 meters (300 feet) and visibility poor.
	   Planes were rerouted to other airports in Poland, such as Krakow
or Poznan, while a Delta flight from New York City landed in the
Czech capital of Prague.
	   Delta officials in Prague said all passengers were fine, but
refused to say how many were stranded and how they could get to
Warsaw.
	   After waiting more than four hours, about 80 passengers booked
on the return Delta flight from Warsaw to New York were told it was
canceled. Airline officials said they were hoping the weather
improves by Thursday so that the plane could make it from Prague to
Warsaw and then take off for New York.
	   Airline authorities also canceled all domestic flights, Jozwik
added.
	   Jozwik said 16 international flights had left Warsaw by noon,
all behind schedule.
	   Despite traffic disruption, only about 100 people were waiting
for departures at the airport. Jozwik said there are generally few
passengers at the turn of the year.
	   The weather, which already cleared in northern part of Warsaw,
was expected to improve in the airport area in late afternoon.
