<SLUG> BC-Israel-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,0404 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli soldier killed by friendly fire in Lebanon
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with commander confirming soldier was
killed by friendly fire, details, comment from soldier's mother. &QL; 
 &UR; By SARI BASHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ An Israeli army unit in southern Lebanon
mistakenly opened fire on another unit before dawn Wednesday,
killing one soldier and wounding two, an army commander said.
	   The two units had started out on patrol together in Israel's
self-declared security zone, but were separated when one group lost
its way.
	   ``The rear unit separated from the front forces and mistakenly
thought they were terrorists,'' Brig. Gen. Etti Eitan, an army
commander in the area, told Israel radio.
	   ``The rear force opened fire on the front force ... and as a
result of this, people were hurt,'' Eitan said.
	   Eitan said the rear unit had requested and received permission
from the base commander to open fire.
	   The dead soldier was identified as Staff Sgt. Ohad Zach, 19,
from the northern village of Nofit.
	   Israel has occupied the zone since 1985 to prevent cross-border
guerrilla attacks. With casualties rising, public pressure has been
mounting to withdraw Israel's 2,000 soldiers from Lebanon.
	   Zach's mother told Israel radio that army commanders had ignored
warnings from soldiers that there were problems with path-finding
and orientation within the unit.
	   ``If soldiers warn about a problem, they know what they're
saying, and commanders have to pay attention,'' she said. ``The
front shot the back, the back shot the front, and Ohad is no
more.''
	   David Bar-Illan, a senior aide to Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, said Zach's death, the 24th Israeli casualty in
Lebanon this year, did not affect the ongoing Cabinet debate over
withdrawing.
	   ``It does not change the need for safety of the people in the
Galilee,'' Bar-Illan said, referring to the section of northern
Israel that the occupied zone is designed to protect.
	   Bar-Illan denied that Israel is losing its edge in southern
Lebanon.
	   ``One soldier killed by friendly fire, if that was indeed the
case, doesn't indicate anything except that in one incident it was
a case of negligence,'' Bar-Illan said.
	   Wednesday's shooting was the second case of injuries from
friendly fire this month. Zach was to be buried later Wednesday.
</TEXT>
