<HEADLINE>
Germany defends finance minister's decision to skip Brussels
</HEADLINE>
meeting &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ The German government on Wednesday defended
Finance Minister Oskar Lafontaine's decision not to attend a
European Union meeting at which the exchange rate for the euro will
be formally set.
	   Lafontaine will be on vacation and Germany will be represented
at the Thursday meeting of EU finance and economics ministers
(Ecofin) by Economics Minister Werner Mueller, finance ministry
spokesman Torsten Albig said.
	   The general secretary of the opposition Christian Democrats,
Angela Merkel, accused Lafontaine of lacking ``a feel for historic
situations,'' and called his absence ``embarrassing.''
	   Albig said both the finance and economics ministers were
entitled to represent Germany at the meeting.
	   ``There's no rule about who goes and who doesn't. They are
interchangeable,'' said Albig.
	   ``Our economics minister will be our high-ranking and highly
qualified representative,'' Albig said.
	   The euro's exchange rate will be fixed Thursday, a day before it
becomes the currency of 11 EU nations.
