<HEADLINE>
Six rockets fired on army camp in Kashmir
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SRINAGAR, India (AP) _ Six rockets slammed into an Indian army
camp and injured two soldiers Wednesday in Srinagar, the city at
the center of a separatist movement in Indian Kashmir, an army
spokesman said.
	   The army said it did not know who fired the rockets or from
where. Some barracks and a workshop were damaged in the attack.
	   Soldiers immediately cordoned off residential areas around the
camp and conducted house-to-house searches for the attackers. One
suspected militant was arrested.
	   It was the first time in two years that rockets have been fired
on the army in Srinagar, the summer capital of Jammu-Kashmir state.
In 1996, rockets were fired near a stadium where a parade was under
way to celebrate India's republic day.
	   Dozens of groups in Kashmir, India's only Muslim-majority state,
have been fighting government troops since 1989 to secede from
predominantly Hindu India, either to become independent or join
with neighboring Islamic country of Pakistan. More than 17,000
people have been killed since the fighting began.
