<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Chechnya-President </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chechnya's president says warlords can't remove him
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Chechnya's president said Wednesday that warlords
attempting to drive him from office would not succeed because he
still had the support of the people who had elected him in the
breakaway region.
	   President Aslan Maskhadov has seen many of his former allies
turn against him in recent months and mount a concerted campaign to
remove him as Chechnya's leader.
	   But Maskhadov said it would prove impossible ``to crush a
popularly elected president,'' the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   Maskhadov was a top guerrilla commander in the 1994-6 war
against Russia, and he won an overwhelming election victory shortly
after the war ended and the Russian troops left. But he's been
unable to bring law-and-order to Chechnya or rebuild the fractured
economy.
	   As a result, a number of war-time colleagues have deserted him.
They tried to impeach Maskhadov and accused him of violating
Chechnya's constitution, but the country's top Islamic court ruled
in Maskhadov's favor.
	   ``The proud ... Chechen people are standing behind me,''
Maskhadov said.
	   However, the court suspended parliament's ability to make laws,
dealing a blow to Maskhadov, who could usually count on the
lawmakers to support him.
	   Chechnya has run its own affairs since the Russian troops
withdrew in 1996, but no country has recognized its independence
claim and Moscow continues to consider the southern republic a part
of Russia.
	   Hundreds of people have been abducted for ransom in Chechnya in
recent years. In an unusually gruesome display of lawlessness, four
Western captives were beheaded earlier this month.
	   (gm/nw) 	   
</TEXT>
