<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Europe Advisory </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   EDITORS: The following stories have moved or will move on the
European circuits of The Associated Press by 1600 GMT unless
otherwise noted:
	   PRISTINA _ A top government official in Kosovo warned in remarks
published Wednesday that Serbia is running out of patience with
ethnic Albanian rebels and suggested it could launch another
large-scale action against them. YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO.
	   WASHINGTON _ U.S. fighter jets fired missiles and laser-guided
bombs on an Iraqi missile site early Wednesday after a British
aircraft observed something fired from the site near Talil in
southern Iraq. US-IRAQ.
	   WITH:
	   IRAQ. Despite a confrontation this week with Western warplanes,
Iraq is remaining defiant. The Baghdad government announces that
its aircraft are flying in the ``no-fly'' zones patrolled by U.S.
and British warplanes and says Iraqi anti-aircraft batteries remain
ready to fire on allied planes.
	   SAN`A _ Yemen faced a barrage of criticism Wednesday after its
troops stormed the hideout of Islamic extremist kidnappers holding
16 Western hostages. Four of the hostages were killed.
YEMEN-KIDNAPPING.
	   BRUSSELS _ The birth of the euro is nigh. All the hype and high
anxiety will be turned into reality Friday when 11 European nations
deliver their joint currency and unite their monetary policies, a
giant step towards further unity. THE EURO.
	   WITH:
	   GERMANY-EURO. The German government Wednesday defended Finance
Minister Oskar Lafontaine's decision not to attend a meeting of
European Union ministers in Brussels, during which the exchange
rate for the euro will be formally set.
	   MOSCOW _ Russia's Western creditors on Wednesday consider
whether to announce it formally in default after it missed a
payment on its Soviet-era debts. RUSSIA-ECONOMY.
	   ROME _ A U.N. agency that delivers emergency food aid says that
in 1999 more people around the world will probably need
humanitarian assistance because of crises this year like Hurricane
Mitch and economic collapses in Indonesia and Russia. UN-FOOD
SHORTAGES.
	   FORT WILLIAM _ An avalanche struck a party of seven hikers on a
mountain in northwest Scotland, killing four. Rescuers saved three
survivors trapped in tons of snow, police said Wednesday. BRITAIN
AVALANCHE
	   PHNOM PENH _ King Norodom Sihanouk refuses Wednesday to approve
amnesty for two leaders of the genocidal Khmer Rouge, setting up a
collision course with his prime minister, who has pledged to shield
them from trial. CAMBODIA-KHMER ROUGE.
	   LUANDA _ President Jose Eduardo dos Santos ruled out talks with
the rebel group UNITA on ending the country's renewed civil war,
and described rebel leader Jonas Savimbi as a liar for pretending
to be committed to a 1994 peace pact. ANGOLA.
	   SYDNEY _ Two inquiries will be held into the deadly
Sydney-to-Hobart yacht race amid claims that race organizers knew
of the potential danger 24 hours before the fleet was decimated by
a massive storm. AUSTRALIA-DEADLY YACHT RACE.
