<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Avalanche, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Four people killed and three injured in avalanche on Scottish
</HEADLINE>
mountain &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with details, quotes &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   FORT WILLIAM, Scotland _ An avalanche struck a party of seven
hikers on a mountain in northwest Scotland, killing four, police
said Wednesday. Rescuers saved three survivors trapped in tons of
snow.
	   The hikers had been participating in ``winter skills'' training
course on Aonoch Mor near Ben Nevis in the Scottish Highlands on
Tuesday when they were caught in the avalanche at about 3,500 feet
(900 meters) on the mountainside, police said.
	   ``Rescuers spotted one of the survivors whose top half was
showing, but it took another two hours to dig everyone else out,''
said police inspector Charles Ross. ``It is amazing that anyone
survived in the circumstances. They were all experienced climbers
who were members of some kind of organization and had decided they
wanted to get some winter conditions experience.''
	   The hikers were reported missing at 2230 GMT Tuesday when they
did not return from the day's climb. Royal Air Force mountain
rescue teams immediately began a search. Gale force winds forced a
helicopter to abandon rescue attempts, but ground crews found the
group at 0120 GMT Wednesday, a police spokesman said.
	   The three survivors were found Wednesday, buried under three
feet of snow about 16 hours after the avalanche hit.
	   Rescue leader Terry Confield said the instructor had left
details of the group's route and itinerary.
	   ``Within about an hour we had located one of the survivors who
was stuck in the snow with the upper part of their body exposed,''
Confield said. ``If he hadn't been so easily visible we would have
had a massive job on our hands.''
	   Confield said said rescuers frantically dug down into the snow
to recover the remaining members of the party.
	   ``Sadly, four of them were already dead but we were all
delighted that three had survived,'' he said.
	   Steven Newton, 24; Sarah Finch, 25, and instructor Roger Wilde,
were carried off the mountain one at a time, and taken to Belford
Hospital in Fort William, where they were being treated for
hypothermia.
	   The bodies of Emma Ray, 29; Paul Hopkins, 28; Matthew Lewis, 28,
and Ian Edwards, 30, were recovered Wednesday.
	   (mb-acw) 	   
</TEXT>
