<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Jordan, Egypt, Kuwait &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Jordan and Iraq will hold talks starting
Monday to renew for 1999 the barter deal under which Jordan gets
oil from its neighbor.
	   Energy Minister Hani Mulqi said Wednesday that the meetings will
be held in Baghdad. The talks had been planned earlier but were put
off because of the U.S. and British airstrikes on Iraq in
mid-December.
	   Jordan currently meets its total oil requirements of 90,000
barrels per day with shipments trucked in tankers across the desert
border from Iraq.
	   Some of the oil is given at a concession price. The oil goes
toward paying Iraq's dlrs 1.3 billion debt to Jordan, accumulated
during the 1980s, and to cover the cost of food and medicine
imported from Jordan.
	   Mulqi said Jordan was seeking an increase of 5 percent to 7
percent in oil supplies next year to meet ``natural growth in
industry and civic consumption.''
	   He also intends to speak with Iraq's oil minister, Lt. Gen. Amer
Mohammed Rashid, on ways to increase cooperation in oil and gas
exploration. The two also are expected to resume discussion on
building a 700 kilometer (420 mile) pipeline to carry oil from Iraq
to Jordan.
	   Mulqi revealed that Jordan was affected by the airstrikes on
Iraq, during which oil shipments to Jordan were suspended. He said
Jordan signed agreements to import 60,000 tons of diesel fuel and
40,000 tons of liquefied gas from from the international market.
	   The barter deal is an exception from U.N. sanctions, imposed
after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait, that limit Iraqi oil sales.
 &UR; ___
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Egypt is planing to hold its first trade
fair in Tehran since the 1979 Islamic revolution in, Egyptian Trade
Minister Ahmed Guweili was quoted Wednesday as saying.
	   Guweili told the Egyptian Gazette that the fair, which will
exhibit a variety of Egyptian-made goods, will run June 21-26.
	   Its aim is to open a new market for Egyptian products abroad,
Guweili told the English-language daily. He described Iran as a
promising market.
	   Egypt has slowly but steadily been moving toward restoring
economic and political ties with Iran, which it severed after the
revolution nearly 20 years ago. The two countries recently
exchanged trade delegations.
 &UR; ___
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ Parliament has passed a bill that proposes to make
it obligatory for foreigners living in this oil-rich Gulf state to
buy health insurance, the Arab Times daily reported Wednesday.
	   The bill still needs the approval of the emir, Sheik Jaber
al-Ahmed al-Sabah, to become law.
	   The government has one year to implement the bill, which will
affect 1.4 million expatriate workers who currently enjoy free
health care in state hospitals along with 800,000 Kuwaiti citizens.
	   Lawmakers voted for the bill 34-9 Tuesday, with one abstention,
the English-language daily Arab Times said. It was proposed by a
group of legislators.
	   Although the bill is apparently aimed at reducing the government
health expenditure, critics said it would unjustly hit low-income
foreign workers. They said the scheme was devised to benefit
insurance companies.
	   Workers who refuse to buy insurance will not be given work
permits under the bill.
	   Ibrahim Behbehani, a former Health Ministry official who opposes
the bill, told the Arab Times he will challenge it in court.
	   Behbehani said the government spends only about 16 dinars (dlrs
53) a year on health services for every foreigner, a figure so
small that it is hardly worth canceling.
	   The obligatory insurance will not apply to a few categories of
non-Kuwaitis: children of Kuwaiti women married to foreigners,
foreign wives of Kuwaiti men and up to three domestic helpers for
every household.
