<SLUG> BC-Libya-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Libya orders the arrest of Americans in 1986 air attack
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ In a symbolic _ if futile _ move, a Libyan
prosecutor on Wednesday ordered the arrest of nine American
officials allegedly behind the 1986 bombing of two Libyan cities,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
	   Among those on the list is William Casey, the late director of
the CIA.
	   The announcement came as Libya is maneuvering over American and
British demands that two Libyan suspects be turned over for trial
in the Netherlands for the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am jet that killed
270 people.
	   MENA said that the prosecutor, Mohammed Abdel-Wahab, announced
the arrest orders at a news conference at the People's Court in the
Libyan capital Tripoli.
	   In addition to Casey, Abdel-Wahab gave the names of a number of
American pilots as well as former National Security Adviser John
Poindexter and Marine Lt. Col. Oliver North.
	   The prosecutor said that if Libya failed to secure their arrest,
``it will resort to (U.N.) Security Council to get the accused,''
MENA said.
	   Former U.S. President Ronald Reagan ordered an air attack on
Libya in 1986 in retaliation for the bombing of a Berlin
discotheque in which two U.S. servicemen were killed.
	   Libya said 37 people, including an adopted daughter of Libyan
leader Moammar Gadhafi, were killed in the attack on Tripoli and
the port of Benghazi.
	   Reagan's name was not on the list released by Libya, according
to the MENA report.
	   The United States and Britain have demanded that Libya turn over
two suspects in the bombing of the Pan Am jet over Lockerbie,
Scotland.
	   They have said that if Libya does not do so, they will ask the
Security Council to expand sanctions against Libya.
 &UR; bm-eap
</TEXT>
