<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Obit-Brossa </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Catalan poet/artist Joan Brossa dies at 79
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BARCELONA, Spain (AP) _ Joan Brossa, a versatile Catalan poet
associated with some of the pillars of the Spanish surrealist
movement and best known for his ``visual poems,'' died Wednesday,
National Spanish Television TVE reported.
	   Brossa died from a heart attack in a hospital of this
northeastern Spanish city, he was 79. His funeral was scheduled for
Thursday, TVE said.
	   A friend of artist Joan Miro, Brossa founded a surrealist
magazine called Dau al Set in 1948 together with another of
Catalonia's formidable artistic lineup Antoni Tapies.
	   His poems, written in Catalan, were first published in 1951 and
his last book came out in 1987.
	   Known for his caustic whit and hostility toward artistic
convention, Brossa began developing his ``visual poems'' in the
1950s _ a rifle barrel toped with a church candle snuffer entitled
``Conscientious Objector'' or a football crowned by a Spanish comb
entitled ``The Nation'' .
	   Several examples of his work are displayed in major Spanish
galleries including the Reina Sofia modern art museum in Madrid and
the Fundacion Miro in Barcelona.
	   Upon learning of Brossa's death Tapies said, ``Brossa always
called himself a poet rather than an artist, and I agree with
him,'' the state-owned news agency EFE reported.
	   His career also included several theatrical works.
	   Brossa, who fought for the Republicans in the 1936-39 Spanish
Civil War with a book by Spanish poet Federico Garcia Lorca in his
pocket, was awarded several prizes for his contribution to Spanish
culture.
	   He is survived by his wife Pepa Llopis.
	   (jt)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
