<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-IOC-Salt Lake,0348 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC vice president meets behind closed doors with SLOC officials
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) _ International Olympic Committee vice
president Dick Pound has held closed-door meetings with Salt Lake
Olympics officials as head of the IOC's probe into allegations of
bribery in connection with the 2002 Winter Games.
	   Pound was in Salt Lake City on Tuesday to review documents and
to interview individuals involved with the city's effort to secure
the 2002 Games.
	   Meanwhile, in Washington, a U.S. Olympic Committee panel headed
by former U.S. Senate leader and Northern Ireland peace negotiator
George Mitchell began its own investigation.
	   Salt Lake Olympic officials have admitted having a dlrs 400,000
scholarship fund that benefited 13 recipients, including six
relatives of IOC members. IOC members also were given thousands of
dollars worth of guns and skis, and some received free medical
treatment, including plastic surgery.
	   Pound spent much of the day pursuing his probe at offices of the
Salt Lake Organizing Committee.
	   Shelley Thomas, SLOC senior vice president of communications,
said she was not part of the proceedings and was unsure who was
interviewed. Pound, an attorney from Montreal, told her only that
he did not plan to make any statements to the media.
	   The IOC panel has hired a Los Angeles law firm, O'Melveny and
Myers, to represent it in the investigation, according to USA
Today.
	   ``I thought with so many investigations going on, I should
probably hire a lawyer so we're not bumping into each other,''
Pound told the newspaper.
	   Thomas was uncertain whether Pound's investigation would
continue Wednesday. The commission he leads is expected to submit a
report to the IOC executive board on Jan. 24 in Lausanne,
Switzerland.
	   Mitchell's group is planning to issue its report to the USOC by
Feb. 28.
	   SLOC's ethics committee also is investigating, and the American
federal Justice Department announced last week that it would
investigate to determine whether any laws were broken.
</TEXT>
