<SLUG> BC-Italy-Pigeons of Venice </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
In St. Mark's Square, death knell for puniest of Venice's pigeons
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VENICE, Italy (AP) _ Venice's mayor has signed an order
authorizing the killing of the sickliest among the city's pampered
pigeon population, Italian newspapers reported Wednesday.
	   Surveys estimate the number of the birds at more than 100,000,
many of which live out their days clustered around the pigeon-food
stands in St. Mark's Square.
	   Tourists delight in feeding the throngs of cooing birds,
nurturing a Venetian pigeon flock estimated to be 20 times that of
Rome's.
	   Venice officials say 15 percent of the birds carry salmonella, a
bacterial disease transmittable to humans, and call even the
healthy ones a menace to the city's monuments.
	   Mayor Massimo Cacciari approved a plan Tuesday allowing city
workers to destroy the ailing ones.
	   Venice previously tried to control the size of the flocks by
scattering chemically treated birdseed meant to sterilize the
birds. Animal-rights groups oppose the latest plan; city officials
call it essential.
	   (ek) 	   
</TEXT>
