<SLUG> BC-Emirates-Amnesty </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Emirates pardons 171 prisoners in Ramadan gesture
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) _ The Emirates granted amnesty
Wednesday to 171 prisoners to mark the Islamic holy month of
Ramadan, the official news agency reported.
	   The emirate of Sharjah released 125 prisoners while the
neighboring emirate of Ajman freed 46, the Emirates News Agency
said.
	   The fasting month of Ramadan marks the revelation of the Koran,
Islam's holy book, to the Prophet Mohammed some 1,400 years ago.
Muslims are forbidden to eat, drink or have sex between sunrise and
sunset during the month.
	   During Ramadan, and the feast that follows it, many Arab Gulf
rulers grant amnesties to petty criminals.
	   Sharjah and Ajman are two of the seven emirates of the United
Arab Emirates.
