<HEADLINE>
ADEN: the kidnappers.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Three Britons and an Australian were killed in the siege
Tuesday, and an American and a Briton were wounded. Yemen's
Interior Ministry said its forces killed three of the kidnappers
and captured three others during the shootout in Mawdiyah town, 175
miles (290 kilometers) south of the capital, San`a.
	   Firkin, 55, from Croyden, England, said he was with a group of
11 hostages. The kidnappers had split their 16 captives into two
groups, and Firkin and Brian Smith, another hostage, said they did
not know how the other group had come under attack.
	   Both men said their group wound up in the middle of a gun battle
after government troops opened fire on the kidnappers as they fled
with their hostages.
	   ``We were being led into the mountains to a hiding. Then we
heard the gunfire,'' said Firkin, a chemistry professor whose
sandals were still dusty from the trek.
	   He and Smith, 52, a postal worker from Peterborough, England,
were interviewed at a hotel in Aden where they were taken to rest
from their ordeal.
	   Smith said the gun battle went on for about two hours, with
bullets whizzing over the heads of the hostages.
	   ``We were in the middle of a battle. We weren't armed, with no
military knowledge,'' he said.
