<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Fog, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Warsaw fog disrupts international air traffic
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with details of canceled flights,
descriptions of Warsaw airport scenes, quotes from stranded
travelers; ADDS byline &QL; 
 &UR; By TOM COHEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Thick fog over Warsaw prevented planes
from landing Wednesday, causing delays or cancellations of outgoing
international flights and jeopardizing New Year's Eve plans of
stranded travelers.
	   A Delta Airlines flight from New York to Warsaw had to land in
Prague in neighboring Czech Republic, and the airline said the
unspecified number of passengers on board would spend the night
there.
	   That stranded 80 passengers waiting in Warsaw for the return
flight. Hundreds more passengers on canceled flights for
Copenhagen, Zurich, Paris and Frankfurt stood in front of the
flight information board at Okecie airport, hoping for a sudden
change in the weather.
	   ``I have a New Year's Eve date with my boyfriend in Paris,''
said Monica Kubiak, 25, as she punched numbers on her cellular
telephone. ``I'm optimistic, but we'll see.''
	   While two international flights landed in the afternoon, cloud
levels as low as 30 meters (100 feet) made conditions too dangerous
most of the day, said airline spokesman Marek Wos. He said the
airport lacked the radar technology for flights to land in such
conditions.
	   Outside the Delta office, U.S. college students Joe Cali, 21,
Maja Toth, 20, and her brother Joey, 19, wondered if they would be
able to attend a New Year's Eve block party in Phoenix, Arizona, as
planned.
	   Cali seemed more concerned about using his ticket for the Jan. 4
Fiesta Bowl college football championship game, being played in
Arizona.
	   ``As long as I make the Fiesta Bowl, I'll be happy,'' he said.
	   The three complained that little information on the canceled
flight was immediately available.
	   ``I thought it was pretty unprofessional,'' Cali said. ``They
tell us it's leaving at 1 o'clock, but no one tells us it was
canceled.''
	   Some incoming planes were rerouted to other airports in Poland,
such as Krakow or Poznan, while all domestic flights were canceled.
An airport spokeswoman said 16 international flights left Warsaw by
midday, all behind schedule.
	   Delta officials in Prague said all passengers on the diverted
flight from New York were fine, but they refused to release the
number or say when they would get to Warsaw.
	   In Warsaw, Delta officials said the flight diverted to Prague
would come to Warsaw on Thursday morning, weather permitting, and
then make the return flight to New York.
	   (tsc)
</TEXT>
