u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-GolanHeights     12-30 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Golan Heights </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israel put price tag on the Golan Heights
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SARI BASHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel conducted a survey to determine how much
money it would have to pay residents of the Golan Heights if it
were to give their land back to Syria, Israel's former finance
minister said Wednesday.
	   ``When we started serious discussions with the Syrians in '95,
we did an inventory of what it was we were dealing with,'' said
Labor legislator Avraham Shohat, who supervised the year-long
survey when he was finance minister.
	   Shohat said the survey was conducted under Labor prime ministers
Yitzhak Rabin and Shimon Peres, but stopped when Benjamin
Netanyahu's Likud government came into power in May, 1996.
	   The Israeli daily Yediot Ahronot reported Wednesday that
Netanyahu's government continued the assessment project.
Netanyahu's office was not immediately available for comment.
	   Shohat wouldn't say how much the Golan was actually worth, but
Yediot Ahronot put the price tag at ten billion shekels (dlrs 2.5
billion).
	   Golan Heights residents complained that the government made
plans to turn over their land in secret.
	   ``We are a sovereign part of Israel'' said Avi Zeira, chairman
of the Golan Heights residents committee. ``The government must not
deal with this (possibility).''
	   Shohat said that while no withdrawal plans had been formulated,
he ordered the survey learn estimated costs. He said the project
was conducted secretly to avoid inflaming a sensitive issue.
	   Israel captured the heights from Syria in the 1967 Mideast war
and annexed the area in 1981.
	   Israel conducted peace talks with the Syrians under the Labor
governments of Rabin and Peres, but talks broke off when
Netanyahu's Likud government came to power.
	   Syria says that when the talks broke off in 1996, the Peres
government had given the Syrians to understand that for a full
peace agreement, they could expect to get all of the Golan.
	   The Syrians insist that the Netanyahu government recognize the
understandings Damascus reached with the previous Israeli
government. Netanyahu has refused to do so, saying continued
control over the Golan is vital for Israel's security. He has
approved expansion of Jewish settlements in the Golan.
	   Last week, the Israeli press reported that Netanyahu and
opposition leader Ehud Barak reached a secret deal to give back the
Golan. Netanyahu denied the report.
	   About 17,000 Israelis live in the Golan, along with about 14,000
Druze Arabs.
 &UR; sb-rk
</TEXT>
