r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-SkiJumping-Fou lstld-Writethru   12-30 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Ski Jumping-Four Hills Tour, lst ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Schmitt wins first of Four Hills and draws record crowd
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: CHANGES Slug, corrects crowd size, adds details, RECASTS
thruought &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   OBERSTDORF, Germany (AP) _ Germany's Martin Schmitt, emerging
from nowhere this season, outleaped Austria's Andreas Goldberger
Wednesday to capture the first stop of the ski jumping Four Hills
tour.
	   Schmitt, luring a record crowd of 40,000 to the event, soared to
jumps of 120.0 and 115.5 meters to compile 244.8 points and edge
Goldberger at 242.8.
	   It also proved once again his unexpected success this season is
no fluke.
	   It was the 20-year-old German's fifth World Cup win in seven
outings this season, although he still slightly trails Finland's
Janne Ahonen in the overall standings.
	   Schmitt popularity in Germany has exploded, one reason the crowd
shattered the previous record in Obersthof of 24,000.
	   ``All those spectators motivate me. The mood here was crazy, it
was fun,'' said Schmitt, whose best finish until this season was an
11th. ``I'm sure the attention will get even worse, but I think I
know when to turn off.''
	   Japan's Noriaki Kasai finished third at 241.7 points while
Austria's Andreas Widhoelzl faded to fourth after leading after the
first jump.
	   Widhoelzl, as a backwind pushed up distances on the first leap,
jumped to a day's best of 124.0 meters. But his sizeable lead
melted away on his second attempt when he could only manage 109.5
meters.
	   ``That Wildhoelzl failed was my luck. He knew he had to jump at
least 111, 112 meters to match me. He probably put himself under
too much pressure,'' said Schmitt.
	   The other three Four Hills tour stops will be held at
Garmisch-Partenkirchen on New Year's Day, Innsbruck on Jan. 3 and
Bischofshofen on Jan. 6.
	   Ahonen had to settle for fifth after leaps of 117.00 and 115.00
meters but it was enough to maintain first in the overall World Cup
standings.
	   Ahonen, who seized the lead when Schmitt sat out the last two
World Cup events, has 653 points to the German's 640. Olympic
champion Kazuyoshi Funaki of Japan is third at 478.
	   Funaki finished sixth with leaps of 118.0 and 113.0.
	    &UR; (rk)	   
</TEXT>
