<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-New Year, HFR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Schroeder warns against forgetting past as big new year begins
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Hold for release until 2300 GMT Wednesday, set by source &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ In his New Year's address, German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said the new beginning promised in
1999 by the government's return to Berlin does not mean an end to
remembering Germany's past.
	   ``We cannot allow a final line to be drawn under the past, just
as we can't look away when injustice and violence occurs today
against minorities or people of other origins,'' he said in an
advance copy of a speech to be broadcast Thursday.
	   Schroeder, the first German chancellor too young to remember
World War II, noted that Germany's federal republic and its postwar
constitution turn 50 years old in 1999. ``And today we can say,
full of pride: `We've created a model that has proven itself,''' he
said.
	   The same values of a ``living democracy'' will be transferred
along with parliament and the government from Bonn to Berlin this
year, he promised. ``Berlin will then really be our capital, and
not just on paper.''
	   Parliamentary president Wolfgang Thierse, in his New Year's
address, described Berlin as ``the suture point of German unity''
and called for a continuation of ``good democratic politics.''
	   Schroeder and Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer reiterated their
desire to make fighting unemployment their No. 1 goal in the New
Year, when Germany takes over the rotating European Union
presidency. Other important goals are strengthening the union and
passing administrative and agricultural reforms.
	   Schroeder also noted Germany hosts the 1999 Group of Seven
summit of leading industrial nations. ``There we'll especially have
to work on an international financial architecture that will
prevent entire economies from collapsing through speculation,'' he
said.
 &UR; (pfg-dkt)
</TEXT>
