w2866 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yemen-Kidnapping 9thLd-Writethru   12-30 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Kidnapping, 9th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former hostages say Yemeni troops started fatal shootout
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: COMBINES pvs, CORRECTS name to Eric in 4th graf; minor
editing, trims.
 &UR; By SAM F. GHATTAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ADEN, Yemen (AP) _ Westerners freed after a shootout fatal to
four foreign tourists said Wednesday that the battle started when
Yemeni security forces attacked Islamic radicals holding the
foreigners hostage.
	   Their accounts appeared to contradict a Yemeni government
statement, which said security forces only opened fire Tuesday
after the kidnappers began killing some of their hostages at a camp
in the country's south.
	   But the hostages told The Associated Press that once their
kidnappers were attacked, they tried to use their prisoners as
shields and eventually shot two of the captives in ``revenge
killings'' as they fled.
	   ``The worst time for me was that time when a barrel was pointed
at my chest. I said, `No, no, no,''' recounted Eric Firkin, who
said a fellow captive, a woman, was shot dead in front of him by
one of the kidnappers.
	   Three Britons and an Australian were killed in the siege
Tuesday, and an American and a Briton were wounded. Yemen's
Interior Ministry said its forces killed three of the kidnapers and
captured three others during the shootout near Mawdiyah town, 175
miles (286 kilometers) south of the capital, San`a.
	   The 16 hostages _ 12 Britons, two Americans and two Australians
_ were seized nearby a day earlier.
	   Firkin, 55, from Croyden, England, said he was with a group of
11 hostages. The kidnappers had split their captives into two
groups. Firkin and Brian Smith, another hostage, said they did not
know how the other group had come under attack.
	   Both men said two in their group were killed by the kidnappers
after the hostages wound up in the middle of a battle started when
government troops opened fire.
	   ``We were being led into the mountains to a hideout. Then we
heard the gunfire,'' said Firkin, a chemistry professor whose
sandals were still dusty from the trek.
	   He and Smith, 52, a postal worker from Peterborough, England,
were interviewed at a hotel in the southern port of Aden where they
were taken to rest from their ordeal.
	   Smith said the gun battle went on for about two hours, with
bullets whizzing over the heads of the hostages.
	   ``We were in the middle of a battle. We weren't armed, with no
military knowledge,'' he said.
	   One of the wounded, Claire Marston of Britain, was ``in a very
bad way,'' British diplomat David Pearce told reporters at
Al-Jamhouriya Hospital in Aden.
	   Marston was awake after surgery on her shoulder _ where she was
shot _ and knew her husband, Canadian-born Peter Rowe, had been
killed, Pearce said.
	   The two women were ``as well as can be expected,'' he added. The
other woman, an unidentified American, was shot in the pelvis,
hospital officials said on condition of anonymity.
	   In San`a, Brig. Mohammad Saleh al-Turaiq, the chief of security
in Aden province, said Wednesday that the kidnappers were the first
to open fire.
	   ``The Egyptian (kidnapper) began shooting at the hostages, which
forced our troops to storm the hideout,'' he told reporters in the
presence of the British ambassador.
	   Al-Turaiq said his forces were chasing some kidnappers who got
away. He accused foreign elements of instigating the kidnapping,
but refused to elaborate.
	   Yemeni officials have identified the Egyptian as Osama al-Masri.
In Cairo, Egyptian security sources said the name was the alias of
a wanted Islamic extremist. They refused to give his real name.
	   The officials said the kidnappers belonged to Islamic Jihad, a
group of about 200 members based in a camp in south Yemen.
	   They had seized the hostages to demand the release of two of
their leaders and in protest against the recent U.S. and British
airstrikes against Iraq, officials said. Police had detained the
leaders in a crackdown on Islamic vigilantes.
	   Kidnappings of foreigners occur often in Yemen, large parts of
which are run by lawless tribes, but until now the hostages usually
have been treated well and released unharmed.
	   This was the first time Islamic extremists had abducted
foreigners.
	   British newspapers accused the Yemeni authorities of premature
intervention. The Daily Mail asked on the front page, ``Did our
tourists really need to die?''
	   British Ambassador Vic Henderson reportedly had pleaded with the
San`a government to do nothing ``that in any way could jeopardize
the safety of the hostages.''
	   In San`a, Yemenis told journalists they were surprised the
government had intervened so quickly when it usually negotiated for
several days, if not weeks, with kidnappers.
	   After the killings, Germany appealed to the San`a government not
to attempt to rescue the four Germans held hostage by a tribe in
northeast Yemen, Yemeni officials said Wednesday.
	   The British Foreign Office confirmed that three Britons _ Ruth
Williamson, Margaret Whitehouse and Rowe _ were killed, but did not
provide their ages or hometowns.
	   The Australian's name is Andrew Colin Thirsk, 35, of Sydney.
	   The kidnapping began when the tourists' convoy of five vehicles
was ambushed by men who opened fire on their police escorts, Yemeni
security officials said.
	   Yemen said negotiations had been underway when the shootout
began. Tribesmen usually kidnap foreigners to press the government
to provide new roads, water or clinics.
 &UR; str-ti/fsa-jbm/sfg/ggl
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yemen-Kidnapping, 9th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
