w2874 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Iran-Elections     12-30 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Elections </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
16 Iranian groups form coalition to contest municipal elections
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ Sixteen moderate political groups have
formed a coalition to contest crucial municipal elections in
February, newspapers reported Wednesday.
	   The elections will present a fresh test of popularity for
politicians aligned with the reformist President Mohammad Khatami
and his hard-line rivals in the ruling clergy.
	   The new coalition, which calls itself the Coordination
Headquarters of the Elections of the Islamic Councils, said it will
try to make its mark in the Feb. 26 polls for mayors and municipal
councils _ the first to be held since the 1979 Islamic revolution.
	   Moderates hope the municipal elections will produce a huge
turnout similar to the one that gave Khatami his own victory in the
May 1997 polls. Of Iran's 38.5 million eligible voters, 30 million
cast ballots, 20 million of them for Khatami.
	   ``We call on those who were active in the presidential elections
to cooperate with our group and continue playing a role,'' Khordad
newspaper quoted a statement by the coalition as saying.
	   A victory by moderate candidates would be seen as an endorsement
of Khatami's efforts to ease social and political restrictions
imposed by the clergy.
	   Among the groups in the coalition is the powerful and outspoken
student association, the Office of Fostering Unity, and the
newly-formed Participation Front of Islamic Iran, which was
launched by government officials allied with Khatami.
	   The influential Association of Combatant Clergy, of which
Khatami was a founder, is also part of the coalition.
	   There are 10,000 municipalities in Iran, and voters will be
selecting mayors and governing councils. More than 200,000
officials will be elected to manage local government affairs and
advise the central government on social and cultural activities.
	   Political parties are not allowed in Iran and candidates are
officially independent but usually aligned to either moderate or
hard-line camps.
	   Since Khatami took office, hard-liners have resisted his efforts
to grant more freedom to the press and the arts and to reduce
Islamic strictures on average Iranians _ reforms that seem to have
widespread public support.
 &UR; av-fsa/vj
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Iran-Elections; CT:i; 
