w2880 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-GreekSt     12-30 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Greek Strike,0421 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Planned strike by clubs deals another blow to already reeling
</HEADLINE>
sport &QL; 
 &UR; By ELENA BECATOROS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Violence, bribery and corruption
allegations and now a strike by clubs. The beating being taken by
Greek soccer will continue into the new year.
	   All first-, second- and third-division games planned for this
weekend were called off Tuesday by the Association of Professional
Soccer Clubs (EPAE) because of money it says the government owes it
from the weekly gambling pools.
	   And if it doesn't get it by Monday, it will extend the strike
for games Jan. 9-11.
	   EPAE is demanding 300 million drachmas (more than dlrs 1
million) from OPAP, the state agency that organizes the betting
pools, that already is owed and to increase its percentage from the
pool.
	   But the agency, known as OPAP, has refused to budge.
	   ``A hungry bear can't dance. We will play if OPAP gives us the
money,'' Iraklis club owner Petros Theodoridis was quoted in the
daily newspaper Sportime.
	   EPAE's actions appears to be further reducing the public's
interest in soccer _ which is losing popularity in Greece to
basketball.
	   ``It will not be the end of the world if there is no soccer for
a few weeks,'' the Athens daily Kathimerini quoted Sports Minister
Andreas Fouras as saying.
	   His comments seem to reflect the feelings of many soccer fans,
who have shown no signs of being troubled by the prospect of two
weekends without matches.
	   The strike comes towards the end of the holiday season, with
most people taking advantage of the long weekend to head to the
countryside.
	   But a recent series of violent incidents by fans and allegations
of bribery and corruption already have diminished the game's appeal
to mainstream followers.
	   Sparked by accusations of biased officiating, a wave of
vandalism and violence began in November. It led to harsh criticism
of the sport in a parliamentary committee report.
	   ``Our country is being internationally defamed at the time it is
preparing to organize the Olympic Games,'' the report said.
	   Fans that rioted after a first-division match on Dec. 8 between
Olympiakos Piraeus and its main rival Panathinaikos left a stream
of burned cars, battered bystanders and damaged seats in the
stadium set to host the 2004 Olympic Games.
	   Last year, nearly half the country's 300 lawmakers issued a
statement complaining soccer ``is being led to decline and
extermination.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-Greek Strike; CT:s; 
