w2886 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo-UPD     12-30 0217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo-UPDATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
State run company bans printing of Albanian daily
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ A state-run printing house in Kosovo
on Wednesday served notice it would stop printing the oldest
Albanian-language daily in the Serbian province, in the latest step
of a crackdown on independent media.
	   A terse directive telling employees of the Panorama print works
not to print the Bujku daily was posted in the plant without any
details on the ban.
	   Bujku is one of the three largest dailies in the ethnic-Albanian
majority province which is gripped in a bloody struggle between
government forces and Albanian guerrillas seeking independence.
	   The authoritarian Serbian government, after cracking down
earlier this year on Serbian-language papers in the country, has
moved to suppress Albanian-language papers because of their support
for independence.
	   Bujku is the first Kosovo Albanian newspaper targeted. The
state-run plant actually stopped printing the daily two weeks ago,
claiming it was in arrears for printing costs. It has not appeared
on newsstands since then.
	   There was no immediate comment Wednesday from Bujku staff, but
other Albanian-language papers still publishing have said they
would defy government pressure on them.
	   (ih/ms/gj)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo-UPDATE; CT:i; 
