<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-The Euro,0573 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Birth of the euro marks beginning of a new era in Europe
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo BRU101 &QL; 
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The birth of the euro is nigh. The hype
and high anxiety turns to reality at midnight Thursday when 11
European nations deliver their joint currency and merge their
monetary policies, a giant step in solidifying European unity.
	   The euro will live as a virtual currency alongside German marks,
French francs, Italian lire and the others for three years before
it replaces them as the notes and coins used from Spain's
Mediterranean beaches to deep into Finland's frozen tundra.
	   The finance ministers and central bankers from the 11 European
Union nations meet here Thursday to irrevocably lock the exchange
rates of their currencies against the euro before toasting the
creation of the new currency, perhaps the most significant
development in the drive towards European unity since World War II.
	   On Jan 1, the euro will become a new trading currency around the
world and the Frankfurt-based European Central Bank will decide on
the monetary fate of the 11 euro nations. The euro is expected to
trade at around dlrs 1.18.
	   Of the 15 EU nations only Greece failed to make the strict
monetary conditions for joining, while Britain, Sweden and Denmark
decided to opt out for the time being, fearful the euro will erode
their cherished sovereignty. Surrendering one's currency
automatically means surrendering the right to set independent
monetary policy for domestic reasons, such as boosting the economy
or improving social conditions.
	   The euro will be the most palpable sign yet of European
integration, and will streamline trade in a bloc of 290 million
people with an economic clout rivaling that of the United States.
Prices in the neighboring countries will be simpler to compare,
international business will be easier and intra-euro trade will no
longer be hostage to fickle currency fluctuations, a major boon for
businesses.
	   For the world at large, visiting the 11 EU nations will become
somewhat easier, since they will be able to use euros when they pay
with credit cards and checks. Yet for the odd postcard and ice
cream, they will have to rely on the national currencies for three
more years. Euro notes and coins won't be issued until the first
half of 2002 only.
	   Banks, bonds and stock markets and international businesses do
not have that leeway and will spend the whole New Year weekend
adapting trading floors and computer screens to include the joint
currency to be ready when the euro shows up for its first working
day on Monday.
	   ``We will be forced to deal simultaneously with francs and euros
in our whole computer system during the first three-year period.
That's why we had to change 60,000 of our computer systems,'' said
Jean-Francois Colin, euro coordinator of France's Banque Nationale
de Paris.
	   The markets also want to minimize the risk of last minute
foul-ups during the few days of transition.
	   ``There is a lot of work that goes into the planning for this.
Banks and institutions have been working for many, many years.
We've had lots of dress rehearsals, lots of testing,'' said
Margaret Soden, a senior Manager of euro planning at the
London-based HSBC Bank.
	   There will also be festive events. Balloons, bearing the euro
symbol, will be sent skywards from EU headquarters in Brussels.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-The Euro; CT:i; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
