<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Izetbegovic </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bosnia's Muslim leader: optimistic about politics, pessimistic
</HEADLINE>
about economy in 1999

<TEXT>
	   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ Bosnia's Muslim leader is
predicting membership in the European Union next year despite
continued ethnic unrest, corruption and a sickly post-war economy
that is expected to continue to underperform in 1999.
	   ``We expect ... membership in the European Union,'' said Alija
Izetbegovic, the Muslim member of Bosnia's presidential troika.
Bosnia is not being considered for membership by the EU, and it was
unclear what Izetbegovic's optimism was based on _ even countries
being actively considered are not likely to be offered membership
as early as next year.
	   The 73-year-old leader of the Muslim Party of Democratic Action
spoke at his traditional year's end news conference. He said that
because of an expected decrease in foreign donations and plans to
sell parts of the state-run economy, the country will be facing
economic and social difficulties next year.
	   He blamed rampant corruption in the country on ``the fact that
the borders are open, uncontrolled, which gives endless
opportunities for smuggling and cheating on the state.''
	   Izetbegovic said attempts to unify the country in the wake of
war that ended in 1995 have foundered because of obstacles posed by
Bosnia's neighbors, Croatia, and Serb-dominated Yugoslavia.
	   (acr/asd/gj)
</TEXT>
