<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Burundi-Killings </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hutu rebels kill eight in two separate attacks
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUJUMBURA, Burundi (AP) _ Hutu rebels attempting to overthrow
the Tutsi-led government killed eight people and wounded another in
two separate attacks, government officials said.
	   The attacks took place late Tuesday in the province of Muramvya,
50 kilometers (22 miles) west of the capital, Bujumbura. One of the
victims was a local official; two others were teachers.
	   The killings were the latest in a spate of rebel attacks to hit
this tiny Central African nation. Insurgents killed four people,
including an agriculture official, in raids overnight Sunday in the
town of Buhonga, 5 miles south of the capital.
	   The rebels, who claim to represent the country's 85 percent Hutu
majority, are fighting to overthrow the government of Pierre
Buyoya, a retired Tutsi military officer, who seized the presidency
in a bloodless coup in 1996.
	   Bloodshed between the rebels and the Tutsi-dominated military
has claimed more than 200,000 lives, most of them civilian, since
1993, when Tutsi paratroopers killed the country's first
democratically elected president, a Hutu.
	   Talks on ending the conflict are scheduled to resume next month
in Arusha, Tanzania.
	   (cn/cn)	   
</TEXT>
