u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Zimbabwe-Congo     12-30 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Zimbabwe-Congo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Allied forces claim gains in Congo fighting
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANGUS SHAW &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ The Zimbabwe government claimed
Wednesday that allied forces of Congolese President Laurent have
captured two key towns from rebels.
	   The offensive began Dec. 25. and has halted rebel advances in
north and eastern Congo, the government said in a communique.
	   It said Allied Task Force headquarters in the Congolese capital,
Kinshasa, reported heavy enemy casualties in air strikes on rebel
and Rwandan and Ugandan positions along the Congo river with no
losses of allied aircraft.
	   None of the communique's claims could be independently
confirmed.
	   Zimbabwe has 8,000 troops backed by armor and warplanes fighting
alongside Congolese, Angolan, Chadian and Namibian troops in the
five-month Congo war.
	   An ``intensified offensive'' launched on Christmas Day ``largely
immobilized the invading forces and thwarted their attempts at any
further territorial gain,'' the Zimbabwe government said.
	   The communique gave no details of allied casualties. Zimbabwe
has said that 26 of its soldiers died in Congo since mid-August,
most in fighting over Kabalo that began two weeks ago.
	   The government said that Congolese forces on Monday captured the
town of Fizi, close to the border with Burundi, and this cut off a
key rebel supply route from their strongholds of Goma and Bukavu.
	   In the north, also on Monday, allies took control of the
rebel-held town of Businga near Gbadolite, the document said.
	   Gbadolite was the home of former Zairean dictator Mobutu Sese
Seko, who died shortly after being ousted by Kabila nearly two
years ago.
	   The communique said the allies captured former ethnic Hutu
militants who claimed they were released from Rwandan jails on
condition they join rebel forces. The captured men said they were
to help hold the strategic eastern town of Kabalo commanded by
Rwandan Tutsi officers.
	   It also alleged Ugandan forces were enticing retired Tanzanian
soldiers to join the rebels ``through offers of high financial
incentives and other lucrative packages.''
	   The Congolese rebels, backed by Rwanda and Uganda, are a
coalition of ethnic Tutsis, disaffected soldiers and opposition
politicians who took up arms Aug. 2 to topple Kabila. They accuse
him of corruption and fomenting ethnic war.
	   International efforts to broker a cease fire have been blocked
by Kabila's persistent refusal to negotiate with the rebels. He
accuses them of being puppets of Rwanda and Uganda.
	   (as-pr)
</TEXT>
