<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cyprus-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkish Cypriots form new government
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) _ President Rauf Denktash on Wednesday
approved a coalition government that promises to seek international
recognition for the breakaway Turkish Cypriot state and remain in
close cooperation in Turkey.
	   Dervis Eroglu remains premier under a coalition partnership with
a center-left party, led by Mustafa Akinci. Eroglu has led
goverments on the Turkish side of the divided island of Cyprus
since 1996.
	   ``Our foreign policy is based on the integration of Turkish
Cypriots with Turkey through a special relationship,'' the Turkish
Cypriot news agency TAK quoted Denktash as saying. ``It appears
that the new government will remain loyal to these principles.''
	   Cyprus has been split in two since 1974, when Turkey sent in
troops after a coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
	   The Turkish Cypriots declared their own state in 1983, which is
recognized only by Turkey.
	   U.N. efforts to reunify the island have failed and the Turkish
Cypriots now insist on international recognition before talks can
resume.
	   Eroglu's center-right National Unity Party won 24 seats in the
Dec 6. elections. Akinci's Salvation party has seven seats in the
50-member Parliament. Akinci is to serve as deputy premier in the
11-member Cabinet.
	   Eroglu received 40 percent of the votes in the elections, seen
as voter approval for his hard-line stance on the future of his
republic.
	   (sf-ek)
</TEXT>
