<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-BBC Blunder </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BBC faces the music as cricket fans miss famous victory
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ They wanted to watch Headley and Gough. Instead,
it was Handel and Grieg.
	   Thanks to a blunder by the BBC, thousands of cricket fans
watched an introduction to classical music for children on Tuesday
instead of the final few exciting overs of England's unexpected
12-run win over Australia.
	   While Dean Headley and Darren Gough bowled out the Australians
for England's victory in Melbourne, viewers who switched on around
breakfast time back in England didn't see a ball bowled.
	   ``We've had hundreds of calls,'' a BBC spokesman said. ``At one
point there were 60 people waiting on the lines to make an official
complaint.''
	   Although the BBC changed the schedules last week, the
alterations didn't make the daily papers.
	   Tuesday's victory lifted the spirits of England's downhearted
cricket followers and was celebrated nationwide, even though the
Australians, 2-1 ahead in the series, have already made sure of the
big prize, keeping the Ashes.
	   England can still tie the series by winning the final test at
Sydney on Saturday.
	   (rjm) 	   
</TEXT>
