<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yugoslavia seeks to have Kosovo rebels declared terrorists
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMS. UPDATES with Kosovo newspaper ban, body found. Changes
byline.
 &UR; By MISHA SAVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Kosovo was reported quiet Wednesday,
but a top government official in the ethnic Albanian majority
province warned a new offensive was possible anytime authorities
deemed it necessary.
	   Veljko Odalovic, the province's leading official, accused the
Kosovo Liberation Army of taking advantage of an October truce to
take positions abandoned by withdrawing Serbian police and Yugoslav
army.
	   ``We have to defend our state, its integrity and people ... with
or without the international community,'' said Odalovic in an
interview with the Belgrade daily Glas. ``There will be problems,
but we will punish the last terrorist.''
	   Odalovic's comments heightened concerns that the October truce,
mediated by American diplomats, could collapse altogether.
	   Four days of fierce fighting last week in northern Kosovo
claimed at least 15 lives and sent thousands fleeing. Ethnic
Albanian sources reported that the body of an elderly ethnic
Albanian was found Wednesday near Lapastica, 30 kilometers (20
miles) north of Pristina, and that he was presumably killed during
last week's clashes.
	   Serb officials accuse the KLA of triggering the clashes by
attacking police and army units. Yugoslavia, formed of Serbia and
Montenegro, on Tuesday urged the United Nations to declare the KLA
a terrorist organization and crack down on their support network
abroad.
	   The guerillas assert they are only responding to attacks on
them. They received a psychological boost on Wednesday, when an
alliance of radical Kosovo Albanian parties expressed full support
Wednesday for the Kosovo Liberation Army.
	   ``The Kosovo Liberation Army is the central national, political
and moral force,'' said Rexhep Qosja, the leader of six parties and
political groups of ethnic Albanians in the Serbian province.
	   The alliance is a rival of the main ethnic Albanian leader,
Ibrahim Rugova, despite their common ultimate goal of an
independent Kosovo. Though most Kosovo Albanians still support
Rugova, the statement was symbolically important to the KLA, which
is at odds with the Rugova camp.
	   Kosovo's Serb-Albanian struggle continued Wednesday despite the
lack of reported violence, with a state-run printing house in
Kosovo serving notice it would stop printing the oldest
Albanian-language daily in the Serbian province.
	   Bujku is one of the three largest dailies in the ethnic-Albanian
majority province.
	   The authoritarian Serbian government, after cracking down
earlier this year on Serbian-language papers in the country, has
moved to suppress Albanian-language papers because of their support
for Kosovo's independence from Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant
republic. Bujku is the first Kosovo Albanian newspaper targeted.
	   Odalovic, the senior Kosovo official, accused the
independence-seeking rebels of trying to frighten the minority
Serbs into leaving Kosovo and create an ethnically pure Albanian
land. Ethnic Albanians make up some 90 percent of the population in
Kosovo, while the Serb population has decreased in the past
decades.
	   ``There can be only one state here, one authority, one police
and one army. There is no space for any paramilitary forces,'' said
Odalovic, referring to the ethnic Albanians' struggle to form their
own state in Kosovo since Serbia revoked their autonomy in 1989.
	   A Serb crackdown against KLA earlier this year claimed over
1,000 lives and left some 300,000 people homeless. Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic ended it in the face of the threat of
NATO airstrikes.
	   NATO has said it is ready to act in fighting in Kosovo flares up
again.
	   Yugoslavia's Serb-led government claims the ethnic Albanian
Kosovo Liberation Army is a terrorist organization which should be
branded as such by world leaders in order to restrict its support
from Albanian expatriate communities in Switzerland, Germany and
elsewhere.
	   Yugoslavia's foreign minister, Zivadin Jovanovic, claimed
Tuesday the rebels have carried out 470 attacks since the October
agreement, including the killing of ethnic Albanians loyal to the
government.
	   (pvs/ms/gj)
</TEXT>
