w2978 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-Premier     12-30 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Premier League </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Villa stays ahead in wide open title race
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT MILLWARD &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The last Premier League game of 1998 was a
goal-less tie between the two favorites for the title, Chelsea and
Manchester United. That doesn't mean the second half of the
championship race is going to be a bore _ it should be anything
but.
	   If Chelsea's Tore Andre Flo and Gianfranco Zola had capitalized
on their chances, the Blues would have beaten the Reds 4-0 and
replaced Aston Villa at the top in one of the most open title races
in years.
	   The tie at Stamford Bridge means that Villa still leads Chelsea
by two points. Manchester United, two points further behind in
third place, remains well in contention to win its fifth title in
seven seasons.
	   Behind United on goal difference is defending champion Arsenal,
which appears to have recovered from its injury crisis and is well
placed to mount another challenge.
	   Leeds, holding steady at fifth, is another contender although
new manager David O'Leary fears that his young team is a little too
inexperienced to reach the top just yet.
	   Don't rule out Liverpool, which has won three games in a row
under French coach Gerard Houllier. Its last was a spectacular
turnaround from two goals down against Newcastle, winning 4-2 with
two strikes each by Michael Owen and KarlHeinz Riedle.
	   Liverpool, which had gone through its worst winless run for 44
years, is back up to seventh although it still has eight points to
make up on surprise leader Villa.
	   John Gregory's Villa soared to the top Sept. 12 and has proved
difficult to replace.
	   Chelsea, whose only league title triumph was in 1955, has twice
made it to No. 1 in the past two weeks on the back of 19 games
unbeaten but didn't stay there very long. Villa's players reacted
with winning performances to make sure they remained at the top at
the end of 1998 with 20 of the 38 Premier League games now behind
them.
	   Gregory puts some of his team's success down to the fact that he
is fielding an entirely English-born lineup with no problems with
language or adjusting to the cold, wet English climate.
	   Apart from Stan Collymore, who runs into discipinary trouble on
and off the field, Gregory has few big names on his team. But
younsters such as Lee Hendrie, 21, and Gareth Barry, 17, are rated
as future England stars.
	   ``We have won more games than anyone and, if we carry on doing
that, we have as good a chance as anyone,'' Gregory said.
	   ``The Premier League dictates that you have to play 38 matches
at high tempo. Whoever wins the title earns it. You are never given
anything on a plate.''
	   The feeling is that Villa, which last won the title 18 seasons
ago, won't last the pace, and bookmakers Ladbrokes haven't changed
their odds after the recent two rounds of matches.
	   They rate Chelsea and Manchester United the joint 7-4 favorites
to win the title with Arsenal third at 4-1 and Villa at 11-2.
Liverpool, which last won the league title in 1990, is rated a 20-1
shot compared with 33-1 three weeks ago while Leeds, titlist in
1992, is 25-1.
	   While Villa relies almost entirely on home grown talent, Chelsea
can field a cosmopolitan lineup of overseas stars while United,
Arsenal, Leeds and Liverpool each have a balance between the two.
	   Eight players from Chelsea, United and Arsenal were on the
French and Dutch squads that made the World Cup semifinal. Franck
Leboeuf and Marcel Desailly (Chelsea) and Patrick Vieira and
Emmanuel Petit (Arsenal) went on to lift the trophy in Paris as
France beat Brazil in the final.
	   The Premier League is on hold for two weeks while the clubs
enter the FA Cup at the third round stage this weekend.
	   That means the clubs can take their minds off the title race
until Jan. 9 when Villa goes to Middlesbrough, Chelsea visits
Newcastle, Arsenal hosts Liverpool and Leeds goes to Blackburn
Rovers.
	   (rjm) 	   
</TEXT>
