<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Cyprus Missiles, 1st Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkey threatens to maintain pressure over Russian missiles
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS to UPDATE with Russia indicating it still expects to be
paid for missiles &QL; 
 &UR; By SUZAN FRASER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ Turkey claimed victory Wednesday in Greek
Cypriots' decision to cancel deployment of Russian-made missiles on
Cyprus _ but warned it would use force to prevent their
installation on the Greek island of Crete.
	   Greek Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides announced the
cancellation of the planned deployment late Tuesday. He said he
would negotiate with Russian officials for the deployment of the
S-300 surface-to-air missiles on Crete, instead.
	   ``We would take all appropriate political and military means if
they were to be deployed in Crete,'' Turkish Foreign Minister
Ismail Cem told reporters Wednesday.
	   ``If there is a threat directed toward Turkey, then we will do
the necessary analysis and respond accordingly.''
	   The Mediterranean island of Cyprus is divided between two
hostile republics _ one Greek Cypriot, one Turkish Cypriot.
	   Turkey had threatened to use military strikes to block the
missiles' deployment on Cyprus ever since plans were announced two
years ago.
	   The United States and NATO also criticized the decision as
potentially leading to conflict between NATO members Turkey and
Greece.
	   There was no firm decision on what would happen to the missiles.
Some reports suggested the missiles would now be stored.
	   Russian Foreign Minister Vladimir Rakhmanin indicated Wednesday
that Moscow still expected to be paid for the missiles.
	   ``The Russian-Cypriot contact has an exclusively commercial
character. The Russian side will strictly fulfill this contract,''
Rakhmanin said in a statement. ``It is important that the
recipients of the complexes fulfill their primary obligations.''
	   ``Any possibility of changing the parameters of the contract is
a question for the orderer, the government of the Republic of
Cyprus, and the supplier, the state arms exporter
Rosvooruzheniye,'' he said.
	   Greece strongly, 7th graf pvs
