<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-World Court-Guinea-Congo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Guinea takes businessman's dispute with Congo to UN court
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ Guinea has asked the World Court
to condemn the Democratic Republic of Congo for grave breaches of
international law for expelling a Guinean national from Congo, then
Zaire, in 1996 and stripping him off his assets.
	   The case concerns a businessman called Ahmadou Sadio Diallo who
had lived and worked in Congo for 32 years before being jailed for
two and a half months and deported from the country in February
1996, according to brief details of Guinea's unilateral application
released by the court on Wednesday.
	   Diallo also was ``divested from his important investments,
companies, bank accounts, movable and immovable properties,''
Guinea claims. Among companies owing him an undisclosed amount of
money are the Congolese branches of oil giants Mobil, Shell and
Fina, according to the claim which was filed Dec. 28.
	   No further details were immediately available.
	   Formally known as the International Court of Justice, the
Hague-based World Court is the United Nations' highest judicial
organ, dealing with disputes between nations. It relies on nations
to voluntarily comply with its rulings.
	   Congo did not immediately file a response to Guinea's
application to the court and no schedule has yet been set for the
proceedings.
	   (mc) 	   
</TEXT>
