<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Police Brutality </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian authorities log more than 40,000 complaints of police
</HEADLINE>
brutality &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The Russian Interior Ministry logged more than
40,000 complaints of police brutality in 1998, and more than 5,000
led to disciplinary action against police, the government said
Wednesday.
	   Sergei Shadrin, deputy chief of the ministry's Internal Security
Department, said 2,800 cases of brutality were sent to prosecutors
and criminal proceedings were instituted in 1,347 cases, ITAR-Tass
reported.
	   The report did not say how many led to convictions.
	   Another top official, Vladimir Fyodorov of the road police, said
corruption remained a serious problem among police who patrol
Russia's roads. Most Russian motorists would agree.
	   He said there were more than 7,300 anti-corruption operations
launched against road police in 1998, leading to disciplinary
action against 2,944 officers and criminal procedings against 53.
	   Also, he said, 66 were punished for bribery and five for
extortion. ``We realize this is only the tip of the iceberg,''
Fyodorov said, according to ITAR-Tass.
	   (ml)
</TEXT>
