<SLUG> BC-Yemen-German Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru,0298 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security officials say 4 German hostages freed
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Combines urgent series &QL; 
 &UR; With Yemen-Kidnapping &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ Four Germans taken captive by Yemeni
tribesmen on Dec. 7 were set free on Wednesday, Yemeni security
officials said.
	   They said the four _ three women and a man _ were in good
condition and were on their way to the Yemeni capital San`a. The
officials spoke on customary condition of anonymity.
	   There was no information on whether the government had agreed to
the kidnappers' demands for better public services.
	   The release of the Germans came a day after Yemeni security
forces confronted Islamic militants holding 16 Western hostages.
Four of the captives died in the melee.
	   Bani Dhabyan gunmen abducted the Germans on Dec. 7 in Marib
province, which is 170 kilometers (105 miles) southeast of San`a.
	   The Bani Dhabyan were pressing the government to provide more
schools, hospitals, telephone lines and roads for their region.
	   German officials had expressed concern about the hostages,
especially a woman who reportedly was ill.
	   A Yemeni newspaper has identified them as Norbert Degen, Petra
Penglista, Rozwita Adlung and Inge Brunner. The embassy has not
confirmed the names.
	   The tribal leader said the health of 64-year-old Brunner, who
suffers from high blood pressure, was of concern.
	   But he said the hostages received medicine for Brunner along
with Christmas gifts of chocolates and cigarettes from the embassy.
	   Kidnappings occur frequently in Yemen, large parts of which are
controlled by armed tribesmen who do not hesitate to take the law
into their own hands to get their demands fulfilled. The hostages
are usually treated well and released unhurt.
</TEXT>
