<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Miners' Protests </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Miners suspend underground sit-in until the end March
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Miners from the Solidarity union on
Wednesday further suspended their protest and gave the union-rooted
government until the end of March to produce a bill guaranteeing
them early retirement privileges.
	   The protest that involved several hundred miners taking part in
underground sit-ins at some 50 mines in southern Poland was
originally suspended Dec. 23, after the government promised miners
would retain early retirement schemes.
	   Union leaders said the protest will continue under the form of
meetings and rallies. The sit-in could be resumed ``as soon as the
government tries to go back on its promises,'' said Henryk
Nakonieczny, head of miner's Solidarity.
	   Under an agreement reached last week, the government proposed
miners would receive so-called ``bridge'' pensions of 70 percent of
their monthly wages if they retire with 25 years of service before
the legal age. They would receive the regular full pension when
they reach the legal retirement age.
	   Miners want the provision guaranteed in a bill later next year
that will spell out details of retirement rules for miners and
workers employed in dangerous conditions.
	   On Tuesday, President Aleksander Kwasniewski signed into law the
new pension system, in line with Western standards, that sets
retirement age at 65 for men and 60 for women, but Nakonieczny said
it did not affect the miners, who trust the agreement with the
government.
 &UR; (ms-ajs-gb)
</TEXT>
