<HEADLINE>
BAGHDAD: the zone.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   It was the second American-Iraqi missile exchange in a no-fly
zone this week.
	   On Monday, U.S. warplanes fired missiles at an Iraqi air defense
post in the north after the Iraqis fired surface-to-air missiles at
the jets. Iraqi military officials said that four soldiers were
killed and seven injured.
	   The northern zone was set up by the United States and its allis
in 1991 to protect Iraqi Kurds after a failed uprising against
Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein following the Gulf War. The southern
zone was set up the following year to protect Iraqi Shiite Muslims.
	   The zones are patrolled by British and American warplanes flying
from neighboring countries or from ships in the Gulf.
