<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Algeria </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Eight members of Islamic group found dead
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) _ Eight members of the Islamic Salvation
Army, which has laid down its arms, were found dead Wednesday,
victims of an attack by active Islamic militants, local residents
said.
	   The eight men were shot and their throats were slit in the
attack in Ouled Azza, near Ain Defla, 120 kilometers (75 miles)
southwest of Algiers. It wasn't immediately clear when the attack
took place.
	   The residents, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
victims were killed by the Armed Islamic Group, the most radical
rebel group in Algeria's seven-year insurgency.
	   The victims used to belong to the Armed Islamic Group, but
defected to the Islamic Salvation Army, prompting what appeared to
be a settling of scores, the residents said.
	   An estimated 75,000 people have been killed since the start of
Algeria's insurgency, triggered by an army decision to cancel
elections the Islamic Salvation Front was poised to win.
	   The Islamic Salvation Army is the military wing of the Islamic
Salvation Front, which reached a truce with the government in
October last year.
	   (parf/ip)
</TEXT>
