w1081 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-SoldiersKil 4rdLd-Writethru   12-30 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Soldiers Killed, 4rd Ld-Writethru,0575 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Villagers kill eight soldiers, mob attacks police in northwest
</HEADLINE>
Indonesia
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with remarks from local police chief that one was
found alive; burning in separate incident, grafs 4-5, 12-13 &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ A mob of 200 villagers, some armed
with machetes, tortured and killed seven Indonesian soldiers after
stopping a public bus. On Wednesday, rioters in the same area
attacked a police station and burned two police cars.
	   The violence in northwestern Aceh province was likely to raise
tensions in a region where the Indonesian military recently ended a
decade-long campaign against separatist rebels.
	   Officials suspect guerrilla followers were behind the slayings
of the soldiers on Tuesday.
	   More than 300 personnel of the police's special force of Brimob
have been mobilized to hunt the suspected guerillas who fled after
the attack, said Col. Djuharnus Wiradinata, chief of Aceh Police.
	   The official Antara news agency quoted Wiradinata as telling a
news conference in Aceh's capital of Banda Aceh on Wednesday that
one of the eight soldiers was found alive with wounds, while five
bodies of the seven were believed to have been dumped into a river.
	   Accused of widespread atrocities in Aceh, the military
apologized and withdrew some troops in a conciliatory gesture after
the resignation in May of former President Suharto. However,
resentment toward the military remains deep.
	   In Jakarta, armed forces chief Gen. Wiranto said the attack on
off-duty soldiers could jeopardize a plan to reduce the military
presence by entrusting community leaders with security.
	   ``The killing was a brutal action which can never be tolerated
by the armed forces,'' Wiranto said. ``This action could spoil the
wishes of the Aceh people to free the region of military
operations.''
	   The assailants forced the victims to get off a bus in the
village of Lhok Nibung that was heading to the nearby city of
Medan. Ten other soldiers managed to escape and reported to their
superiors, who dispatched hundreds of troops to search for the
killers.
	   Wiranto said eight soldiers were killed and that 25 people
suspected of provoking the mob attack were arrested.
	   In a separate incident in the nearby town of Lhokseumawe, a mob
of 500 people hurled stones at a police station after a dispute
between a policeman and a security guard at a neighboring building.
There were no reported injuries or arrests.
	   The mob also burned down three cars and four motorcycles during
the predawn assault, Wiradinata said.
	   According to Antara, the mob also tried to attack a nearby
military post but dispersed as soldiers at the post fired warning
shots.
	   Lhokseumawe, a center of Indonesia's oil and gas industry, was
hit by anti-military rioting in August and November.
	   Aceh, about 1,750 kilometers (1,100 miles) northwest of Jakarta,
is a staunchly Muslim province where rebels have been fighting for
an Islamic state for decades.
	   The military has acknowledged that 760 people died in fighting
since the late 1980s, although human rights groups put the death
toll higher. Mass graves have been uncovered and some widows have
alleged they were raped by soldiers.
	   Separatist guerrilla movements also operate in the remote
province of Irian Jaya and the former Portuguese colony of East
Timor.
</TEXT>
