w1082 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Yeltsin-Clinto     12-30 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Yeltsin-Clinton </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin castigates Clinton for strikes on Iraq
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's Boris Yeltsin listened to Bill Clinton's
arguments for military action against Iraq, but reiterated his
strong objections to U.S. and British raids in a telephone
conversation Wednesday.
	   ``The Russian president confirmed his firm assessment that the
Anglo-American action is unacceptable from the point of view of
international law, the United Nations Charter and the principles of
partnership and cooperation,'' Yeltsin's office said in a statement
released to the news media.
	   Yeltsin struck the same chord in his traditional New Year's
message to Clinton, saying that ``attempts to solve international
crises by force, especially circumventing the competent
international organizations, are unacceptable.''
	   Moscow condemned U.S. and British raids against Iraq earlier
this month in angry rhetoric eerily reminiscent of the Cold War era
and briefly recalled its ambassadors to Washington and London.
Russian officials have since softened their tone, stressing they
want to have good relations with the United States and Britain.
	   During their conversation Wednesday, the first since they met in
Moscow in September, Yeltsin and Clinton sought to mend ties
damaged by differences over Iraq. Both presidents spoke for ``the
preservation and development of the positive potential accumulated
in the Russian-American relations over the past years,'' the
Kremlin statement said.
	   They exchanged New Year greetings and noted the next year's
``importance for the preservation of atmosphere of trust and
further progress in relations between Russia and the United
States.''
	   In Washington, White House spokesman David Leavy said Clinton
and Yeltsin expressed their differences over Iraq but agreed not to
allow that to disrupt U.S.-Russian relations.
	   Leavy said Yeltsin did not specifically mention the incidents
Monday and today in which Iraqi air defense units have fired
missiles at U.S. and British aircraft patrolling ``no-fly'' zones
in northern and southern Iraq.
	   The Russian Foreign Ministry expressed concern Wednesday about
missile exchanges and urged both sides to show restraint, stopping
short of outright condemnation of the U.S. and British action.
	   In the talk with Clinton, Yeltsin called for ``restoring the
unity of the U.N. Security Council and coming back on a peaceful
way of Iraqi settlement,'' the Kremlin said.
	   Moscow, which is owed billions of dollars by Iraq in Soviet-era
debts, has pushed for the early lifting of the U.N. sanctions
against Iraq while urging its long-time ally to comply with the
U.N. resolutions.
	   Leavy said that Yeltsin said he continues to support
ratification of the START II arms reduction treaty with the United
States, indefinitely put on hold by the Communist-dominated Russian
parliament after the strikes on Iraq. The Kremlin statement didn't
mention the issue.
	   The two leaders also discussed plans for Vice President Al Gore
to meet with Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov in March and Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright to meet with Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov in Moscow in late January.
	   (vi/ml)
</TEXT>
