<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq, 1st Ld-2nd Add,0281 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAGHDAD: the Gulf.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Iraq has remained defiant. The Baghdad government announced
Tuesday that its aircraft were flying in the no-fly zones. And it
said anti-aircraft batteries remained ready to fire on allied
planes that enter Iraqi airspace.
	   However, Pentagon spokesman Col. Richard Bridges said Wednesday
there have been no reported sightings of Iraqi planes in the air in
the past few days.
	   Iraq's stance appeared aimed at building Arab support for its
plight following mid-December airstrikes by American and British
jets to punish the Baghdad regime for failing to cooperate with
U.N. weapons inspectors.
	   On Tuesday, Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan was asked by
Associated Press Television News whether Iraq was flying aircraft
in no-fly zones. He answered: ``We are doing it right now.''
	   ``Iraqi planes in effect are flying in a normal manner in Iraqi
airspace,'' he said.
	   Ramadan did not specify whether the aircraft were military or
civilian, but almost all of Iraq's passenger aircraft are either
out of the country or unusable. All aircraft in Iraq are owned by
the government.
	   France initially participated in patrolling the zones.
	   But Paris withdrew from northern zone patrols in 1996, and
Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret confirmed Tuesday
that French planes stopped participating in patrols over southern
Iraq on Dec. 16, the first day of airstrikes.
	   Ramadan on Tuesday reiterated the government's stance that it
does not recognize the zones.
	   ``The so-called air exclusion zones exist only in the sick
imagination of the British and American administrations,'' he said.
</TEXT>
