w1096 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-India-PoliceInquiry     12-30 0274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Police Inquiry,0274 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Judge's report says police firing on low caste Hindus unjustified
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ A report by a Bombay judge released
Wednesday criticized police for the shooting of 10 low-caste Hindus
killed during a protest last year.
	   As many as 32 others were injured when police opened fire in a
Bombay slum during a protest over the descreation of a low-caste
leader's statue.
	   ``The police firing was without warning, unjustified,
unwarranted and indiscriminate,'' Judge Sudhakar Gundewar said in
his report, which specifically blamed two police officers in the
shootings.
	   On July 11, 1997 a crowd of protesters stopped traffic and threw
stones when they discovered that a garland of shoes _ considered an
insult in India _ had been draped around the statue of their hero
Babasaheb Ambedkar.
	   Ambedkar is an icon for the lower castes. He helped write
India's constitution and was a leader of India's independence
struggle against British rule.
	   Police said they were forced to open fire when the mob
threatened to throw burning tires at nearby gas tankers. An
explosion would have killed many more, the police said.
	   The judge rejected the police explanation, saying they did not
make enough efforts to disperse the mob.
	   The government said one of the officers cited by the judge had
been suspended but that it had not decided on an action to be taken
against the second officer.
	   The judge began the inquiry in November last year and submitted
his report to the state government a couple of months ago, but it
was initially kept confidential to give officials time to respond.
</TEXT>
