<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Brazil-Best of 1998,0234 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Paraguay's Gamarra wins Player of Year award
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) _ Brazilians like to say they have
the world's best soccer players, but the top player in Brazil is
from Paraguay.
	   Paraguayan fullback Gamarra, the captain of Brazilian champion
Corinthians, was named the outstanding player of the year by the
Brazilian Soccer Confederation.
	   Gamarra, who is rumored to be headed for Paris Saint-Germain
next season, was awarded a trophy and a prize of 30,000 reals (dlrs
25,000). ``This is a tremendous honor for me,'' he said in a mix of
his native Spanish and Brazil's Portuguese.
	   Corinthians won a slew of honors, including best-disciplined
team and coach of the year for Wanderley Luxemburgo, who also
assumed the Brazilian national team duties in August.
	   The scoring title went to Santos striker Viola, who scored 21
goals. The league's goalkeeper award went to Andre of
Internacional, who received his first call to the national team in
1998.
	   The title of revelation of the year went to Fabio Junior, the
21-year-old striker of Cruzeiro, who also was selected for the
national team.
	   The national championship honorary all-star team was comprised
of Dida in goal; Arce, Gamarra, Cesar and Felipe on defense;
midfielders Vampeta, Djair, Jackson and Valdo; and Fabio Junior and
Viola as forwards.
</TEXT>
