<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Track-St Silvester,0413 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South America's biggest city set for New Year's Eve tradition
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By STAN LEHMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) _ The cars, trucks and buses that
normally clog the streets of South America's biggest city will
vanish Thursday as thousands of athletes from around the world
compete in the traditional year-ending St. Silvester road race.
	   On Thursday, more than 12,000 athletes _ about 11,000 men and
1,000 women _ from some 15 countries will run in the 15-kilometer
(9.3 mile) route along the wide, skyscraper-lined avenues and
through the narrow, twisting streets of this city of 10 million.
	   Competing for a top prize of 10,000 reals (dlrs 8,350), women
athletes start the race at 3:15 p.m. (1715 GMT), and men set out at
5:00 p.m. (1900 GMT).
	   This year's field includes about 500 foreign runners, including
Kenyan Paul Tergat, the 1995 and 1996 St. Silvester champion.
	   Marcelo Eduardo Braga, one of the organizers of the event said
Tergat is one of the top favorites to win the men's division.
Others include Brazil's Ronaldo da Costa, who earlier this year
broke the marathon world record in Berlin; defending champion
Emerson Iser Bem, also of Brazil; and South Africa's Hendrick
Ramaala.
	   Other runners will come from Yugolsavia, Mexico, Colombia,
Ecuador, Chile, Argentina, Portugal, Uruguay, Paraguay, Peru and
Italy.
	   Tergat isn't as confident as some of his supporters.
	   ``I haven't run a race since September, so I can't promise
anything,'' he said.
	   Iser Bem, who has been preparing since October, says he isn't
necessarily looking for victory.
	   ``All I want to do is come in among the top five finishers,'' he
said.
	   In the women's category, Ecuador's Martha Tenorio, who won the
St. Silvester in 1987 and 1997 is among the favorites.
	   Three-time winner Maria del Carmen Diaz of Mexico and Brazil's
Viviany Anderson Oliveira also top the field.
	   ``I have come to win my third St. Silvester victory,'' Tenorio
said. ``This has been one my best years ever.''
	   ``I hope one day I will equal the record established by Rosa
Mota,'' she added, referring to the Portuguese who won the St.
Silvester every from 1981 to 1986.
	   The race is named after St. Silvester, the Roman Catholic saint
whose feast day is celebrated Dec. 31. It was first run in 1924,
started by Casper Libero, founder of the Gazeta Esportiva
newspaper, the event's main sponsor.
</TEXT>
