<SLUG> BC-Iraq, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraq says U.S. attack kills farmer, injures two civilians
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: COMBINES urgent series, CORRECTS quote in 4th graf, UPDATES in
first 15 grafs with more details from Iraqi statement, TRIMS. &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-US-Iraq &QL; 
 &UR; By LOUIS MEIXLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraq said Wednesday that U.S. aircraft fire
killed a farmer and wounded two other civilians in a village in
southern Iraq.
	   The American jets reportedly retaliated after an Iraqi
anti-aircraft battery fired on British planes patrolling a
``no-fly'' zone in the south.
	   The statement, carried by the official Iraqi News Agency, made
no mention of military casualties.
	   The report also claimed that Iraq ``almost certainly shot down
one of the planes.''
	   It was the second such claim in recent days, but officials at
the Pentagon said that all U.S. and British aircraft again returned
safely to their bases.
	   Washington officials said the U.S. warplanes fired missiles and
laser-guided bombs at an anti-aircraft battery after the Iraqis
fired missiles at British aircraft patrolling the southern no-fly
zone. Iraq has never recognized the zone.
	   It was the second American-Iraqi missile exchange in a no-fly
zone this week.
	   On Monday, U.S. warplanes fired missiles at an Iraqi air defense
post in the north after the Iraqis fired surface-to-air missiles at
the jets. Iraqi military officials said that four soldiers were
killed and seven injured.
	   Iraq had claimed to have downed a plane Monday, but was never
able to produce wreckage and the Western allies said they lost no
jets.
	   The northern no-fly zone was set up by the United States and its
allies in 1991 to protect Iraqi Kurds after a failed uprising
against Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein following the Gulf War. The
southern zone was set up the following year to protect Iraqi Shiite
Muslims.
	   The zones are patrolled by British and American warplanes flying
from neighboring countries or from ships in the Gulf. Their mission
is to keep Iraqi planes out of the air.
	   On Wednesday, Iraq said its forces opened fire after ``the
criminals once again committed an aggression against the integrity
of our national airspace,'' INA said.
	   It said Iraqi troops fired ``a number of surface-to-air missiles
at one of these enemy formations'' and forced it to flee. It said
that a second group of aircraft approached about 45 minutes later
``and fired a number of cowardly missiles on a farming village.''
	   The statement carried by the news agency said a farmer was
killed and that his brother and a woman were wounded. A tractor was
destroyed, it added.
	   The Baghdad government announced Tuesday that its aircraft were
flying in the no-fly zones. And it said anti-aircraft batteries
remained ready to fire on allied planes that enter Iraqi airspace.
	   However, Pentagon spokesman Col. Richard Bridges said Wednesday
there have been no reported sightings of Iraqi planes in the air in
the past few days.
	   Iraq's stance appeared aimed at building Arab support for its
plight following mid-December airstrikes by American and British
jets to punish the Baghdad regime for failing to cooperate with
U.N. weapons inspectors.
	   On Tuesday, Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan was asked by
Associated Press Television News whether Iraq was flying aircraft
in no-fly zones. He answered: ``We are doing it right now.''
	   ``Iraqi planes in effect are flying in a normal manner in Iraqi
airspace,'' he said.
	   Iraq has never recognized the zones, and Ramadan repeated the
government's view Tuesday.
	   ``The so-called air exclusion zones exist only in the sick
imagination of the British and American administrations,'' he said.
 &UR; lm-eap
</TEXT>
