w1112 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Olympics-IOCPr     12-30 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-IOC Probe </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOC inquiry could take longer than expected
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By STEPHEN WILSON &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The IOC may not complete its investigation into
alleged vote-buying during Salt Lake City's successful bid for the
2002 Winter Olympics as quickly as planned.
	   IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch said two weeks ago he
wanted the inquiry wrapped up by the end of January and he called a
special meeting for Jan. 23-24 to act on the case.
	   But International Olympic Committee director general Francois
Carrard, coordinator of the investigation, said Wednesday the Salt
Lake inquiry may take more time.
	   ``I don't know whether we will have a final report on Jan. 23,''
he said in a telephone interview from IOC headquarters in Lausanne,
Switzerland. ``I'm sure there will be a progress report, but it may
not be the final stage.''
	   Samaranch was eager to get the case closed before the IOC's
world summit on drugs, scheduled for Feb. 2-4 in Lausanne. That
target may now be difficult to meet.
	   The IOC is looking into whether bribery or other impropriety
took place during the Salt Lake bid and, if so, what action to
take.
	   The investigative panel will meet in Lausanne on Jan. 23 and
report the following day to the full 11-member executive board.
	   The investigation is led by Dick Pound, an IOC vice president
from Canada. He was in Salt Lake City on Tuesday, reviewing
documents and interviewing individuals involved with the 2002 bid.
	   Salt Lake Olympic officials have admitted that 13 people,
including six relatives of IOC members, benefited from nearly dlrs
400,000 in scholarship funds. IOC members also were given thousands
of dollars worth of guns and skis, and some received free medical
treatments, including plastic surgery.
	   The IOC inquiry is one of four separate investigations into the
Salt Lake scandal. Also investigating are the Justice Department,
the U.S. Olympic Committee and the Salt Lake organizing committee's
ethics board.
	   Any IOC members found guilty of accepting bribes or engaging in
other misconduct face being ousted from the organization.
	   Under the IOC charter, a member can only be expelled by a
two-thirds majority vote from the general assembly. But officials
said the IOC leadership could pre-empt that by demanding the
members' resignation.
	   The IOC is also studying what measures could be taken against
Salt Lake officials. There is no provision in the Olympic charter
for sanctions against an organizing committee.
	   One Olympic official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
one possibility could be to impose a financial penalty for damages
_ with the money allocated to a special solidarity fund.
	   While the Salt Lake inquiry may not be finished by Jan. 23,
Carrard said it is likely the IOC will be in a position by then to
decide on changes to the bidding and selection process for Olympic
host cities.
	   Samaranch has suggested leaving the selection to the executive
board or other small group, effectively stripping the general
assembly (currently numbering 115) of its principal responsibility.
	   Changes could already be put in place for the 2006 Winter
Olympics, which are due to be awarded at the IOC session in Seoul,
South Korea, next June.
	   The 2006 candidates are Turin, Italy; Sion, Switzerland;
Helsinki, Finland; Zakopane, Poland; Klagenfurt, Austria, and
Poprad-Tatry, Slovakia.
	   Carrard said the leaders of the 2006 bid committees have been
invited to a meeting in Lausanne on Jan. 24 or Jan. 25 to discuss
the rules.
	   Samaranch has already said he plans to stop IOC members from
visiting candidate cities in a bid to limit the chances for
corruption.
	   Carrard said Samaranch had written to every IOC member
explaining that, ``We need to clean the house and take some steps
for the future.''
	   Meanwhile, Thomas Bach, a German executive board member who is
on the IOC panel investigating the Salt Lake case, said he was
shaken by what has been uncovered so far.
	   ``I believed in the integrity of the members, and when you then
hold documents that show the opposite, you are deeply affected,''
he said in an interview Wednesday in the Stuttgarter Zeitung daily.
	   ``If what is in the documents we have proves true, then it is a
serious situation that can lead to the expulsion of IOC members.''
	   Bach said the IOC must demand the same high ethical and moral
standards for its members as it does for athletes.
	   ``When a doped athlete is suspended, then an IOC member guilty
of serious wrongdoing must also be punished,'' he said.
	   (sw) 	   
</TEXT>
