<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Kidnapping, 10th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Freed hostages say Yemeni troops started fatal shootout
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs; New throughout to UPDATE with quotes, CORRECTS spelling
of Firkins; German hostages freed
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By SAM F. GHATTAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ADEN, Yemen (AP) _ The hostages were being led by their
kidnappers up the mountains to a hideout when shots rang out _
Yemeni soldiers sent to rescue the 16 Westerners had opened fire.
	   It was this shooting Tuesday in southern Yemen that triggered
the two-hour gun battle that killed four hostages, three Britons
and an Australian, two former hostages said Wednesday.
	   They said they were forced to stand with their hands in the air
to shield the gunmen. When the hostages staggered back two of them
were shot dead by their captors and the others cowered behind an
embankment, they said.
	   The account appeared to contradict a Yemeni government
statement, which said security forces opened fire ``after the
kidnappers had already started killing the hostages.''
	   The soldiers were only trying to ``prevent further killings and
to save the lives of the hostages,'' the statement said.
	   Eric Firkins and Brian Smith had a different tale to tell.
	   Firkins, 55, from Croydon, England, said the abductors armed
with assault rifles and grenade launchers were leading the hostages
into the mountains to a hideout. ``Then we heard the gunfire,'' he
said.
	   ``The army approached us and the nearer they got, the more tense
the situation in our group became,'' said Smith, 52, a postal
worker from Peterborough, England.
	   He said the shooting then started in earnest with bullets
whizzing over their heads and shells crashing against surrounding
mountains or exploding in the air.
	   He and Firkins were interviewed at a hotel in the southern port
of Aden, about a three-hour drive from the town of Mawdiyah where
the hostages were held captive for a while after being seized
nearby on Monday. Mawdiyah is 175 miles (286 kilometers) south of
the capital, San`a.
	   Firkins, a chemistry professor whose sandals were still dusty
from the trek, said the the kidnappers had divided the hostages _
12 Britons, two Americans and two Australians _ into two groups of
11 and five. He and Smith were in the larger group and they didn't
know how the other group came under attack.
	   ``We were in the middle of a battle. We weren't armed, with no
military knowledge,'' Smith said.
	   At one point, the abductors told them to stand in open ground
with their hands up. ``We stood very bravely and even held our
hands up. Thereafter we fell back and the army approached and then
there were the two killings,'' he said.
	   ``My colleagues and I and another woman fell behind an
embankment and we held each others' hands until the army got very
close to us and we could surrender ourselves,'' he said.
	   This was the first time Islamic extremists had abducted
foreigners.
	   In the past tribes people have kidnapped scores of foreigners to
win economic concessions from the government but have usually
treated the hostages well and released them unharmed. On Wednesday,
four Germans kidnapped by Yemeni tribesmen on Dec. 7 were set free
unharmed.
	   The Yemeni government statement said that unlike previous
kidnappings the latest tragedy had ``purely political motives.''
	   ``The kidnappers were terrorists .. and their aim was
martyrdom,'' it said.
	   Firkins said the kidnappers tried to take cover behind the
prisoners before killing two of them ``in revenge'' as they fled.
He said he saw one of the victims, a woman, being shot in the back
of her neck.
	   ``We were used as human shields by our abductors,'' Smith said.
	   Firkins said his worst experience during the shootout was when a
kidnapper pointed a gun at his chest. ``I said, `No, no, no,' ...
Miraculously, he (the gunman) went away ... the army was just too
close,'' he recounted.
	   The British Foreign Office confirmed three Britons were slain _
Ruth Williamson, 34, Margaret Whitehouse, 52, and Peter Rowe, a
60-year-old math lecturer from Durham University. The fourth person
killed was an Australian named Andrew Colin Thirsk, 35, of Sydney.
	   Yemen's Interior Ministry said its forces killed three of the
kidnapers and captured three others.
	   An American woman, who was not identified, was shot in the
pelvis and Rowe's wife, Claire Marston, was shot in the shoulder.
On Wednesday, Marston was awake after surgery in Aden and knew her
husband had been killed, British diplomat David Pearce said.
	   Marston is ``in a very bad way,'' he told reporters at
Al-Jamhouriya Hospital in Aden.
	   In San`a, Brig. Mohammad Saleh al-Turaiq, the chief of security
in Aden province, said Wednesday that the kidnappers were the first
to open fire.
	   He said one kidnapper, an Egyptian identified as Osama al-Masri,
started it. Egyptian security sources said the name was the alias
of a wanted Islamic extremist. They refused to give his real name.
	   The officials said the kidnappers belonged to Islamic Jihad, a
group of about 200 members based in a camp in south Yemen.
	   They had seized the hostages to demand the release of two of
their leaders and in protest against the recent U.S. and British
airstrikes against Iraq, officials said. Police had detained the
leaders in a crackdown on Islamic vigilantes.
	   The group has loose ties to radical Muslim groups elsewhere in
the Arab world. The common aim of these groups is to set up
theocratic rule in their countries, and many of their leaders had
fought against the Russian occupation of Afghanistan in the 1980s.
 &UR; vars/sfg/ggl/vj
</TEXT>
