<SLUG> BC-Finland-EU-Espionage </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foreign Ministry official charged with spying for Russia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) _ A foreign ministry official who was
dismissed from his post in September has been charged with
espionage, the state prosecutor's office said Wednesday.
	   First Secretary Olli Mattila is suspected of handing over
confidential information to Russia, mainly business-related
documents regarding the European Union, said state prosecutor Jorma
Rautakoski.
	   There is no evidence Mattila received any money in return, he
said.
	   According to the prosecutor's office, Mattila is suspected of
delivering a few dozen documents during 1997 and 1998.
	   Olli Mattila's father, Olavi J. Mattila, a well-known politician
who was foreign minister in the early 1970s, has defended his son.
	   ``I'm not overly concerned about it. It was a question of
ordinary diplomatic contacts, which I believe is completely normal,
having been a diplomat myself,'' he said.
	   Even though the surrendered documents were not secret, charges
can be pursued if the information revealed in them could hurt
Finnish foreign relations, prosecutor Rautakoski said.
	   ``Someone in Mattila's position should know what kind of
information is appropriate to reveal,'' he said.
	   Two Russian diplomats who were involved in the case left the
country in September, said the foreign ministry. One of them was
expelled.
	   According to Security Police director Seppo Nevala, it is the
first time in Finland that a foreign ministry official is suspected
of espionage.
	   ``The case is particularly problematic because an intelligence
agency has broken into the core area of foreign policy
decision-making,'' he said earlier.
	   The maximum penalty for espionage in Finland is ten years
imprisonment.
	   (moz-ewm)	   
</TEXT>
