u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SierraLeone     12-30 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sierra Leone </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rebels continue to push toward Freetown
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) _ Rebels fighters advancing toward
Sierra Leone's capital have captured the central town of Lunsar, a
junction point on the road to Freetown.
	   Defense officials who spoke on condition of anonymity on
Wednesday said troops assigned to Sierra Leone's West African
defense force had withdrawn from Lunsar, about 65 kilometers (40
miles) east of Freetown by road.
	   Missionaries in Lunsar said the West African force, known as
ECOMOG, had been unable to repel the rebel attack, the Italian
missionary news service, Misna, reported from Rome.
	   There were also unconfirmed reports of fighting near Port Loko,
the next major community toward Freetown.
	   The rebel Revolutionary United Front began an offensive more
than a week ago to recapture ground lost to ECOMOG. The insurgent
force, marked by brutal tactics, has swept through several
important towns in the east and north of the country.
	   The key central town of Makeni fell to the rebels over the
weekend.
	   The surprisingly swift advances toward Freetown come as the
rebels say they are preparing for a final assault on the capital.
	   On Tuesday, a top rebel commander said his forces would begin
attacking Freetown before the weekend if the government fails to
agree to immediate talks.
	   The West African intervention force, led by Nigerian troops, has
shifted the focus of its operations in Sierra Leone toward
defending Freetown.
	   ECOMOG troops were hailed as heroes in February when they drove
the rebels and an allied military junta from power. The coalition
defense force successfully battled the rebels away from the city
and helped restore the country's elected President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah.
	   Kabbah was deposed in a military coup in May 1997, but returned
to power in March of this year after ECOMOG ousted the junta led by
Lt. Col. Johnny Paul Koroma.
	   Koroma's regime was denounced as brutal, while its RUF rebel
allies have been accused a widespread atrocities in the
countryside. Countless villagers have been maimed, tortured or
murdered by the rebels, relief workers and missionaries say.
	   The rebels have demanded Kabbah resign and are calling for
mediation with the government through the Organization of African
Unity.
	   Although they lack popular support, the Revolutionary United
Front have mounted a surprisingly successful resurgence after they
suffered heavy loses to the Nigerian-led defense force earlier in
the year.
	   Sierra Leonean government officials say the rebels are being
aided by neighboring Liberia and mercenaries from Burkina Faso.
	   Liberia has repeatedly denied the charge.
	   (var/ids)
</TEXT>
