<SLUG> BC-Cyprus-Missiles </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two Cabinet ministers to resign over missile row
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; BY ALEX EFTY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) _ The ministers of defense and education
will resign to protest the government's cancellation of a plan to
deploy Russian missiles in Cyprus, an official said Wednesday.
	   President Glafcos Clerides' decision Tuesday on the missiles has
drawn criticism both from opposition parties and members of his
right wing Democratic Rally party, which rules in coalition with
the Socialist Party.
	   Defense Minister Yiannakis Omirou and Education Minister
Lycourgos Kappas _ the only socialists in the 11-member Cabinet _
will submit their resignations Saturday, said leader of the
Socialist Party, Vassos Lyssarides.
	   He said the party's political bureau had agreed to the
resignations.
	   The resignation of the two ministers will embarrass Clerides but
will not affect his government because under the presidential
system he can remain in power until the end of his five-year term
in 2003.
	   Clerides' decision followed pressure from the United States and
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization after Turkey threatened to
use force to prevent the deployment of the S-300 anti-aircraft
missiles in Cyprus.
	   Greece, which has a joint defense agreement with Cyprus, also
opposed the deployment, to avoid a likely clash with fellow NATO
ally Turkey.
	   ``The cancellation will prove damaging to both Cyprus and Greece
as their joint defense policy will now become a satellite of
Turkish threats and foreign pressures,'' Lyssarides said.
	   Greece and Cyprus said they agreed to have the missiles deployed
instead on the Greek island of Crete.
	   But Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem said Wednesday that his
country would take ``appropriate political and military means'' to
prevent their deployment in Crete.
	   Greek opposition parties also attacked Greek Prime Minister
Costas Simitis for backing down on earlier promises to help Cyprus
if it were attacked by Turkey over the missile deployment.
	   The government suffered ``a heavy defeat on a serious issue,''
charged Costas Caramanlis, leader of New Democracy, the main
opposition party in Greece.
	   Athens newspapers also charged that concessions had been made
without Athens or Nicosia getting anything in return. ``Washington
decides and Simitis carries out the orders, that is the principle
of our foreign policy,'' charged the conservative Eleftheros Typos.
 &UR; ae-sf/vj
</TEXT>
