<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Angola-Fighting, 1st Ld-Writethru,0464 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With BC-Angola
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Angolan rebels bombard second-largest city &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with army report of five killed; Red Cross saying no
staff reported injured, canceling flight to Huambo; Kuito Bishop
concerned about food shortages &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Angola &QL; 
 &UR; By CASIMIRO SIONA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LUANDA, Angola (AP) _ Rebel forces Wednesday launched an
hour-long artillery bombardment of Huambo, the country's
second-largest city and a base for U.N. and aid agency staff,
according to reports.
	   Five civilians were killed and three were injured, the army
said.
	   Some shells landed in downtown areas of the central highland
city which lies about 500 kilometers (300 miles) southeast of the
capital, Luanda, state radio RNA reported from Huambo.
	   The explosions reportedly began at noon and caused panic among
local people in the government-held city which the army is using as
a base to fly in reinforcements for fighting in surrounding areas.
	   Before the civil war restarted Dec. 4 Huambo had a population of
about 300,000, but tens of thousands of refugees fleeing fighting
in the countryside have converged on the city in recent weeks.
	   The U.N. and International Red Cross headquarters in Luanda both
said they had received no reports of injuries to their staff in
Huambo.
	   However, IRC spokeswoman Francoise Zambelini said a scheduled
aid flight to the city was canceled because the warring factions
did not provide guarantees of safe passage.
	   A cargo plane chartered by the United Nations crashed near
Huambo on Saturday with 14 people on board. The cause of the crash,
as the plane passed over the war zone, was not known.
	   Artillery shells also were landing sporadically in Kuito, 130
kilometers (80 miles) to the east of Huambo, which has been under a
rebel siege for more than two weeks, according to the city's Roman
Catholic Bishop.
	   Most of the shells were landing near the airport outside the
city and only a few people were injured, Bishop Jose Nambi said in
a telephone interview.
	   He said the food shortage in the town was ``very worrying.''
	   The United Nations observer mission, which is monitoring a 1994
peace accord that halted a two-decade civil war between the rebels
and the government, has been unable to stop the renewed fighting
which so far been concentrated in the central highlands.
	   The U.N. Security Council has blamed UNITA, a Portuguese acronym
for the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola, for
the return to war.
	   UNITA refused to yield control of areas under its control and
maintained a hidden army, according to the United Nations.
	   The country has been ravaged by conflict since gaining
independence from Portugal in 1975.
</TEXT>
