<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Yemen-Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With Yemen-Germany-Hostages
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; German foreign minister thanks Yemeni government, others for
hostages' release &QL;  Eds: CORRECTS in 2nd graf that freed Germans
still on the way to San'a, ADDs last name of ambassador in last
graf &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Foreign Minister Joschka Fisher on
Wednesday thanked the Yemeni government and others involved in
gaining the release of four German hostages, three and a half weeks
after they were kidnapped by tribesmen.
	   Fischer also said he was releaved to hear that the three women
and a man were ``in good condition considering the circumstances,''
and that they were in the care of German embassy personnel and
expected to arrive in the capital of San'a about 10 p.m. (2000
GMT).
	   ``We have all worried and hoped for them and their families in
the last 24 days of the kidnapping, the longest hostage taking of
foreign tourists in Yemen,'' Fischer said.
	   After the attempt by Yemeni authorities on Tuesday to free a
group of 16 tourists in which three Britons and an Australian was
killed and several injured, President Roman Herzog sent a message
to his Yemeni counterpart to avoid any action that might endanger
the Germans.
	   Fischer's spokesman Martin Erdmann said the ministry does not
know exactly what led to the release of the hostages.
	   He said it was unclear if Yemeni officials met demands of the
tribe that had kidnapped the Germans, but that he could confirm
that Germany did not pay a ransom or promise other services.
	   German Ambassador to Yemen, Helga Graefin Strachwitz, was
originally informed by the Yemeni interior and defense ministries
that the hostages had been freed, Erdmann said.
	   (gb)
</TEXT>
