<SLUG> BC-Georgia-Power </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Georgian capital looks forward to dark New Year
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TBILISI, Georgia (AP) _ When the clock strikes midnight
Thursday, 80 percent of the people in Georgia's capital can expect
to welcome 1999 by candlelight, the head of the city energy service
said.
	   While people around the world worry about the Year 2000 computer
bug plunging cities into darkness a year from now, Tbilisi is ahead
of its time _ but for more down-to-earth reasons.
	   A portion of the city's power station broke down as the result
of a recent fire, giving the city the ability to transmit far less
electricity, Bezhan Khutsishvili said on state television
Wednesday.
	   He did not say when the problem is expected to be fixed.
	   (str/ml)
