r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Poland-Kwasniewski-NA     12-30 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Kwasniewski-NATO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kwasniewski: Poland will be ready for NATO in April
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ President Aleksander Kwasniewski said
Wednesday that Poland's smooth access to NATO will be ``our great
trump card in negotiations with the European Union.''
	   In an interview for the Polish News Agency PAP, Kwasniewski said
he hopes Poland will make a huge effort and will be ready to fully
join NATO in April, when the Western military alliance celebrates
it's 50th anniversary.
	   Joining the alliance smoothly ``will show that Poland is
credible, that it is a country that takes its obligations
seriously,'' Kwasniewski said.
	   Poland, along with the Czech Republic and Hungary is to join the
EU early next century. The three former Warsaw Pact countries are
invited to join NATO, a Cold War-era foe, during the organization's
summit next year.
	   Kwasniewski said he sees no threats to Poland's access to NATO,
but that intensive effort is required at this stage, to meet all
the requirements.
	   ``Extending the time of Poland's access to NATO would be a
political defeat, that Poland cannot afford. Even worse, if it
turned out we are not a serious ally,'' he said.
	   In a move to mend Polish-Russian ties, strained over Poland's
access to NATO, Kwasniewski repeated an invitation to Russia's
President Boris Yeltsin to visit Poland ``the sooner the better.''
No date has been set yet, he said.
	   Yeltsin's visit scheduled for December was canceled, due to his
ill health.
	   Kwasniewski said the decision last week by Yeltsin and Belarus
President Alexander Lukashenka to join the two countries resulted
``more from weakness than from the strength of the two countries.''
	   ``I think President Yeltsin and President Lukashenka need it to
improve their public image,'' he said.
 &UR; (ms-gb)
</TEXT>
