w1186 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Bank     12-30 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Bank </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia's top banker attacks corruption probe as unfounded
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's top banker chastised police and
prosecutors Wednesday for smearing the bank's reputation by making
what he said were unfounded corruption allegations against its top
officials.
	   Central Bank Chairman Viktor Gerashchenko was responding to a
statement from Interior Minister Sergei Stepashin, who said Tuesday
that police and prosecutors were probing the activities of the
Central Bank because of suspicions that its leadership may have
misappropriated up to dlrs 1 billion.
	   Stepashin didn't mention any names or provide further details.
	   ``There are no facts whatsoever to back those vague
statements,'' Gerashchenko said in a live interview on the ORT
television station. ``It's an attempt to discredit not only the
Central Bank, but also undermine the government's efforts to
stabilize the economic situation.''
	   The Central Bank has played a key role in the government's
efforts to contain the economic crisis, supporting the embattled
ruble and propping up the ailing banks.
	   During the past few months, the prosecutor's office also accused
bank officials of spending resources on ambitious construction
projects and high salaries instead of using them to ensure
stability of the currency and financial markets.
	   No charges have been brought.
	   Gerashchenko acknowledged that there had been some
irregularities in the bank's activities. He specifically cited the
use of credit cards on business trips by Central Bank officials.
``There is no corruption or thievery here,'' he said.
	   He blamed police and prosecutors for the failure to clearly put
forward their accusations. ``It's incorrect to make such statements
without providing any concrete facts,'' Gerashchenko said.
	   ``It's either incompetence or a premeditated action, and I'm
afraid it's the second,'' he said without elaboration.
	   Gerashchenko, the former Soviet chief banker, served as Russia's
Central Bank chief since the start of free-market reforms in 1992
until he was fired by President Boris Yeltsin in the fall of 1994
over a sharp drop of the national currency.
	   Yeltsin re-appointed Gerashchenko in September at the same time
he named Yevgeny Primakov as Russia's new prime minister. Both
quickly won parliament's approval and enjoy broad support among
lawmakers.
	   Gerashchenko's predecessor, Sergei Dubinin, who was ousted in
August over the government's decision to devalue the ruble and
default on some debts, also denied any wrongdoing in an interview
Tuesday.
	   (vi/ml)
</TEXT>
