<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Islamic Leader </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police arrest Islamic militant leader accused of plotting New
</HEADLINE>
Year's attacks &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) _ Police arrested the leader of a violent
Islamic group, foiling a string of planned attacks on bars and
discos across Turkey on New Year's Eve, news reports said
Wednesday.
	   Riot police arrested Salih Izzet Erdis, leader of the outlawed
Great Eastern Islamic Raiders' Front, on Tuesday at a house in
Istanbul where he was in hiding, Turkey's Anatolia news agency
said.
	   Authorities had learned the group was plotting to bomb places
where alcohol is consumed, private Star television said.
	   Star said the group had planned New Year's Eve bombings in
Istanbul, the Aegean port city of Izmir, the Mediterranean city of
Antalya and the popular Aegean resort town of Bodrum.
	   Erdis is better known in the Islamic world as Salih
Mirzabeyoglu. His group, the bloodiest of the fundamentalist
Islamic movements in Turkey, has claimed responsibility for a
number of attacks on left-wing targets and Western-oriented
secularists.
	   Following Erdis' capture, police increased security in big
cities for the holiday.
	   Many Turks in this predominantly Muslim country celebrate the
New Year in Western fashion, giving gifts and throwing dinners and
parties.
	   Drinking alcohol is forbidden under most interpretations of
Islamic doctrine. Islamic circles are particularly sensitive about
the consumption of alcohol when the New Year coincides with the
holy Muslim month of Ramadan, which requires dawn-to-dusk
abstinence from all food, drink, sex and smoking.
	   (sh-ek) 	   
</TEXT>
