<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Congo Fighting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Missionaries: Congo rebels gain ground in new fighting, retake town
</HEADLINE>
in north &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Rebel forces in Congo are gaining ground in some
central and northern sections of the central African country,
retaking a town near the northern border, Italy's missionary news
service said Wednesday.
	   The town of Dingila fell Monday, Misna news service said,
quoting missionary sources in Congo. Dingila is about 400
kilometers (250 miles) northeast of the city of Kisangani, Congo's
third-largest city.
	   The biggest advances are being made in Orientale province, which
includes Kisangani, and the central province of Kasai, the
missionary news service said.
	   A rebel coalition has been fighting to overthrow President
Laurent Kabila since August.
	   Neighboring Rwanda and Uganda are supporting the rebels, while
Angola, Zimbabwe, Namibia and Chad are backing Kabila.
	   Misna said shipments of military supplies from Uganda are
continuing to Kisangani, a rebel base. 	   
</TEXT>
