<HEADER>
w1224 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Mexico-Budget 1stLd-Writethru   12-30 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru,0435 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mexican legislators reach last-minute budget agreement
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: NEW throughout with budget agreement reached. CHANGES byline. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; By ADOLFO GARZA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Avoiding a crisis with just 36 hours to
spare, Mexican legislators ended weeks of deadlock and reached a
compromise Wednesday on the 1999 budget.
	   The Mexican government had faced the prospect of beginning the
new year without a budget _ an unprecedented event in Mexican
history. Officials didn't know if they'd be able to keep the
government operating without a budget.
	   Legislators were stalled over a dlrs 2.86 billion shortfall,
largely the result of falling oil prices. Oil makes up about a
third of the Mexican government's revenue.
	   President Ernesto Zedillo had proposed a series of tax
increases, including a 15 percent telephone usage surcharge on top
of the current 15 percent sales tax. Opposition parties, who have a
majority in the lower house of Congress, opposed the plan, as did
businesses and civic groups.
	   Legislators said compromise worked out Wednesday makes up for
the budget shortfall by including at least dlrs 1.4 billion in
spending cuts, a higher corporate income tax rate than Zedillo had
proposed and higher diesel prices charged by the state-owned oil
monopoly.
	   It also calls for higher tariffs on goods from countries with
which Mexico doesn't have free trade agreements. Those tariffs
presumably wouldn't affect the United States, Canada or much of
Latin America.
	   The lower house was to consider the revenues part of the budget
later Wednesday. It would then need approval in the Senate, which
is controlled by the governing party. The lower house would then
consider the spending part of the budget, which does not need
Senate approval.
	   The agreement was worked out largely between legislators of
Zedillo's Institutional Revolutionary Party and the right-center
National Action Party, which has about a quarter of the seats in
the lower House. The other major opposition party, Democratic
Revolution, strongly opposed Zedillo's plan.
	   For most of its 69-year history, the governing party, known as
the PRI, was able to dictate its will in Congress. But it lost its
majority in the lower house in elections last year _ after PRI
legislators raised the sales tax to 15 percent from 10 percent in
1995.
	   But the opposition has failed to vote as a solid bloc.
Legislators from National Action and the PRI approved the 1998
budget over the objections of Democratic Revolution.
</TEXT>
