<HEADLINE>
Iraq says U.S. attack kills farmer, injures two civilians
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CLARIFIES that Iraqi statement did not identify origin of
aircraft &QL; 
 &UR; With US-Iraq
 &UR; By LOUIS MEIXLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraq said Wednesday that fire from
``enemy'' aircraft killed a farmer and wounded two other civilians
in a village in southern Iraq.
	   Officials in Washington said U.S. warplanes fired missiles and
laser-guided bombs at an anti-aircraft battery after the Iraqis
fired missiles at British aircraft patrolling the southern no-fly
zone. Iraq has never recognized the zone.
	   The Iraqi statement, carried by the official Iraqi News Agency,
made no mention of military casualties.
	   The report also claimed that Iraq ``almost certainly shot down
one of the planes.'' The statement only referred to ``enemy''
aircraft and did not specify whether they were American or British.
	   It was the second such claim in recent days, but officials at
the Pentagon said that all U.S. and British aircraft again returned
safely to their bases.
