<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Caucasus </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ingush leader: North Ossetia dragging its feet on refugee
</HEADLINE>
admissions &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A leader of the Caucasus republic of Ingushetia
accused neighboring North Ossetia on Wednesday of preventing Ingush
refugees from returning to their homes, a news agency said.
	   ``The leadership of North Ossetia ... is artificially creating
obstacles to the return of Ingushis deported from North Ossetia,''
Ingush Vice Premier Akhmet Malsagov said, according to ITAR-Tass.
	   The Ossetian-Ingush conflict goes back to a 1944 decision by
Soviet dictator Josef Stalin to deport the entire Ingush nation for
collaborating with the Nazis during World War II.
	   When the Ingush were permitted to return to the Caucasus in
1957, they found their homes inhabited by Ossetians. Ever since,
both groups have claimed territory that is now part of North
Ossetia.
	   Malsagov charged that only 835 families, or 3,353 people, had
been allowed to return to their homes this year, and about 5,000
people over the last six years.
	   The two Russian regions fought a brief territorial and ethnic
war in 1992, and sporadic violence has continued. Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov convened a meeting of the leaders of the
two republics in September in an effort to calm tensions.
	   (ml)
</TEXT>
