<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Kidnapping, 11th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Freed hostages say Yemeni troops started fatal shootout
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with prime minister's letter to Blair, condolences to
families &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By SAM F. GHATTAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ADEN, Yemen (AP) _ The hostages were being led by their
kidnappers up the mountains to a hideout when shots rang out _
Yemeni soldiers sent to rescue the 16 Westerners had opened fire.
	   It was this shooting Tuesday in southern Yemen that triggered
the two-hour gun battle that killed four hostages, three Britons
and an Australian, two former hostages said Wednesday.
	   They said they were forced to stand with their hands in the air
to shield the gunmen. When the hostages staggered back two of them
were shot dead by their captors and the others cowered behind an
embankment, they said.
	   The account appeared to contradict a Yemeni government
statement, which said security forces opened fire ``after the
kidnappers had already started killing the hostages.''
	   The soldiers were only trying to ``prevent further killings and
to save the lives of the hostages,'' the statement said.
	   In a letter to British Prime Minister Tony Blair, Yemen's Prime
Minister Abdel Karim al-Iryani repeated that version of events and
conveyed his condolences to the victims' families.
 &UR; Eric Firkins, 6th graf prvs
