<SLUG> BC-People and Places,0754 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People and places in the news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Includes items on Elke Sommer, Zsa Zsa Gabor and Prince
Frederic von Anhalt, Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, drug smugglers
posing as fishermen, a revolutionary scam in Romania and a
mother-son burglary team; some items may have moved as separates.

<TEXT>
	   NUREMBERG, Germany (AP) _ German actress Elke Sommer won the
latest round Wednesday in a long-running dispute with Zsa Zsa Gabor
and her German husband, Prince Frederic von Anhalt.
	   A Bavarian court rejected an appeal from the prince, who had
been ordered by a lower court to stop telling people that Ms.
Sommer had once called all German men ``pigs.''
	   But since Ms. Sommer could not definitively prove that she had
not made the statement, the court did not order von Anhalt to make
a full retraction.
	   The three have been fighting for years. According to Ms. Sommer,
there has been bad blood ever since she said Ms. Gabor had a big
rear end.
	   In 1992, a Los Angeles jury ordered the Hungarian-born Ms. Gabor
and von Anhalt, her eighth husband, to pay Ms. Sommer dlrs 2.5
million for describing her as a haggard Hollywood has-been.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   ST. PAUL, Minnesota (AP) _ Having a former Navy special forces
commando as Minnesota's governor-elect seems to have had a powerful
effect on military recruiting in the state.
	   On Dec. 10, the Minnesota National Guard mailed 62,000 brochures
featuring a snapshot of Gov.-elect Jesse Ventura to high school
juniors. Recruiters have gotten more than twice as many replies as
usual.
	   ``He is someone people can recognize and become interested in,
and if he can help us recruit people into the National Guard,
that's great,'' said Maj. Kevin Gutknecht, a National Guard
spokesman.
	   Ventura, 47, a former professional wrestler, joined the Navy in
1969 and became a member of a SEAL underwater demolition team,
serving in the Vietnam War.
	   Since his election as governor, other state agencies and
organizations have asked him whether they could use him in their
advertisements.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   BARCELONA, Spain (AP) _ A heroin addict who held up fast-food
joints to feed his habit had an unlikely accomplice -- his
76-year-old mother, who says she went along to look after him.
	   Police in Barcelona arrested the duo Sunday after the
42-year-old man robbed a sandwich shop at gunpoint and attempted a
slow getaway on foot with his mother, news reports say.
	   The woman confessed to accompanying him on several such holdups
``so he would not do anything bad,'' the newspaper El Pais
reported.
	   In Sunday's incident, the two had a meal in a fast-food
restaurant, after which the woman waited outside while her son
robbed it with the aid of a .38-caliber Smith and Wesson pistol.
	   The woman told police that in the past she had gone by herself
to rough neighborhoods to buy heroin for her son.
	   Officials did not identify the woman or her son.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ A man who coaxed thousands of dollars
out of Romanian companies by evoking the name of a hero of the 1989
revolution has been arrested for suspected fraud, police said
Wednesday.
	   Catalin Alistar, 23, has been obtaining money and free services
for two years from companies that thought they were dealing with
the ``Gavroche'' of revolution fame, officer Mariana Apostol said.
	   The real Gavroche is Florin Vieru. Only a child during the
events that toppled communism, Vieru marched on the streets of the
capital waving a revolutionary flag. His picture appeared in the
media worldwide. He is now a taxi driver.
	   Alistar used to call managers of different companies pretending
to be a state secretary and saying someone nicknamed Gavroche would
come on his behalf to collect.
	   He has admitted misleading even the Moldovan Interior Ministry,
which arranged for his accommodations and gave him presents during
a visit last year.
	    &UR; ___ &QC; 
	   MALAGA, Spain (AP) _ Police who smelled a rat when they saw two
men fishing with no reels or line found more than a ton of hashish
hidden nearby.
	   The two fake anglers were arrested Tuesday on a cliff
overlooking the Mediterranean near the town of Lagos in southern
Malaga province, the state news agency Efe reported.
	   The men, who had fishing rods with no reels or line, were
apparently guarding a drug shipment hidden at the foot of the
cliff. Police found 37 bails containing a total of 1,200 kilos
(2,640 pounds) of hashish.
	   Firemen used ropes and pulleys to retrieve the drugs.
</TEXT>
