<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,1120 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
and Guyana.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Puerto Rico, Venezuela, Brazil, Grenada.
 &UR; By The Associated Press

<TEXT>
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Prosecutors have charged a fourth
man in an alleged fraud scheme in Puerto Rico following Hurricane
Georges, the U.S. Attorney's Office in San Juan said Wednesday.
	   Prosecutors claim Marcos Gonzalez Reyes worked with another
contractor, Jose Orlando Figueroa, to inflate reports of debris
left by the hurricane.
	   The fraudulent reports were submitted the Federal Emergency
Management Agency in order to get more disaster funds for the city
of Toa Alta, prosecutors say.
	   They also allege he prepared blank documents and work reports
for a city worker to fill out and submit to the agency.
	   Gonzalez Reyes faces a maximum of 10 years in jail, a dlrs
250,000 fine and three years of probation on a charge of conspiring
to defraud the United States.
	   Figueroa and Toa Alta Mayor Angel Rodriguez were charged in
November with exaggerating hurricane damage and demanding dlrs 2.5
million in bribes from a Mississippi-based company, JESCO, in
exchange for a contract to collect debris.
	   Rodriguez and Figueroa have pleaded innocent to conspiracy,
extortion and bribery indictments.
	   Another contractor, Luis A. Rodriguez Sierra, was charged Dec.
15 with inflating damage estimates.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Inmates who held 19 hostages at gunpoint
after a failed Christmas Day escape attempt had bought their
weapons from a guard, officials said.
	   The guard, identified as Rodolfo Sanchez Morales, sold three
pistols, a rifle and a hand grenade, to the inmates at the
Reclusorio Sur prison for dlrs 4,500, the Mexico City attorney
general's office said in a statement Tuesday.
	   A prisoner, Carlos Angel Ferrat Garcia, said they had bought the
weapons in October, the statement said.
	   Sanchez Morales has been ordered under house arrest. Another
guard is under investigation.
	   Five inmates held the hostages for more than 20 hours after the
escape failed. No one was seriously injured. Officials previously
said four inmates had been involved in the hostage-taking.
	   ___
	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) _ Venezuelan President-elect Hugo Chavez
exchanged pleasantries with a senior U.S. official Wednesday in
what appeared to be an attempt by Washington to ease tensions with
the former coup leader, barred from the United States until last
week.
	   Assistant secretary of state for InterAmerican affairs Peter
Romero told reporters after meeting Chavez in Caracas that the
United States intends ``to be partners in every sense'' with
Venezuela.
	   Chavez, who tried to overthrow Venezuela's government in a
bloody 1992 coup attempt, won a landslide victory in Dec. 6
elections and will be sworn in as president on Feb. 2.
	   After their meeting, Chavez said the two countries will seek to
bolster bilateral efforts to fight corruption and drug trafficking.
	   Last week, Washington reversed its policy of denying Chavez a
visa. The new leader is expected to visit the United States in
early 1999.
	   The United States and Venezuela recently completed negotiations
on a bilateral treaty to avoid double taxation and are currently
trying to devise a treaty to protect investments.
	   Venezuela's is the No. 1 exporter of oil to the United States.
	   ___
	   BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) _ The Brazilian government announced a
series of measures Wednesday intended to shore-up the country's
fiscal situation and meet savings goals established in an agreement
with the International Monetary Fund.
	   The measures, which are expected to yield 5.4 billion reals
(dlrs 4.5 billion) next year, will eliminate interest deductions on
certain corporate taxes, speed up payment for recently privatized
telephone companies and raise a financial transactions tax by 0.38
percentage points.
	   The measures were needed to compensate for the revenues lost
after Congress failed to pass the CPMF, a tax on all banking
transactions, and other key points of the fiscal stabilization plan
released last October. The ministry estimates those losses at 6.7
billion reals (dlrs 5.5 billion) in 1999.
	   Another 1.3 billion reals (dlrs 1.08 billion) in budget cuts
will be announced at a later date.
	   In October, the government announced plans to save the 28
billion reals (dlrs 23.3 billion) from next year's budget. The plan
formed the basis of an agreement for an IMF-lead bailout package
worth dlrs 41.5 billion, of which about 9 billion has been released
so far.
	   ___
	   ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) _ A local newspaper is accusing
Grenada's government of corruption, saying an audit shows kickbacks
and conflicts of interest in public construction projects.
	   In this week's edition, the independent Grenada Today claims the
government gave contracts to allies of Prime Minister Keith
Mitchell and that one senator is renting a house to contractors
working on government projects at a hugely inflated price.
	   It also accuses the Carnival and Cultural Development Committee
of arranging kickbacks on contracts.
	   Prime Minister Keith Mitchell has denied all of the accusations.
	   ``The NNP and its agents have turned out to be the most corrupt
government to hold the reigns of power in Grenada since the return
of democratic government in 1984,'' the newspaper said.
	   An audit by KPMG Peat Marwick showed overspending and violations
of public bid procedures, but did not touch upon questions of
wrongdoing.
	   ___
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) _ Guyana said Wednesday it is waiting
for an explanation from Venezuela before complaining to United
Nations supervisors about an alleged overflight by warplanes along
a disputed border.
	   The United Nations is overseeing efforts to resolve a
100-year-old border dispute in that area. Guyanese Foreign Minister
Clement Rohee said he wants to talk to Venezuelan officials about
the alleged violation on Dec. 24 before complaining to the
international body.
	   ``We are not on a war footing and we would prefer always to work
through the diplomatic channels,'' Rohee said. ``I don't think we
need to rush to the United Nations with very limited information.''
	   The Guyanese army reported last week that two military jets flew
over northwestern Guyana without permission.
	   Venezuela has not responded to the charges. On Wednesday,
officials at the Venezuelan foreign affairs department left work
early because of the New Year's holiday and could not be reached
for comment.
	   Venezuela claims two-thirds of Guyana, a country rich in timber,
minerals, gold and oil. Guyana also has a running territorial
dispute with Suriname, its neighbor to the east.
</TEXT>
