<HEADER>
w1422 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-BalloonQues     12-30 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Balloon Quest,0612 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Balloon flight team overcomes problems as final countdown nears
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS pvs. Tentative launch time is 5 a.m. local time on Jan.
1 (1930 GMT Dec. 31) &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By ROHAN SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALICE SPRINGS, Australia (AP) _ Engineers made final adjustments
Thursday to a massive, experimental balloon designed to carry three
men to record heights and hopefully nonstop around the world.
	   After delays caused by bad weather and equipment delivery
problems, the spaceship-like capsule which Denver real estate
magnate Dave Liniger and two copilots plan to fly at the edge of
space was lifted free of the earth by a crane for weight and safety
checks.
	   Engineers and scientists worked late into Wednesday night after
a weight distribution problem was found in the six steel cables
which will connect the giant and super-fragile balloon canopy with
the capsule upon which the pilots' lives will depend.
	   Some of the cables were overstressed and others were slack and
not taking enough weight.
	   Dan Pedersen, the former U.S. Navy captain and test fighter
pilot who is Liniger's mission control director, said after more
tests that the problem could be solved by modifying the capsule.
	   A 12-inch goanna _ the Aboriginal word for a type of lizard
considered good eating _ scrambled across the concrete driveway
outside the garage-like Australian Balloon Launch Center Wednesday
as more than 60 people continued final preparations for the Team
Re/Max International bid to be the first to fly around the world in
a balloon.
	   Temperatures soared to almost 100 F (38 Celsius) as winds strong
enough to make a launch too dangerous continued to buffet the
desert launch zone near the Outback town of Alice Springs.
	   Team members packaged the food and water the pilots will take,
and electronics panels were screwed together and installed.
	   The team's own forecasters say weather conditions are looking
good for a dawn takeoff on New Year's Day local time (1930 GMT Dec.
31). If the forecast changes, the launch could be delayed further.
	   Until launch, the team were ``checking and rechecking every
circuit, every life support component,'' of the capsule, the
balloon and the radio guidance systems which will remain on the
ground, Liniger said.
	   The Re/Max pilots _ Liniger, Albuquerque, New Mexico, journalist
Bob Martin and Australian balloonist John Wallington _ expect to
succeed with other attempts have failed by flying just this side of
space, where weather is not expected to be a factor.
	   The 7-ft. by 8-ft. (2.1-meter by 2.4-meter) capsule will hang
below a balloon made of lunchwrap-thin polyethylene plastic that
when fully inflated is 460 feet (138 meters) in diameter and 700
feet (210 meters) high _ large enough to envelope the Houston
Astrodome or two 747 jet liners nose-to-nose.
	   They will rise 1,000 feet (300 meters) a minute during takeoff,
expanding the balloon on the way up with 170,000 cubic ft. (5,100
cubic meters) of helium, rising into the stratosphere to a cruising
altitude of 130,000 feet (39,000 meters), or about 24 miles (39
kilometers) above sea level.
	   That's higher than any manned balloon flight before.
	   ``There's no question that it's more dangerous than the other
missions,'' Liniger said, comparing his first attempt to the more
than a dozen others which have previously failed, using more
conventional balloons at altitudes not exceeding 40,000 feet
(12,000 meters).
	   ``The other people, if they get in trouble they can slowly go
down and sit down in the ocean. If we get into trouble, we're 25
miles (40 kilometers) up.''
</TEXT>
