<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hungary-1956 Institute,0521 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Institute on 1956 uprising latest victim of Hungary budget cuts
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ALEX BANDY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) _ He took on the communist regime in open
debate and got jailed for his views. Now, Andras B. Hegedues' hopes
for detailing Hungary's 1956 revolution against the Soviets may
fall victim to politics in the democratic era.
	   Despite the protests of international researchers and others,
new Prime Minister Viktor Orban has axed the budget of a well-known
institute devoted to researching the 1956 Hungarian revolution.
	   Founded in 1990 after the collapse of Hungary's communist
government, the 1956 Institute is still working to reveal hidden
truths about events the communists vilified for decades.
	   ``We had no hint of trouble ahead, much less any decent
consultation,'' said Hegedues, the institute's executive director
and a former leader of the Petoefi Circle, which organized the
first free debates east of the Iron Curtain in 1956.
	   The government's proposed 1999 budget initially included 73
million forints (dlrs 365,000) for the institute. But a decision
was made to cut it to 6 million forints (dlrs 30,000), which could
prove the institute's death knell.
	   The institute's goal is to publicize the truth about the
uprising against communist rule which exploded in Budapest in
October 1956. The Soviets, fearful the unrest could spread
throughout Eastern Europe, launched a massive attack on Budapest on
Nov. 4, 1956, using tens of thousands of troops and more than 2,000
tanks.
	   About 200,000 Hungarians fled the country. Thousands of others
were arrested, including Premier Imre Nagy who was executed in
1958.
	   Szilard Sasvari, head of the House cultural committee and a
founding member of Orban's party, denies any political motivation
behind the funding decision despite strong appearances to the
contrary. He said this week it was made because ``they are not
alone in researching the 1956 events.''
	   ``There will be a new foundation and they can participate in
competitions for project funding,'' he said.
	   He also said an audit of the institute's finances turned up
irregularities, without elaborating.
	   But Hegedues denies that, saying a government audit cleared the
institute of wrongdoing. He and others suggest another motive:
co-director Gyoergy Litvan is on the National Steering Committee of
the liberal opposition party, the Alliance of Free Democrats.
	   ``The institute ought to be judged on the basis of its work,
which include 57 volumes on various aspects and personalities of
the revolt,'' he said.
	   Letters of support have poured in since word of the funding cut
got out, among them such internationally recognized names as
British author Timothy Garton-Ash, American Kremlinologist Charles
Gati and Joachim Gauck, in charge of East German secret police
archives.
	   But the effort may be in vain. Sasvari said most of the money
originally earmarked for the institute will go toward funding a new
agency to be organized by historians Gyula Teller and Maria Schmidt
_ both advisers to Orban.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
