<SLUG> BC-Colombia-Child Slayings,0373 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Man described as sexual maniac arrested in childrens' murders
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS pvs, CORRECTS prosecutors possibly linking to three
sted four possible other victims &QL; 
 &UR; By JARED KOTLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ Authorities have arrested a man they
describe as a ``psychotic, sexual maniac'' in connection with the
murders of dozens of children whose remains were found last month.
	   ``We may be looking at one of those responsible in the case of
the disappearances and deaths of the children of Pereira,'' Pedro
Gonzalez, chief investigator of the federal prosecutor's office
told a news conference on Wednesday.
	   The skeletons and decomposing corpses of 25 children were
discovered at the bottom of a ravine and scattered about an
overgrown city lot in the Pereira, a state capital located 110
miles (175 kilometers) west of Bogota.
	   The oldest of the victims was 16 and at least half were 10 or
younger. Their bodies were sighted in two searches after workers
spotted what they thought were animal bones in the ravine, and
after a child stumbled on a skull in the empty lot.
	   Gonzalez identified the man captured Dec. 16 in Pereira by two
names, Pedro Pablo Ramirez and Carlos Alberto Arboleda, and said he
had previously been imprisoned for sexual crimes.
	   Officials described the man as short and dark, with green eyes,
brown hair and poor teeth. They said he works as a street vendor,
selling hot food, honey, fruit and bracelets.
	   Investigators have linked the man to the killings of at least
three children in Pereira, and possibly three other children in the
nearby city of Armenia, Gonzalez said.
	   They were ruling out theories floated originally that the
murders were the work of a satanic cult or linked to the
trafficking of organs. ``It was a depraved, psychotic, sexual
maniac who does these things because he has sexual abnormalities,''
said Gonzalez.
	   The capture was said to be part of a broad probe into 80 similar
murders committed in the past few years in Pereira and other cities
in western and southern Colombia. ``We can't attribute all of the
cases to this person, and we have to continue the investigation,''
said Gonzalez.
</TEXT>
