w1441 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-1998-NFLFootba     12-30 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-1998-NFL Football,0932 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Broncos and zebras dominate NFL '98
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DAVE GOLDBERG &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ If the American National Football League named
its seasons after animals, 1998 would be the season of the Bronco
and the zebra.
	   With a Falcon and a Cardinal flying overhead and a Viking ready
to pounce on all of them.
	   The Denver Broncos started the year by finally winning a Super
Bowl, beating Green Bay 31-24 in San Diego to give John Elway his
first NFL title in his 15th season and ending a streak of 13
consecutive victories by NFC teams.
	   They continued it by winning their first three regular-season
games before being upset 20-16 by the New York Giants. That came a
week before what was supposed to be a confrontation with Miami,
which in 1972 was the only unbeaten franchise for a whole season in
NFL history.
	   The Broncos lost that, too, handing over the mantle of the NFL's
strongest team to the Minnesota Vikings, led by rookie wide
receiver Randy Moss and recycled quarterback Randall Cunningham,
moved to the top of the NFC. They lost only once, at Tampa, winning
15, and ending the season with an NFL record 556 points, an average
of almost 35 a game.
	   On the final Sunday, the Arizona Cardinals achieved something
they hadn't done since 1982, when they played in St. Louis. They
made the playoffs at 9-7, winning seven of their games by three
points or less, including a 16-13 victory over San Diego on the
final Sunday in which the Chargers tied the game with 16 seconds
left and the Cardinals won it on a 52-yard field goal by Chris
Jacke as time ran out.
	   But for a few weeks in November and December, the Broncos and
Vikings (and, of course, the Cardinals) were overshadowed by the
officials, those guys in the zebra-striped shirts whose mistakes
played a major part in deciding three games.
	   The first came on Thanksgiving during the coin toss to start
overtime in the Steelers-Lions game.
	   Jerome Bettis of the Steelers said he called ``tails.'' Referee
Phil Luckett said he heard ``heads-tails'' and went with ``heads''
when the coin came up ``tails.'' So Detroit got the ball and drove
for the winning field goal without Pittsburgh ever getting the
ball.
	   The second came four days later, when the officials made what
the league conceded were two bad calls that gave New England a
victory over Buffalo.
	   The third mistake came a week later, when the officials gave the
New York Jets a 32-31 victory over Seattle by ruling Vinny
Testaverde over the goal line. Replays showed he wasn't and Earnie
Frantz, who made the TD call, later acknowledged that he mistook
Testaverde's white helmet for the brown ball.
	   As a result, the NFL floated the idea of instant replay for the
playoffs, a good public relations move that was shot down by its
rule-making competition committee by a 7-1 vote. The committee,
however, did vote 6-1 with one ``maybe'' vote to bring it back at
the league meetings in March.
	   As the playoffs began, Minnesota (15-1) and Denver (14-2), held
home field for the playoffs.
	   But while the Vikings were a heavy favorite to represent the NFC
in the Super Bowl, the hot team in the AFC was the Jets, led by
Testaverde, who finally fulfilled the promise he was supposed to
show when he was the No. 1 overall pick in the draft.
	   New York, 1-15 two years ago, entered the postseason on a
six-game winning streak that gave them a 12-4 season under Bill
Parcells, who could become the first coach ever to take three
different teams to a Super Bowl. Like the Broncos and Vikings, the
Jets had a first-round bye along with Atlanta, which finished 14-2
and won the NFC West for the first time since 1980.
	   The Falcons, who were led by running back Jamal Anderson and a
revived defense, finished the season without coach Dan Reeves, who
underwent quadruple heart bypass surgery on Dec. 15, got out of the
hospital three days later, then went back in. Despite that, he was
in the locker room before the final game, a 38-16 victory over
Miami.
	   The day after the season ended, five coaches were fired within a
few hours of one another _ Ray Rhodes of Philadelphia (3-13), Dave
Wannstedt of Chicago (4-12), Dennis Erickson of Seattle (8-8), Dom
Capers of Carolina (4-12), and Ted Marchibroda of Baltimore (6-10).
	   San Francisco's Steve Young, Buffalo's Doug Flutie, Testaverde
and Cunningham all were part of what came to be known as the Year
of the Ancient quarterback, a list that also includes long-time
standbys John Elway of Denver and Dan Marino of Miami. All are 36
or over.
	   Terrell Davis of Denver made life easy for Elway. He became only
the fourth back in NFL history to run for more than 2,000 yards,
finishing with 2,008, 97 short Eric Dickerson's NFL record of
2,105.
	   Moss was clearly the rookie star, although running back Fred
Taylor of Jacksonville and quarterback Peyton Manning of
Indianapolis made claims. Manning, the first pick in the draft, was
shaky at the start, strong at the end, setting a rookie record with
28 touchdown passes.
	   But Ryan Leaf, the second overall pick, wasn't as successful _
either on or off the field.
	   He was benched at midseason after a series of off-field
misadventures, including a tiff with a reporter and late-night
spree in Spokane, Washington, where he bragged ``I could buy you
all.''
	   Leaf was no bargain on the field. He threw just two touchdown
passes, had 15 interceptions and a league-low quarterback rating of
39.0, just about the minimum any QB can have.
</TEXT>
