<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-New Zealand-Antarctic Trek </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Member of ice trek falls ill, delays progress
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RAY LILLEY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) _ A member of Peter Hillary's
Antarctic ice trek team has fallen ill, but supporters said
Thursday the trio will press on with their attempt to ski to the
South Pole.
	   Jon Muir is laid up in the team's tent with suspected food
poisoning, although the team hopes he'll recover within 24 hours,
Hillary's wife Yvonne told The Associated Press.
	   ``I'm hopeful Jon's sickness will pass quickly,'' she said.
``The crucial thing is for them to be on the road again, since food
(supply level) is a factor now.''
	   New Zealander Hillary and Muir and Eric Phillips, both from
Australia, left Scott Base on Nov. 4 to cross country ski to the
South Pole, retracing the 3,000-kilometer (1,875-mile) route of
English explorer Robert Falcon Scott in 1911.
	   Scott's ill-fated expedition made it to the pole, only to die of
starvation on their return a few kilometers (miles) short of help.
	   If successful, the trip led by Hillary _ the son of the first
man to climb Mt. Everest, Sir Edmund Hillary _ will be the longest
ice trek without outside assistance of this century.
	   Too long a delay could force them to scrap the attempt because
their only supplies are what they can fit on sleds that they
brought with them.
	   Phillips reportedly said Wednesday that Muir's illness was a
blow to morale because of concerns he may be too weak to haul his
huge sled on the final 415 kilometers (260 miles) to the South
Pole.
	   ``We cannot go on at the moment because Jon is vomiting and has
a severe headache,'' Phillips told the New Zealand's Herald
newspaper.
	   The team now has to average 22 kilometers (13 miles) a day to
reach the South Pole on their current supplies.
	   The trio has completed just 75 kilometers (47 miles) in the past
eight days, with progress slowed by two blizzards.
	   Yvonne Hillary said she was ``feeling stressed'' about the
trio's slow progress but that they would continue as soon as Muir
is able.
	   ``Oh, there's no possibility of them turning back. They have to
get to the pole, there's no choice for them now but to get to the
pole,'' she said. 	   
</TEXT>
