<SLUG> BC-Sports-Boxing-Foreman-Holmes,0355 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Promoter for Foreman-Holmes says fight will go on
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS throughout with quotes from promoter that fight will go
on &QL; 
 &UR; By JEFF GOODMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ The ``Battle of the Aged'' between George
Foreman and Larry Holmes is still on as scheduled.
	   Promoter Roger Levitt said Wednesday there is no truth to recent
speculation that the Jan. 23 heavyweight fight will be canceled.
	   ``The fight is definitely going to go on,'' Levitt said from his
New York office. ``All of the financial arrangements that need to
be put in place will be done so.''
	   Levitt said the letters of credit, which guarantee the fighters
will receive their share of the purse, must be in order by the
close of business on Thursday.
	   He is optimistic he'll meet the deadline, going as far as making
final travel plans for the fighters.
	   The status of the fight became unclear when one of Levitt's
largest financial backers pulled out about two weeks ago. A
replacement was found earlier this week.
	   ``We informed both boxers and their advisers of our situation
and they were very understanding,'' Levitt said. ``We are doing
everything we can to rectify the situation and this whole scenario
will be tied up by the end of Thursday.''
	   Foreman, who turns 50 on Jan. 10, is to receive dlrs 10 million
for the fight, which will be held at the Houston Astrodome. The
49-year-old Holmes will get dlrs 4 million.
	   Levitt has already given Foreman a dlrs 1 million deposit and
Holmes dlrs 400,000 _ both are nonrefundable.
	   Holmes, who last fought in July 1997, was in Texas on Monday to
obtain his license. Because he is older than 36 he must be approved
by boxing authorities.
	   Foreman's last bout was in November 97.
	   The bout will be carried on pay-per-view cable television.
	   ``Despite all the rumors, we have been assured everything is
moving forward and the fight will go on,'' said Rebecca Kramer, a
spokesman for Viewer's Choice, which will offer the fight telecast.
``There's no truth to the reports that the event has been
canceled.''
</TEXT>
