w1479 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-US-DiggingintoMar     12-30 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-US-Digging into Mars,1009 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ground-pounding experiment hitching ride on Mars lander
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Note in 2nd graf that launch scheduled for Sunday, Jan. 3 &QL; 
 &UR; With SCI-Mars-Name Contest &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo NY373 &QL; 
 &UR; By MARCIA DUNN &QC; 
 &UR; AP Aerospace Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAPE CANAVERAL, Florida (AP) _ An unusually risky
ground-pounding experiment is hitching a ride on NASA's next
spacecraft to Mars.
	   Aboard the Mars Polar Lander, due to lift off Jan. 3 and arrive
at the red planet next December, are two probes designed to slam
into the Martian surface between 400 mph (640 kph) and 500 mph (800
kph) and, if they survive, burrow 3 feet (one meter) deep.
	   It is the first attempt by NASA to crash-land a spacecraft on
another planet with the intent of penetrating its surface and
sending back radio signals.
	   The trick is getting the probes to withstand the impact,
estimated at up to 60,000 times the force of Earth's gravity.
	   To come up with a durable design, project manager Sarah Gavit
and her team at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena,
California, hurled sample probes from planes and shot them out of a
cannon into the ground.
	   They settled on a probe the size of a cantaloupe that is
enclosed in a thermal protective shell the size of a basketball.
Total weight: 8 pounds (3.6 kilograms).
	   The silicon carbide aeroshell is meant to shatter on impact,
with the probe inside separating into two parts connected by a
ribbonlike cable.
	   One part, made of aluminum and magnesium, is supposed to remain
on the surface of Mars to serve as a radio-relay station. The
other, a 4-inch-long (10-centimeter-long), 1 1-2 -inch-wide
(3.8-centimeter-wide), bullet-shaped tube, hopefully will penetrate
as deep as 3 feet (one meter).
	   This stainless steel and tungsten tube contains a miniature
drill that will be propelled out the side to collect bits of soil.
The dirt will fall into a small cup that will be sealed and then
heated, turning any water ice into vapor that would flow into a
chamber containing a laser and mirrors.
	   The laser will emit a beam of light. Scientists will know
whether water vapor is present if any of that light is absorbed.
	   At the same time, temperature sensors will measure the rate at
which each penetrating tube cools after plunging into the ground.
That will allow scientists to determine how fast heat dissipates in
the soil.
	   If all goes well _ a big if _ the probes could collect and send
data for one to three days, the expected lifetime of their tiny
lithium batteries.
	   Almost everything in the probes had to be developed from
scratch.
	   ``Either there was nothing out there small enough, or nothing
that was packaged to survive the kind of forces we're going into,''
says Gavit.
	   In 1996, the Russians used different designs and technologies
for a much larger pair of soil-penetrating probes that were to have
drilled 20 feet (6 meters) beneath the Martian surface. The
spacecraft on which they were launched, unfortunately, never made
it out of Earth orbit _ it came crashing down through the
atmosphere shortly after liftoff.
	   Even with the best design, which engineers believe they have
after three years of testing, luck will play an inordinately large
role when the probes divebomb into Mars near the South Pole on Dec.
3, 1999.
	   They are supposed to peel away from the Mars Polar Lander five
minutes before the lander enters the planet's upper atmosphere.
They should hit the Martian surface a minute before the
three-legged lander plops down some 60 miles (100 kilometers) away,
where it will shovel up dirt for analysis.
	   If the probes hit a small rock or the side of a rock, that's OK
as long as they penetrate. ``But if we go splat right in the middle
of a big one, we're history,'' Gavit says.
	   The terrain near the planet's unexplored South Pole shouldn't be
as rocky as the spot where NASA's Mars Pathfinder bounced down on
July 4, 1997.
	   Just as bad would be landing in soft, fluffy layers of dust.
``The whole thing could be buried,'' Gavit says, preventing radio
signals from getting out.
	   Another problem is if a big gust of wind tilts the probes the
wrong way just before they hit. If the angle at which they descend
is too great, the probes will skip along the surface like pebbles
on a pond.
	   If Gavit and her team get even one radio signal back, they'll be
thrilled _ that means at least part of their package survived and
most of the technologies were demonstrated.
	   Those in charge of the program put the chance of success at
better than 50-50 _ maybe.
	   That's why two probes are flying _ to double the odds.
	   That's also why the dlrs 29 million experiment is part of NASA's
New Millennium program to test revolutionary new, high-risk
technologies.
	   The first New Millennium project is Deep Space 1, launched in
October. The spacecraft is en route to an asteroid, its ion
propulsion engine working well after a sluggish start.
	   The two penetrating probes on the Mars Polar Lander constitute
Deep Space 2.
	   ``It's meant to be pushing the boundaries of what we think is
possible,'' says Carl Pilcher, NASA's science director for solar
system exploration.
	   The science goal _ hunting for water in the Martian soil _ is
secondary to proving the technology works, notes Richard Zurek,
project scientist.
	   ``The idea is to demonstrate just how small you can get these
devices,'' Zurek says, ``with the idea if they're small enough,
then you can send many of them.''
	   Imagine a string of mini weather stations on Mars, for instance,
or a chain of seismographs to register Marsquakes.
	   ``There's a whole area of science, of understanding the planet,
that you could do if you could put down a network of instruments,''
Zurek says.
	   Gavit gets excited just thinking about the earthly spinoffs of
smashproof materials and electronics.
	   Imagine a remote control or tape recorder that didn't break when
it fell on the floor. Or how about indestructible toys? Now that
would be a breakthrough, Gavit says, laughing.
</TEXT>
