<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: was 73.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Feb. 2
	   Roger L. Stevens, a theatrical producer who brought more than
200 plays to the London and Broadway stage, dies in Washington. He
was 87.
	   Haroun Tazieff, an internationally known volcano expert, dies in
Paris. He was 83.
	   Feb. 6
	   Nazim al-Kudsi, an Arab nationalist and former Syrian president,
dies in Jordan. He was 91.
	   Carl Wilson, a Beach Boys founding member, dies in Los Angeles
of complications of lung cancer. He was 51.
	   Feb. 7
	   Lawrence Sanders, a best-selling suspense novelist, dies in
Pompano Beach, Florida. He was 78.
	   Falco, an Austrian-born classical music prodigy who turned to
pop music, dies in a traffic accident in Puerta Plata, Dominican
Republic. He was 40.
	   Feb. 8
	   Halldor Laxness, who won the 1955 Nobel Prize in literature,
dies at a nursing home near Reykjavik, Iceland. He was 95.
	   Feb. 10
	   Erich Mueckenberger, a former member of the East German
Politburo and one of six top officials accused in the killings of
citizens trying to flee to the West, dies in Berlin. He was 87.
	   Feb. 10
	   Maurice Schumann, the London-based radio voice of the French
Resistance during World War II and later foreign minister, dies in
Paris. He was 86.
	   Feb. 17
	   Marie-Louise von Franz, who worked with Swiss psychiatrist Carl
Gustav Jung and wrote books based on his theories, dies in
Kuesnacht, Switzerland, She was 83.
	   Feb. 20
	   John Fulton, an American artist who became a professional
bullfighter, dies from complications following a heart attack in
Seville, Spain. He was 65.
	   Feb. 23
	   Count Andre de Laborde de Monpezat, the father of Denmark's
Prince Henrik and father-in-law of Queen Margrethe, dies in Cayrou,
France. He was 90.
	   Feb. 24
	   Bob Santamaria, an anti-communist crusader, who never held
public office but was still one of the most influential figures in
Australia this century, dies from a brain tumor in Melbourne,
Australia. He was 82.
