<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 12/30/1998 21:52:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1492 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-1998-Deaths 5thAdd   12-30 0276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-1998-Deaths, 5th Add,0276 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: was 83
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   June 8
	   Gen. Sani Abacha, a Nigerian dictator who crushed dissent,
defied world condemnation and repeatedly put off handing power over
to a civilian government, dies of a heart attack in Abuja, Nigeria.
He was 54.
	   June 9
	   Cardinal Agostino Casaroli, the Vatican's former No. 2 official
whose cautious diplomacy helped the church survive in Eastern
Europe during the Cold War, dies in Rome. He was 83.
	   June 14
	   Ginette Mathiot, best-selling French cookbook author, dies in
Paris. She was 91.
	   Eric Tabarly, France's best-known yachtsman who crisscrossed
oceans to win numerous solo titles, dies after falling overboard
near Wales. He was 66.
	   June 17
	   Sheik Mohammed Mutwali Sharawi, a leading cleric in the Muslim
world and minister of religious endowments under former President
Anwar Sadat, dies in Giza, Egypt. He was 87.
	   June 20
	   Conrad Schumann, a former East German soldier whose flight to
the West is one of the best-known photographic images of the Cold
War, commits suicide in Kipfenberg, Germany. He was 56.
	   June 21
	   Francois Lehideux, a former minister in the pro-Nazi Vichy
regime who tirelessly defended its anti-Jewish measures, dies in
France. He was 95.
	   Ernst Brugger, former Swiss president, dies in Grueningen,
Switzerland. He was 84.
	   June 22
	   Maureen O'Sullivan, an Irish-born actress who starred as Jane in
a string of Tarzan films, dies in Phoenix, Arizona. She was 87.
	   June 30
	   Renato Capecchi, an Italian baritone best known for his
interpretations of comic roles, dies in Milan, Italy. He was 74.
 &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
