w1494 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-1998-Deaths 7thAdd   12-30 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-1998-Deaths, 7th Add,0397 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: was 114
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Aug. 3
	   Alfred Schnittke, one of the former Soviet Union's most prolific
composers, dies in Hamburg, Germany, after suffering a stroke. He
was 63.
	   Aug. 5
	   Todor Zhivkov, Bulgaria's longtime Communist dictator and the
last surviving Soviet-bloc Stalinist leader, dies in Sofia,
Bulgaria. He was 86.
	   Aug. 10
	   Alekos Papanikolaou, an architect who led major restoration
works on the Acropolis, dies of pneumonia in Athens, Greece. He was
49.
	   Aug. 12
	   Abdel-Qawi Makkawi, a prominent Yemeni opposition leader and
former prime minister, dies of a heart attack in Cairo, Egypt. He
was 73.
	   Aug. 13
	   Eve Boswell, a Hungarian-born singing star who dominated British
pop charts in the 1950s, dies of a heart attack in Durban, South
Africa. She was 76.
	   Davina Thompson, the world's first known triple transplant
patient dies in Cambridge, England, from lung disease. She was 47.
	   Aug. 16
	   Pan Mingdong, a veteran dissident who was repeatedly jailed for
his activism, dies of cancer in Changsha, China, after a long wait
for a passport that would have enabled him to be treated in the
United States. He was believed to be 49.
	   Aug. 17
	   Elli Souyioutzoglou-Seidari, a photographer universally known as
Nelly, dies in Athens, Greece. She was 99.
	   Aug. 18
	   Otto Wichterle, a Czech researcher who invented the soft contact
lens, dies in Strazisko, Moravia. He was 84.
	   Persis Khambatta, a former Miss India, who was a navigator in
the film ``Star Trek _ The Motion Picture,'' dies in Bombay
following a massive heart attack. She was 49.
	   Aug. 20
	   Vu Van Mau, a prominent figure in South Vietnam and prime
minister for five days before it fell to the Communist North in
1975, dies in Paris. He was 84.
	   Aug. 21
	   Wanda Toscanini Horowitz, conductor Arturo Toscanini's daughter
who nurtured and guarded her husband, piano virtuoso Vladimir
Horowitz, dies in New York. She was 90.
	   Aug. 22
	   Elena Garro, a leading Mexican playwright and novelist, dies in
Cuernavaca, Mexico, of heart and lung failure. She was 77.
	   Aug. 26
	   Frederick Reines, a Nobel Prize-winning physicist known as the
father of neutrino physics for his groundbreaking research on
particle physics, dies in Irvine, California, from complications of
Parkinson's disease. He was 80.
 &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
