w1498 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-1998-Deaths 10thAdd   12-30 0254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-1998-Deaths, 10th Add,0254 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: was 90
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Nov. 7
	   John Hunt, who led the British expedition that enabled Sir
Edmund Hillary of New Zealand and Tenzing Norgay of Nepal to
conquer Mount Everest, dies in Henley-on-Thames, England. He was
88.
	   Nov. 8
	   Jean Marais, an actor who began his career as the protege of
surrealist artist Jean Cocteau and became a pillar of the French
cinema, dies in Cannes, France. He was 84.
	   Nov. 13
	   French actress Edwige Feuillere, whose career on the stage and
in the movies spanned more than 60 years, dies in Paris. She was
91.
	   Nov. 15
	   Kwame Ture, who as Stokely Carmichael made the phrase ``black
power'' a rallying cry of the civil rights upheavals of the 1960s,
dies in Guinea. He was 57.
	   Nov. 17
	   Yefim Geller, a chess grandmaster who helped found a renowned
Soviet chess school, dies. The place of death is unknown. He was
73.
	   Nov. 18
	   Gerard Grisey, a leading modern French composer, dies of a
stroke in Paris. He was 52.
	   Nov. 20
	   Galina Starovoitova, an outspoken deputy in Russia's lower house
of parliament, is gunned down in St. Petersburg, Russia.
	   Nov. 22
	   Vladimir Demikhov, a Russian surgeon who conducted the world's
first animal heart and lung transplants, dies after a long illness.
The place of death is unknown. He was 82.
	   Nov. 22
	   Mikolaj Kozakiewicz, a peasant party activist who became the
speaker of Poland's first post-communist parliament, dies in
Warsaw, Poland. He was 75.
 &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
