<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 12/30/1998 21:57:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1499 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-1998-Deaths 11thAdd   12-30 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-1998-Deaths, 11th Add,0423 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: was 75
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Dec. 1
	   Freddie Young, a triple Oscar winner for his cinematography on
the legendary films ``Lawrence of Arabia,'' ``Doctor Zhivago'' and
``Ryan's Daughter,'' dies in London. He was 96.
	   Dec. 2
	   Cleopa, the charismatic Romanian monk persecuted by communists
and admired by pilgrims, dies in the Sihastria monastery in
northern Romania. He was 87.
	   Dec. 6
	   Cesar Baldaccini, a sculptor best-known for compressing cars
into huge blocks of twisted steel, dies of cancer in Paris. He was
77.
	   Sengchen Lobsang Gyaltsen, a senior Tibetan Buddhist cleric and
controversial supporter of Chinese rule who openly criticized the
Dalai Lama, dies in Lhasa, Tibiet. He was 62.
	   Dec. 10
	   Wang Ganchang, the scientist credited with founding China's
atomic bomb program, dies in Beijing. He was 90.
	   Dec. 13
	   British entertainment tycoon Lew Grade, who founded Britain's
first commercially funded television company, dies of heart failure
in London. He was 91.
	   Dec. 17
	   Dr. Patrick Leahy, Ireland's leading euthanasia campaigner, dies
in his sleep at home in Dublin, Ireland. He was 81.
	   Dec. 19
	   Antonio Ordonez, one of Spain's most famous bullfighters and a
close friend of Ernest Hemingway and Orson Welles, dies in a
hospital in Seville, Spain. He was 66.
	   Mel Fisher, a treasure hunter who found fortune in underwater
riches left behind by unlucky Spanish sea captains, dies in Key
West, Florida. He was 76.
	   Dec. 20
	   Andre Dewavrin, a leading member of the French resistance and
one of Gen. Charles de Gaulle's closest collaborators during World
War II, dies in Paris. He was 88.
	   Sir Alan Hodgkin, a biologist who won the 1963 Nobel Prize in
medicine as part of a team that helped explain how nerve cells send
messages to the brain, dies in Cambridge, England. He was 84.
	   Dec. 22
	   The Rev. Lord Soper, a Methodist minister and Britain's most
famous soapbox orator, dies in London. He was 95.
	   Dec. 24
	   Raemer Schreiber, a physicist who helped assemble the plutonium
cores for the world's first atomic blast and the bomb that was
dropped on Nagasaki, Japan, dies in Los Alamos, New Mexico. He was
88.
	   Dec. 25
	   Swiss climate researcher Hans Oeschger, who warned of the
effects of human activity on the Earth's climate, dies in Bern,
Switzerland. He was 71.
	   Dec. 26
	   Cathal Goulding, a committed Marxist and former chief of staff
of the Irish Republican Army, dies in Dublin, Ireland. He was 75.
</TEXT>
