<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 12/30/1998 22:00:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1502 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-1998Chronology 12Takes   12-30 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-1998 Chronology, 12 Takes,0416 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chronology of news events in 1998
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Updates version transmitted Dec. 15 with additional December
dates &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   A month-by-month chronology of notable news in 1998:
	   Jan. 1
	   A 1,000-strong band of Hutu rebels attacks an army base outside
Bujumbura, Burundi, killing at least 150 civilians.
	   Jan. 3
	   Kenya's President Daniel arap Moi wins his fifth straight term.
	   Jan. 4
	   Valdas Adamkus, an ex-administrator for the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency, wins Lithuanian presidency.
	   Jan. 5
	   A passenger train slams into a parked train in northern India,
killing at least 51 people.
	   Jan. 9
	   A bomb explodes outside the New Delhi police chief's office and
injures at least 48 people.
	   Jan. 11
	   An armed gang attacks two villages outside Algiers, Algeria and
slaughters 120 people.
	   Jan. 12
	   Nineteen European nations sign an agreement to prohibit the
genetic replication of humans beings; Cuba's President Fidel Castro
wins re-election.
	   Jan. 13
	   An Afghan cargo plane crashes in southwestern Pakistan, killing
all 51 people aboard.
	   Jan. 15
	   Milo Djukanovic is inaugurated president of Montenegro;
Indonesian President Suharto signs a new deal with the
International Monetary Fund aimed at boosting the nation's troubled
economy.
	   Jan. 16
	   Turkey's high court outlaws the Islamic-oriented Welfare Party;
a methane explosion in a coal mine in southern Serbia kills 29
miners.
	   Jan. 18.
	   The Bosnian Serbs' legislature elects Milorad Dodik premier.
	   Jan. 20
	   Dr. James Robl at the University of Massachusetts and Dr. Steven
Stice of Advanced Cell Technology Inc. announce that they have
successfully cloned two identical, genetically engineered calves.
	   Jan. 21
	   Pope John Paul II lands in Cuba to start a historic five-day
visit.
	   Jan. 23
	   Pakistani national Mir Aimal Kasi is sentenced to death in
Fairfax, Virginia, for a politically motivated ambush outside CIA
headquarters five years ago that left two men dead and three others
wounded.
	   Jan. 28
	   President Jacques Chirac inaugurates the futuristic 80,000-seat
Stadium of France in Saint-Denis, France; a judge in Poonamallee,
India, convicts 26 conspirators in the 1991 assassination of former
Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and orders all to be hanged.
	   Jan. 30
	   Former rebel groups win control of most of the local councils in
Sri Lanka's Tamil heartland.
 &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-1998 Chronology, 12 Takes; CT:i; 
