<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 12/30/1998 22:05:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1511 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-1998Chronology 7thAdd   12-30 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-1998 Chronology, 7th Add,0655 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: prime minister.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Aug. 1
	   Serbian forces attack and burn villages in Kosovo, despite an
official pledge that their offensive is over; a U.N. tribunal's
first genocide trial ends when a Bosnian Serb who set up three
notorious prison camps dies in his cell of a heart attack.
	   Aug 3
	   Serb forces overrun another ethnic Albanian stronghold and press
their attacks elsewhere in Kosovo; Kashmiri guerrillas kill 34
construction workers in northern India.
	   Aug. 6
	   Fighting eases in Kosovo after a fierce, two-week Serb offensive
that drove tens of thousands of people from their homes.
	   Aug. 7
	   Terrorist bombs explode minutes apart outside the U.S. embassies
in Kenya and Tanzania, killing 224 people and injuring thousands;
Andres Pastrana is sworn in as Colombia's president.
	   Aug. 10
	   More than 2,000 people die in flooding across China.
	   Aug. 12
	   Swiss banks agree to pay dlrs 1.25 billion to Holocaust
survivors as restitution for lost assets.
	   Aug. 14
	   President Laurent Kabila flees Congo's embattled capital.
	   Aug. 15
	   Raul Cubas is sworn in as president of Paraguay, marking the
first transfer of power between elected civilians since the end of
a 34-year military dictatorship in 1989; eighteen foreign activists
sentenced to five years of hard labor for handing out pro-democracy
leaflets are deported from Myanmar; a car bomb tears apart the
center of Omagh, Northern Ireland, killing 29 people and injuring
more than 330.
	   Aug. 17
	   U.S. President Bill Clinton undergoes questioning before a grand
jury about his relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky; Russia effectively devalues the ruble.
	   Aug. 20
	   Retaliating after the embassy bombings in East Africa, U.S.
forces attack alleged terrorist camps in Afghanistan and a chemical
plant in Sudan causing ``moderate to heavy damage''; Canada's
Supreme Court rules that Quebec cannot secede without the federal
government's consent.
	   Aug. 21
	   Former apartheid president P. W. Botha of South Africa is found
guilty of ignoring a summons from a panel investigating atrocities
during the country's era of white rule.
	   Aug. 22
	   Angolan troops enter the war against Congolese rebels.
	   Aug. 23
	   Russian President Boris Yeltsin replaces Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko with former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin.
	   Aug. 24
	   Congo's Angolan allies drive rebels from a string of Atlantic
coast towns in a stunning reversal of rebel gains; the United
States and Britain agree to allow two Libyans charged in the 1988
bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over Scotland to be tried by a
Scottish court in the Netherlands.
	   Aug. 25
	   Seven Cuban-Americans are indicted by a federal grand jury in
San Juan, Puerto Rico, on charges of conspiracy to murder Cuban
President Fidel Castro.
	   Aug. 26
	   A suspect in the bombing of the U.S. Embassy in Kenya is brought
to the United States for trial.
	   Aug. 27
	   The Dow tumbles 357.36 points, extending Wall Street's summer
slide to 12.6 percent, as the deepening crisis in Russia and doubts
about a Japanese recovery jolt stock markets around the world.
	   Aug. 28
	   A second suspect in the bombings of the U.S. Embassy in Kenya is
brought to the United States for trial; Gen. Huseyin Kivrikoglu
takes control Turkey's armed forces, NATO's second-largest army,
vowing to intensify the military's fight against radical Islam.
	   Aug. 31
	   The Dow plummets a near-record 512 points, tumbling below 8,000
for the first time in seven months; Russian lawmakers
overwhelmingly reject the appointment of Viktor Chernomyrdin as
prime minister; North Korea fires a ballistic missile that likely
flies over northeastern Japan and lands in the Pacific Ocean;
Congo's President Laurent Kabila declares victory in the country's
southwestern war over an army of rebels.
 &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
