<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-1998 Chronology, 8th Add,0825 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: of rebels.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Sept. 1
	   Malaysia imposes radical restrictions on foreign exchange
trading.
	   Sept. 2
	   A Swissair jetliner crashes off Nova Scotia, killing all 229
aboard; Malaysia's Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad fires his deputy
prime minister Anwar Ibrahim.
	   Sept. 6
	   Malta's Nationalist Party claims victory in parliamentary
elections. Prime Minister Alfred Sant of the Labor Party concedes
defeat and resigns.
	   Sept. 7
	   The lower chamber of Russian parliament rejects Viktor
Chernomyrdin as prime minister for the second time.
	   Sept. 10
	   Afghanistan's rulers say that nine of 11 Iranian diplomats
missing since a battle in August are dead, but deny responsibility
for the killings.
	   Sept. 11
	   Russian lawmakers overwhelmingly approve former spy chief
Yevgeny Primakov as prime minister; the British government frees
six convicted IRA and pro-British militants; Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr tells U.S. Congress that there are 11 grounds for
impeaching President Bill Clinton, including perjury and
obstruction of justice in his effort to conceal his affair with
Monica Lewinsky; after eight days of rain and flooding, the death
toll in Mexico's Chiapas state rises to more than 100; dozens of
junior military officers revolt at Lesotho's military headquarters.
	   Sept. 12
	   Azem Hajdari, a leading Albanian opposition lawmaker, is
assassinated by unidentified gunmen.
	   Sept. 13
	   The Yugoslav republic of Montenegro deports thousands of Kosovo
refugees to Albania; Former Albanian President Sali Berisha blames
Albanian Socialist Premier Fatos Nano for opposition lawmaker Azem
Hajdari's killing and demands his resignation.
	   Sept. l4
	   Supporters of former Albanian President Sali Berisha seize
government buildings in Tirana and demand the government resign;
ten people are charged in what prosecutors say is the largest Cuban
spy ring ever uncovered in the United States since Fidel Castro
came to power nearly 40 years ago.
	   Sept. 17
	   Israelis in a passing car open fire on Palestinian high school
students in the West Bank, killing one and wounding another;
demonstrators close down government offices and private businesses
in Lesotho to protest election results, while a week-old mutiny by
junior army officers continues.
	   Sept. 18
	   Chrysler Corp. shareholders vote to merge the No. 3 U.S.
automaker with Germany's Daimler-Benz AG; the armed Basque
separatist group ETA begins observing an open-ended cease-fire
after 30 years of fighting for an independent homeland.
	   Sept. 19
	   A ferry carrying 443 people sinks in stormy waters south of
Manila, killing at least 39 of the 454 people on board.
	   Sept. 20
	   The Social Democrats come through Sweden's national elections
with their worst performance ever, but conservative parties fail to
budge them from power; Malaysia's sacked deputy prime minister
Anwar Ibrahim is arrested after thousands of his supporters march
to the prime minister's house and demand the ouster of Asia's
longest-serving leader.
	   Sept. 21
	   Three Croats accused of atrocities against Serb rebels and
civilians in the 1991 Serbo-Croat war decline to enter a plea at
the opening of the first such trial in Croatia.
	   Sept. 22
	   Troops from South Africa and Botswana cross into Lesotho and
storm the royal palace, touching off a gunbattle with protesters;
Serb forces pound villages with heavy artillery and tank fire in
the heartland of ethnic Albanian resistance in Kosovo.
	   Sept. 23
	   Doctors in France transplant a hand and forearm on an accident
victim; the U.N. Security Council demands a cease-fire in Kosovo
and threatens further action if fighting continues.
	   Sept. 24
	   Iran says it is distancing itself from a dlrs 2.5 million reward
for killing author Salman Rushdie, and is ready to exchange
ambassadors with Britain; Hurricane Georges charges toward the
Florida Keys, leaving more than 300 people dead in the Caribbean;
soldiers from South Africa and Botswana move to quell an outbreak
of looting after suppressing mutinous Lesotho troops;
ultranationalist Nikola Poplasen defeats Western-backed Biljana
Plavsic for the presidency in the Serb-run part of Bosnia.
	   Sept. 27
	   Gerhard Schroeder and his Social Democrats win national
elections after 16 years of conservative rule under Chancellor
Helmut Kohl.
	   Sept. 28
	   Serbia's premier Mirko Marjanovic announces Kosovo's armed
separatists have been defeated and special police units will be
withdrawn from the province _ a condition demanded by American and
European governments to avert a NATO attack; Albanian Socialist
Premier Fatos Nano resigns, two weeks after rioting in the wake of
opposition lawmaker Azem Hajdari's assassination.
	   Sept. 29
	   Malaysia's sacked deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim appears in
court and pleads not guilty to corruption and sodomy charges.
 &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
