<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-1998 Chronology, 10th Add,0602 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: monitoring sites.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Nov. 1
	   Hamas' military wing makes its first direct threat against the
government of Yasser Arafat, accusing the Palestinian leader of
treason.
	   Nov. 2
	   More than 9,000 people die in Central America in floods and
mudslides unleashed by Hurricane Mitch.
	   Nov. 3
	   Patrizia Reggiani Martinelli, the ex-wife of murdered fashion
heir Maurizio Gucci, is convicted of his contract killing and
sentenced to 29 years in prison; a center-right conservative
coalition wins parliamentary elections in Macedonia, defeating the
ruling former Communists.
	   Nov. 4
	   Democrats show surprising strength against Republicans in U.S.
parliamentary elections; U.S. district court indicts fugitive Saudi
millionaire Osama bin Laden and a top aide in the U.S. Embassy
bombings in Africa, and authorities offer a record dlrs 5 million
reward for bin Laden's capture; a car carrying two bombs speeds
through Red Square and explodes just outside the main gate to the
Kremlin, injuring three guards and the car's mentally ill driver.
	   Nov. 6
	   A car bomb explodes in Jerusalem, killing two suicide attackers,
wounding 21 and prompting the Israeli Cabinet to suspend
implementation of the Palestinian peace accord. The Islamic
militant group Hamas claims responsibility; Newt Gingrich announces
he won't seek another term as U.S. House Speaker.
	   Nov. 9
	   A left-wing coalition becomes the strongest force in Venezuela's
new Congress.
	   Nov. 10
	   The Labor Party sweeps to victory for the first time in
Bermuda's general elections, ending the conservatives' 30-year
rule.
	   Nov. 11
	   The Israeli Cabinet narrowly ratifies the peace agreement with
the Palestinians.
	   Nov. 13
	   President Boris Yeltsin's envoy to Chechnya is freed, more than
six months after being taken hostage.
	   Nov. 15
	   The governor of Okinawa, Japan, opposed to having U.S. troops on
Okinawa, loses his re-election bid.
	   Nov. 17
	   Israel's parliament overwhelmingly approves the latest Mideast
land-for-peace accord with the Palestinians, paving the way for an
Israeli troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
	   Nov. 19
	   Burkina Faso's incumbent president, Blaise Compaore, wins a
sweeping electoral victory, extending his mandate by another seven
years.
	   Nov. 20
	   A Rome court frees Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan from
detention; Israel withdraws troops from parts of the northern West
Bank, fulfilling the first step of the new Mideast peace accord and
moving the Palestinians a step closer to statehood; a Russian
Proton booster rocket carries the first part of the international
space station into orbit, heralding the start of a new era in
international space colonization; Galina Starovoitova, a prominent
member of Russian parliament, is shot to death.
	   Nov. 24
	   The party that ruled Sao Tome and Principe for 16 years under a
single-party Marxist system wins a majority in Parliament; the
Palestinians open Gaza International Airport, their first gateway
to the world.
	   Nov. 25
	   Britain's highest court rules that Gen. Augusto Pinochet does
not have immunity from arrest, reversing a court ruling that
Pinochet's arrest Oct. 16 is illegal.
	   Nov. 26
	   A train collision in India kills at least 208.
	   Nov. 29
	   A magnitude-6.5 quake kills at least 25 people in Mangole
island, Indonesia.
	   Nov. 30
	   In the first war-crimes convictions following Guatemala's civil
war, three former pro-government fighters are sentenced to death
for their role in a 1982 massacre of Indian villagers.
 &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
