<HEADER>
w1518 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-1998Chronology 11thAdd   12-30 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-1998 Chronology, 11th Add,0771 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: Indian villagers.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Dec. 1
	   U.S. President Bill Clinton lifts some sanctions against India
and Pakistan as a result of progress made by the two countries in
curbing their nuclear weapons programs.
	   Dec. 2
	   Grenada's governor general dissolves Parliament, paving the way
for early elections; a fire at an orphanage in Manila kills at
least 28 people, mostly children; President Emile Lahoud appoints
U.S.-educated economist Salim Hoss as Lebanon's next prime
minister.
	   Dec. 4
	   Space shuttle Endeavour blasts off from Cape Canaveral, Florida,
on NASA's first space station construction flight.
	   Dec. 5
	   Turkish police arrest about 400 people after an Italy-bound ship
packed with hundreds of illegal immigrants, mostly Turkish Kurds,
runs aground off Canakkale, Turkey.
	   Dec. 6
	   Former Lt. Col. Hugo Chavez, who staged a bloody coup attempt
six years ago, is elected president of Venezuela.
	   Dec. 7
	   A coalition of one-time opponents of the late dictator Gen. Sani
Abacha wins a majority of seats in Nigeria's key local council
elections; returning to work from a hospital, Boris Yeltsin fires
most of his top aides and says he is assuming control of two key
government agencies.
	   Dec. 9
	   Britain rejects former Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet's plea
to be set free, and rules that Spain can start extradition
proceedings on charges of genocide, torture and kidnapping by his
security forces.
	   Dec. 10
	   Five American and one Russian astronauts open the doors to the
new international space station, becoming the first guests aboard
the 250-mile-high (400-kilometer-high) outpost; keeping a promise
to Israel and the United States, a group of senior Palestinians led
by Yasser Arafat votes overwhelmingly to revoke clauses of the PLO
charter calling for Israel's destruction.
	   Dec. 13
	   Puerto Ricans reject U.S. statehood.
	   Dec. 14
	   In the presence of U.S. President Bill Clinton, hundreds of top
Palestinian officials, including former guerrilla fighters,
renounce parts of the Palestinian charter that call for the
destruction of Israel.
	   Dec. 16
	   U.S. President Bill Clinton orders a ``strong, sustained series
of airstrikes'' against Iraq in response to Saddam Hussein's
continued defiance of U.N. weapons inspectors.
	   Dec. 17
	   U.S. forces trigger a second wave of airstrikes against Iraq;
Guinea's President Lansana Conte wins reelection to a seven-year
term.
	   Dec. 18
	   Anti-aircraft fire shakes central Baghdad for a third straight
night; a boat carrying Cubans capsizes in the Atlantic, killing
eight people and leaving at least four missing in what appears to
be the deadliest immigrant-smuggling attempt ever off the Florida
coast.
	   Dec. 19
	   U.S. President Bill Clinton is impeached by the
Republican-controlled House for perjury and obstruction of justice;
U.S. President Bill Clinton halts airstrikes against Iraq after a
fourth day of attacks, saying U.S. and British forces had inflicted
``significant damage'' on Iraq's military establishment.
	   Dec. 20
	   A 27-year-old woman gives birth to the only known living set of
octuplets in Houston, Texas.
	   Dec. 21
	   Israel's parliament rejects Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
peace policies, then gives initial approval to a law calling early
elections; a Chinese court sentences a prominent dissident to 13
years in prison.
	   Dec. 23
	   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat frees Hamas spiritual leader
Sheik Ahmed Yassin from house arrest.
	   Dec. 24
	   Serb forces backed by tanks and artillery launch a strong attack
on a rebel stronghold in Kosovo, burning houses and killing at
least one person.
	   Dec. 25
	   The presidents of Russia and Belarus agree to take steps to
merge the two former Soviet republics into a single state.
	   Dec. 26
	   Two senior Khmer Rouge leaders wanted for genocide and crimes
against humanity defect to the Cambodian government, saying they
want to become ``ordinary citizens.''
	   Dec. 28
	   U.S. warplanes patrolling a ``no-fly zone'' in northern Iraq
fire at an Iraqi air defense site after coming under attack,
killing four Iraqi soldiers and injuring seven others; Islamic
militants kidnap 16 Western tourists, including two Americans, in
southern Yemen and demand the release of two jailed leaders; the
storm-decimated Sydney-to-Hobart yacht race leaves four sailors
dead and two missing.
	   Dec. 29
	   An American woman and two British men are killed when Yemeni
troops storm the hideout of kidnappers who abducted 16 foreign
tourists on Dec. 28.
</TEXT>
