<HEADER>
w1520 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Boxing-Jones-F     12-30 0269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Boxing-Jones-Frazier,0269 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Roy Jones likes Ricky Frazier. That's why Jones
says he is giving the moonlighting New York City policeman a shot
at his WBC and WBA light heavyweight crowns next month.
	   ``Anytime you see a good opponent, you like to give him a
chance. I don't mind if my kids looked up at him,'' Jones said of
Frazier, who has patrolled the streets of Harlem for the last 16
years.
	   But Jones says that he will not that get in his way when he
fights the 39-year-old Frazier on Jan. 9 at the Civic Center in his
hometown of Penscola, Fla.
	   ``He is a southpaw with a pistol. I think I can manage that. I
don't intend on getting beat for some more years,'' said Jones, who
is 39-1 with 32 knockouts. ``I feel that I am enjoying myself in
the ring again and I'm getting back to being the old Roy Jones.''
	   After losing a controversial decision which cost him a gold
medal in the 1988 Olympics, Jones took it out on the pros, winning
middleweight and super middleweight titles to go with his light
heavyweight title.
	   ``I worked hard for everything and I earned that,'' he said.
``I'm glad that I am the best pound-for-pound boxer in the world
because that was my goal after being robbed in the Olympics.''
	   Frazier is getting his first breakthrough fight and still can't
quite believe it is happening.
	   ``I learned not to believe. Being a cop, I don't believe that
much as well,'' said Frazier, who is 16-3-1 with seven KOs. ``I'm
just training as hard as I can but there is still one part of me
that feels like something is going to happen.''
</TEXT>
