w1533 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-KhmerRouge     12-30 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Khmer Rouge leaders enjoy VIP treatment as UN probes possible trial
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHRIS FONTAINE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ As two Khmer Rouge leaders left the
capital on Thursday for a seaside vacation, the United Nations
human rights officer for Cambodia said work will proceed at the
U.N. to explore bringing those responsible for genocide to justice.
	   After basking in VIP treatment and luxury accommodations in
Phnom Penh for the past two days, Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea began
a tour of the country that they helped turn into a vast slave-labor
camp when the Khmer Rouge held power from 1975-79.
	   The two drove with their families in luxury vehicles to the
seaside resort town of Sihanoukville, the first leg of a tour that
will take them to the ancient Angkor temple complex and their home
provinces.
	   The two guerrilla chiefs, who share blame for the deaths of up
to 2 million Cambodians during the Khmer Rouge reign, emerged from
hiding last week and sealed a defection deal with Prime Minister
Hun Sen that included assurances they would not face trial.
	   The deal, which contradicted earlier pronouncements by Hun Sen
that remaining Khmer Rouge leaders would stand trial if captured,
has shaken hopes that the architects of the murderous experiment
will ever face justice.
	   At the request of Cambodia's leaders, the United Nations sent a
trio of legal experts to Cambodia last month to assess existing
evidence against senior Khmer Rouge members and offer
recommendations for a tribunal.
	   ``The defection of Noun Chea and Khieu Samphan does not change
the plans,'' said Thomas Hammarberg, the U.N. rights officer for
Cambodia, from his home in Sweden. ``We intend to present their
recommendations as soon as possible to the government and hope for
a constructive discussion.''
	   King Norodom Sihanouk, who initially voiced support for Hun
Sen's defection deal, said Tuesday he would not provide amnesties
for Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea because of the ``undeniable
discontent'' of a majority of Cambodians in seeing the bloodstained
leaders go free.
	   Hun Sen has since been silent on the issue, but as Cambodia's
most powerful man he can easily put pressure his nation's pliant
court's to ensure there is no Cambodian trial for the Khmer Rouge.
	   Hopes for a tribunal now seem to rest solely with the U.N.,
which could pass resolutions to try the Khmer Rouge in an
international court for crimes against humanity.
	   Sihanouk appeared to voice his support for that option Tuesday
when he said the international community had ``the perfect right to
take up the case of genocide in Cambodia'' because of the nature of
the Khmer Rouge crimes.
	   Several possibilities for a trial are being considered by the
U.N. team, according to Hammarberg, who said it was necessary to
send a message to future generations in Cambodia that atrocities
cannot go unpunished.
	   ``Considering the scale and the brutality of the Khmer Rouge
crimes, genuine healing in Cambodia will be extremely difficult
without a justice process,'' he said.
</TEXT>
