<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 12/30/1998 22:39:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1536 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-UnrestAhead     12-30 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Unrest Ahead </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian military predicts more unrest in 1999
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Crime rose 10 percent in economically
battered Indonesia in 1998, and the government expects more unrest
in the year ahead, a newspaper reported Thursday.
	   Military officials, whose resources have been stretched by riots
and protests, predicted that clashes between rival political groups
will escalate ahead of parliamentary elections scheduled for June.
	   However, they said any political unrest is unlikely to reach the
scale of street violence in May that helped oust former President
Suharto after 32 years of authoritarian rule.
	   Some 1,200 people died in several days of riots in Jakarta, the
Indonesian capital, and many shops and homes in other major cities
were also burned and looted.
	   ``We'll experience an increasing trend of unrest in 1999,'' The
Jakarta Post quoted Zaini Azhar Maulani, chief of military
intelligence, as saying in yearend remarks Wednesday.
	   ``But now there is only a small group of people that are
described as anarchic who still want a change in the state
leadership,'' he said.
	   Student protesters have staged sometimes violent demonstrations
against the government of President B.J. Habibie, Suharto's
successor, to protest the pace and scope of political reforms. They
also want Suharto to be put on trial on corruption charges.
	   However, most student rallies have been smaller than those that
preceded the fall of Suharto.
	   There have also been incidents of church- and mosque-burnings as
religious and ethnic tensions in predominately Muslim Indonesia
rise. The economy remains mired in its worst crisis in three
decades, leading to higher unemployment and crime rates.
	   Authorities recorded 157,180 crimes across the archipelago
nation of 200 million people in 1998, 10 percent higher than the
previous year, said national police chief Lt. Gen. Roesmanhadi. The
crimes included armed robbery and vehicle theft.
	   ``The greater incidence of crimes this year is closely related
to the prolonged economic crisis and the social and political
tension here,'' the Post quoted him as saying.
	   The figures excluded looting, arson and other crimes tied to the
frequent riots that erupted across Indonesia in 1998.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Indonesia-Unrest Ahead; CT:i; 
