<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 12/30/1998 22:48:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1539 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Taiwan-Independen     12-30 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Taiwan-Independence,0876 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan's main opposition might change independence stance
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANNIE HUANG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ It was a thrilling moment for many
Taiwanese when the main opposition party risked China's wrath and
adopted a platform calling for formal independence from the
mainland back in 1988.
	   Today, the thrill has been replaced by a deep soul-searching.
After its recent election setback, the Democratic Progressive Party
faces calls for changing the sacrosanct platform, if not scrapping
it entirely.
	   The reason: Beijing claims sovereignty over the island and
threatens to invade if Taiwan ever declares independence, and few
foreign countries, if any, would likely intervene in a war over
Taiwan.
	   Over a decade's time, more voters have awakened to that reality,
and more DPP politicians realize formal independence may be nothing
but wishful thinking that ends up costing them the votes of people
who are scared of the consequences of a declaration of
independence.
	   If the DPP sticks to a dream that can't be realized, the party
could see more voters flee to the ruling Nationalist Party, which
increasingly has become viewed as a stabilizing force because of
its moderate stance on China relations.
	   The Nationalists badly beat the DPP in Dec. 5 legislative
elections, and voters chose Nationalist challenger Ma Ying-jeou to
replace the DPP's top politician, Chen Shui-bian, as mayor of the
capital city of Taipei.
	   The defeat left the DPP reeling and has focused attention on
whether the independence platform might be changed. Top DPP
politicians will hold an unprecedented televised debate on the
issue Sunday, no doubt to be followed by months of public and
private talks before the platform comes up for formal discussion at
the party congress in May.
	   Shen Fu-hsiung is among several DPP lawmakers proposing to amend
the independence platform and to subject any declaration of
independence to constitutional changes rather than a vote by the
public.
	   ``Our stance is not fundamentally different from that of
President Lee Teng-hui. But one is seen as safe and the other
dangerous,'' Shen said Sunday in an interview with The Associated
Press.
	   Lee has called Taiwan and China separate but equal, though he
favors eventual reunification.
	   ``Many people believe we will make the announcement of
independence once we are in power so they do what they can to
prevent such a disaster,'' Shen said.
	   But he insisted the DPP would not make such a provocative move,
now that Taiwan has already been turned into what he calls a de
facto sovereign state. Lee was elected as its first president by
popular vote in 1996 after he was appointed to a term by a
rubberstamp National Assembly.
	   ``Is there one country in the world which elects its own
president and yet it is not a sovereign state?'' Shen asked. ``We
elected a president without declaring independence, and China found
no excuse to attack us.''
	   Despite its territorial claims, China test-fired missiles off
the Taiwanese coast during the presidential election campaign but
did not follow through on threats to invade the island.
	   ``When you have been estranged from your wife for 50 years, you
don't have to go to your rooftop to announce you are living with
another woman,'' Shen said.
	   Chiang Kai-shek's Chinese Nationalists retreated to Taiwan in
1949 after losing a civil war to Mao Tse-tung's communist forces.
The Nationalists clung to their claim as sole legitimate rulers of
all of China _ and for years anyone advocating independence faced
charges of subversion _ but the hard lines were dropped during the
past decade of democratization.
	   This leaves many Taiwanese favoring the status quo. But while
shifting away from the independence claim might help DPP
politicians win popular support, the party's hard-liners would be
furious.
	   Two years ago, former DPP chairman Hsu Hsin-liang said no
declaration of independence was necessary because Taiwan was
already sovereign. He was viciously attacked, even manhandled, by
party activists.
	   The current DPP chairman, Lin Yih-hsiung, has ordered a policy
review but refrained from calling for a change, underscoring the
party's divide.
	   With a presidential election just 15 months away, lingering
impressions that the DPP is reckless toward China relations do not
bode well for the party.
	   A Chinese semi-official body handling exchanges with Taiwan has
made opposing Taiwanese independence its top priority next year.
	   ``The mainland does not intend to impose its system and
lifestyle on Taiwan,'' said Tang Shubei, a senior official of the
Association for Relations across the Taiwan Strait. But Taiwanese
``cannot use any referendum to decide the future of Taiwan nor can
they separate Taiwan from Chinese territory. This is our main
concern.''
	   A more pragmatic attitude toward China is also needed, some say.
	   ``Voters question our ability to handle relations with China,
not just our stance,'' said Sisy Chen, a top aide to Hsu, the
former DPP chairman. ``We need to review our entire policy, our
attitude, whether we still want to stage a demonstration next time
China sends a delegate here.'' 	   
</TEXT>
