<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-GDP </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Vietnam GDP grows at 5.8 percent in 1998
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ Vietnam's economy grew by 5.8 percent in
1998, its lowest increase in recent years, according to preliminary
data Thursday from the General Statistical Office.
	   Vietnam's gross domestic product _ the measure of all goods and
services produced within its borders _ fell short of government
forecasts as the country was hit hard by Asia's economic crisis.
	   Declines in exports to the rest of Asia and investment from the
region slowed Vietnam's economy, which had grown by 8.3 percent
last year and more than 9 percent in 1996.
	   The government originally had estimated GDP growth for 1998 at 9
percent but slashed that to 6 percent in July, along with most
other economic indicators.
	   According to Thursday's figures, agricultural production grew by
2.8 percent in 1998, while industrial production growth stood at
10.9 percent and services at 4.2 percent.
	   The foreign investment sector of the economy posted the highest
growth of 18.2 percent _ although that still was lower that 1997's
figure _ while the state sector grew by 5.7 percent and the private
sector 7 percent.
	   Vietnamese leaders have predicted that 1999 would be an even
more difficult and challenging year for their country, one of the
region's poorest.
	   The National Assembly last month set the GDP growth target at 5
percent to 6 percent. The government stressed the target was only a
goal, not a figure that must be achieved, as was the case before
Vietnam began switching from a central command economy to a market
economy a decade ago.
</TEXT>
