w1548 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Thailand-Myanmar-Drug     12-30 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Myanmar-Drugs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Myanmar ethnic rebels burn speed pills, pledge to fight drugs
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Shan rebels from Myanmar burned 300,000
amphetamine pills and a kilogram (2.2 pounds) of heroin in an
attempt to prove they are drug fighters not traffickers, local
papers reported on Thursday.
	   The Shan are one of several ethnic groups that have been
fighting for autonomy from the government of Myanmar, also known as
Burma, for decades.
	   Their troops are bracing for a massive assault by Myanmar's army
that Thai intelligence officials have said is imminent, and they
are attempting to improve their image to gain more support.
	   Historically, the Shan have received little support in their
struggle from the international community because of their
reputation as opium and heroin traffickers.
	   Myanmar is the world's largest producer of opium, the raw
material for heroin.
	   Various Shan leaders have through the years offered to destroy
the entire opium crop in exchange for cash and support for their
independence struggle from the United States government, which has
always refused the offer.
	   ``The drugs problem cannot be resolved without resolving the
ethnic conflict,'' Yawd Serk, commander of the Shan State Army, was
quoted as saying in Thursday's Bangkok Post newspaper.
	   The speed pills and heroin were seized from dealers from the
Kachin, another ethnic group, Shan fighters said.
	   Several ethnic groups have used money from drug trafficking to
fund their insurgency movements.
	   Low-level Myanmar army officers in the border areas have also
been implicated in the trade.
	   While the leaders of Myanmar's military government have not been
implicated in drug trafficking, they have allowed former top
traffickers such as Khun Sa to live in Yangon and invest in
businesses there, leaving them open to charges of helping the
dealers launder their money.
	   The United States imposed economic sanctions on Myanmar in 1997
for the military government's repression against the democracy
movement but also for failing to fight the drug trade.
</TEXT>
