</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Nikko-Tokyo-Mitsubishi </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Nikko, Tokyo-Mitsubishi to negotiate tie-up
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ In a move likely to repair strained relations
between two Japanese financial giants, Nikko Securities Co. and the
Bank of Tokyo Mitsubishi Ltd. will start negotiating a broad
business tie-up early next year, a newspaper reported Thursday.
	   The news comes less than six months after Citigroup Inc., a
major U.S. financial services group, bought a quarter stake in
Nikko, pushing Tokyo-Mitsubishi out of the top shareholder
position.
	   Nikko's potential tie-up with Tokyo-Mitsubishi would cover the
sale of Mitsubishi group financial products such as mutual funds
via Nikko's extensive retail network, cooperation in the pension
asset management business and joint development of new financial
products, the Sankei Shimbun reported.
	   Because of the New Year's holidays, officials from both Nikko
and Tokyo-Mitsubishi were unavailable to confirm the report.
	   Tokyo-Mitsubishi has reportedly opposed the link between Nikko
and Citigroup, in which the firms will offer investment services to
corporate customers through their newly-formed securities company,
Nikko Salomon Smith Barney Ltd.
</TEXT>
